<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="1CO" stage="Final" version="D">
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">1 Korintus</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Sasuri Paulus ka èci<bt>Paul's first letter</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">hia dhèu parcaya ètu kota Korintus<bt>to the *believers in the city of Korintus</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">1 Korintus<bt>1 Korintus</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saloom<bt>Saloom [shalom greetings]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Sasuri ne nèti ja'a, Paulus. Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le ja'a, sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus Kristus. Sostenes hia miu lii maho'o kahèi.<bt>This letter is from me, Paulus. Father God has chosen me/selected me out (from a group of similar things) to be Yesus Kristus' *apostles/emissary (doublet-commissioned underling). Sostenes also sends greetings to you-pl.</bt><v n="2" />Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu dhèu parcaya Ama Lamatua ètu kota Korintus. Na hag'e nare le miu ho j'aj'i dhèu mola-mèci Nèngu, lula miu parcaya le Yesus Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji mema le karèi nèti uru ka ho Na mai. Ama Lamatua tao miu mola-mèci kahèi, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i ètu mia-mia. Te rèngu manèngi le sèna ka Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus soru-bara si. Nèngu ne j'aj'i Kètu mi dedha èdhi aa rèngu kahèi.<bt>I am writing this letter to you-pl believers of God in the city of Korintus. He has chosen you to be/become His clean/holy/pure (doublet) people, because you have believed in Yesus Kristus, whom God promised beforehand from long ago to send here. [NOTE: full long form explication here of "Christ"]. God also makes you be/become clean/holy/pure like all other believers wherever/everywhere. Cuz (elaboration) they have asked that our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus help (doublet) them. He (focused) is Head to us-inc and also to them.</bt><note reference="1:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:1; Yoel 2:32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ja'a manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama èdhi, Ama Lamatua, dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus. Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Rèngu pad'elo d'ara hua iia Ra mi miu, ho miu mamuri dame dènge mera-milu.<bt>I pray (doublet) to our Father God, and our Head, Yesus Kristus. I ask for Them to show Their goodness/grace/kindness/generosity to you, so that you can live in peace1 (relational), and peace2 (doublet-situational). [NOTE: I've done a fairly extensive word study on /eirene/ and find no lexical or contextual support for those who want to limit it to "inner peace" here. I wonder if their blindly following a tradition of limiting it to that sense that came in along with Freud. These 3 different lexical items in Kupang nicely reflect the 3 primary senses of /eirene/ (and /shalom/)--NOTE Dhao only reflects two of these senses naturally in a formulaic blessing without forcing it.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus manèngi makasi mi Lamatua lula dhèu Korintus<bt>Paulus gives thanks to God2 because of the Korintus people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Lod'o-lod'o ja'a ngee kèdhi miu, ja'a padhai lii dènge Lamatua ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Makasi ae-ae lula parcaya dhèu Korintus sèra!&gt;&gt; Te Lamatua dhu pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na mi miu, lula miu lèka taruu Yesus Kristus, dhu Lamatua pua Na mai.<bt>Each time I think of you, I speak with my God2, saying, &lt;&lt;Thank you so much for the *faith/belief of those Korintus people!&gt;&gt; Cuz (elaboration) God2 has shown His goodness/ grace/ kindness/ generosity to you, because you continue to believe2 in Yesus Kristus, whom God2 sent [short explication of “Christ”].</bt><v n="5" />Hèia Na hia miu a'èra, ka miu bisa pakako sasab'a-la'a aa'i-aa'i, lula miu pa'èki dènge Ne. Èèna ka dhu tao d'ara miu kaja-su'i dènge j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a. Nèti èèna ka miu me'a mèu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu hua iia risi, lula-nèti j'ara mamuri Nèngu. Miu me'a kahèi j'ara mia dhu be'a risi, ladhe miu lole mi dhèu lula-nèti Yesus Kristus.<bt>So He has given you strength/ability be able to carry out all kinds of work/ responsibilities (doublet), because you are bound/linked with Him. That has made your insides be/become rich with matters that are good. That is why you truly understand the things that are important about His life way. You also know which (of choices) is best if/when you tell/inform people about Yesus Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Tuu dai èèna ka"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 01:07:24Z" status="Anyone">Oleh karena itu</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />J'ara aa'i-aa'i ne'e ka dhu padelo, na, j'ara-j'ara dhu ji'i peka le dènge miu lula-nèti Kristus èèna, dhu amo le ètu d'ara miu. Nèti èèna ka, miu me'a tare'a-re'a, na, j'ara sèra lèke.<bt>All these things indicate that the things/matters which we-exc have told you-pl about Kristus, are rooted in your insides. That is why you are still sure/confident that those things are true. [NOTE to daughter translations: if /ba'akar/ doesn't work as rooted, consider an equivalent of /tatanam/ "planted in the heart" which works in several languages.]</bt><v n="7" />De miu abhu le j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu be'a, dhu Roh Lamatua pala-bagi hia dhèu unu Na. Kura boe ciki sa. Hèia miu tatae lod'o dhu bèli-camèd'a Lamatua bhoke ho pad'elo Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>So (consequently), you have gotten/ received every good thing, which the Spirit of God2 gives/divides out to His people. (You) are not lacking/short in anything. So you are waiting for that day, when later God2 will reveal/unveil showing our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, to all people. [EXEG: Even though it is the same Gk root, most commentators feel that Gk /xarismati/ is broader here than what we translate as /karunya/ in chaps 12-14 (see Ex. Summ., including the lexical renderings). The Gk word /pneuma/ is not a part of this, so watch out for noise from the English ‘spiritual gift’ since ‘from the Spirit’ is not part of the meaning of the Gk. In the broad context the point is these gifts/blessings come from God. That is the sense that they are spiritual and not material.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patalele "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 01:19:12Z" status="Anyone">(buka) secara jelas</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Kristus èèna ka dhu neo pa'èra miu sèna ka miu taha taruu, toke Na mai hari asa rai-haha ne. Dènge j'ara ne'e, miu manahu boe, aa abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa pèci sasala mi dedha miu.<bt>That Kristus is the one who is going to strengthen you to keep on enduring until He comes back to this world. In that way, you do not fall (morally, socially, spiritually), and there is nobody who can accuse you of doing wrong. [REF TRACKING: 'Lord Jesus Christ' redundant with v.7 --&gt; Pron.]</bt><v n="9" />Èdhi bisa parcaya Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua, lula ngaa dhu Nèngu peka, èèna ka dhu j'aj'i. Tatu Nèngu neo tao j'ara se aa'i-aa'i hia miu. Te Nèngu ka dhu bhoke j'ara, sèna ka miu bisa tadhe Ana Na, nuka Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus èèna.<bt>We-inc can believe/trust in God's Words, because what He says, that is what happens/comes into being. Surely He wants to do all these things for you-pl. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who opens the way for you to be able to know his Offspring well, that is our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Miu dhèu parcaya hud'i j'aj'i èci ku, aa baku mae-manyèla<bt>You-pl believers must be/become one/united; don't be split up/divided (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />A'ari dhu pasue! Ètu d'ara aa'i-aa'i se, ja'a padhai lii pake kolongara Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus. De ja'a manèngi tare'a-re'a, sèna ka miu loe ka nèti padhèto ètu d'ara lii padhai. Te ngaa miu hud'i tenge j'ara sèna ka mamuri d'ara èci, aa baku mae-manyèla. Miu hud'i pake ngangee madhera, ho me'a, na, miu neo d'ai too-lane dhu èci èèna ka di.<bt>Dear siblings! In this matter, I am speaking using the name/reputation of our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus. So (consequently), I ask with all earnestness for you to stop arguing. But make an effort so you-pl live one insides (in accord, harmony, same purpose), and don't split up/become divided (doublet). You must think long together (think through, examine implications, be wise), so that you understand that you are holding the same goals/purpose.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèto "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 01:34:06Z" status="Anyone">bakanjar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te abhu dhèu nèti isi èmu ana hèni èdhi Kloe dhu mai peka dènge ja'a, na, ètu talora miu abhu dhèu cahag'e dhu patao-palaha taruu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there are people/person from our older sister Kloe's household who have come and reported to me that some of you are arguing (doublet) continually.</bt><v n="12" />A'abhu ja'a sèmi ne'e: miu cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a re Paulus!&gt;&gt; Aa cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a re Apolos!&gt;&gt; Aa abhu kahèi dhu paka'uu, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a re Petrus!&gt;&gt;<bt>My meaning/intention is like this (=what I mean is this): some of you are saying, &lt;&lt;I am via Paulus!&gt;&gt; And some say, &lt;&lt;I am via Apolos!&gt;&gt; And there are still others who declare saying, &lt;&lt;I am via Petrus!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kefas&gt;&gt;. Kefas èèna, ngara leo nèti Petrus.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, &lt;&lt;Kefas&gt;&gt;. That Kefas, is Petrus' other name.</bt></note>Aa dhu leo hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, nanene dhoka Kristus di!&gt;&gt;<bt>Still others say, &lt;&lt;I here, listen/obey only to Kristus!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Miu pangee tasamia, ee? Dhèu unu Kristus bisa boe mae-manyèla. Do, miu pangee, na, ja'a ka dhu madhe pala miu ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha? Aad'o! Do, lod'o ra sarani miu, rèngu pake ngara ja'a, ho miu j'aj'i dhèu unu ja'a, do? Bisa boe, si?<bt>What is your thinking/understanding? // What are you thinking!? Kristus' people cannot be split up (doublet). Or, (perhaps) you are thinking, that it was me who died on the *cross (crossed wood) for you? No! Or, when they *baptised you, they used my name to bring you into becoming my person, or (what)? No way, right?</bt><v n="14" />Ja'a manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, te lod'o ja'a ètu èèna dènge miu, ja'a sarani boe dhèu ae. Dhu ja'a sarani ètu nèi dhoka Krispus dènge Gayus di.<bt>I give thanks to God, cuz (elaboration) when I was there (remote) with you-pl, I didn't baptize many people. Only just older brother Krispus and older brother Gayus.</bt><note reference="1:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:8, 19:29, Roma 16:23</note><v n="15" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, abhu boe dhèu dhu bisa peka na, &lt;&lt;Ra sarani ja'a pake ngara Paulus, ka ja'a j'aj'i dhèu unu Paulus.&gt;&gt;<bt>In that way, there is nobody who can say, &lt;&lt;They baptized me using Paulus' name, so I am Paulus' person.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="16" />(Ee, ja'a heka sanèd'e kèna. Ja'a sarani isi èmu Stefanus cahag'e kahèi. Te ngaa ja'a sanèd'e heka, abhu dhèu era dhu ja'a sarani, do aad'o.)<bt>(Ee, I just remembered. I also baptised some people in Stefanus' household. But I don't remember if there are any other people that I baptised, or not.)</bt><note reference="1:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 16:15</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te Kristus pua boe ja'a ho laku sarani dhèu. Kapua sasab'a ja'a, nuka peka-padhai dènge j'ara-j'ara lula-nèti Lii Lolo Be'a Na. Te ngaa ladhe ja'a lole mi dhèu, Nèngu d'èi boe ja'a peka mamèu ja'a, do, pad'elo j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai. Te ladhe ja'a padhai lii sèmi èèna, èèna pakura koasa nèti lii lolo mamadhe Kristus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Kristus did not order me to go *baptise people. My main job/responsibilities are to tell people about His *Good News. But if/when I am telling people like that, He doesn't like me to talk cleverly, or show/point out impressive (things). Cuz (elaboration) if I talk like that, it reduces the power/authority of the story about Kristus' death on the cross.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Koasa Kristus mai nèti Ama Lamatua<bt>Kristus power/authority comes from God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi peka-padhai lula-nèti mamadhe Kristus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha èèna, goa titu kèna. Te ngaa dhèu sèmi sèra, bèli-camèd'a cèri eele nèti Ama Lamatua. Aa te ngaa, bagi mi èdhi, mamadhe Kristus ne, sèna ka pad'elo koasa Lamatua ho patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi.<bt>There are people who think that everything that we-exc tell (doublet) about Kristus' death on the cross, is really stupid/dumb/ ignorant. But people of that sort, will later be separated off/cut off from God. Whereas for us-inc, Kristus' death, is to show God's power/authority to save/rescue us from our *sins/wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="19" />J'ara ne'e nuka sèmi dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya, suri tèke, peka na,<bt>That is like what God's spokesperson named Yesaya once wrote (previously), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua peka na,<bt>&lt;&lt;God says,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu re'a,<bt>&lt;Everything that clever/ knowledgeable people know/ understand,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a Ja'a pa'ele iie aa'i si,<bt>I will ruin/destroy it all,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka j'aj'i mi mèdha dhu dènge boe kab'ua.<bt>so that it becomes something that has no value/meaning.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Rupa-rupa mamèu rèngu,<bt>And whatever kinds of cleverness they have,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a Ja'a core eele aa'i si,<bt>I will throw it all away,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sèna ka j'aj'i mi mèdha dhu guna boe.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>so it becomes something which is useless.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 29:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Uru èèna, mema Lamatua padhai lii sèmi èèna ka. Te ngaa limuri ne, tasamia hari? Dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra, sèmi ngaa sa? Mese agama sèra, j'aj'i sèmi ngaa? Aa tuka tao lii langu sèra, tasa mera mia? Miu nanene sèku! Lamatua tao si nuka sèmi dhèu goa! Nèngu bete eele aa'i le mamèu dhu amo ètu d'ara kahadhu dhèu rai-haha ne, aa tao mamèu sèra nuka sèmi mèdha dhu dènge boe kab'ua.<bt>Formerly, God2 really did say that. But now, how is it? What has become of those wise/clever/ knowledgeable people? What has become of those teachers of religion? What has become of those habitual litigators/ disputers/debaters? Listen up! God2 has made them (become) like stupid/dumb/ignorant people! He has pulled out (uprooted) all ideas/schemes which are rooted in the brains of humans, and made that cleverness as if they have no meaning/value whatsoever.</bt><note reference="1:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 12:17, Yesaya 19:12, 33:18, 44:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21-22" />Mamèu Ama Lamatua lènge aa'i mèu-mèu. Masi ka dhèu rai-haha ne pangee, na, rèngu d'èlu-mèu, te ngaa j'ara ngangee rèngu mesa ra d'ai mèka ho ra tadhe hua iia Ama Lamatua. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Lamatua pake le mamèu Na ho bhoke j'ara hia dhèu rai-haha. Te uru èèna, Lamatua pangee, peka na, &lt;&lt;Masi ka dhèu rai-haha pangee, na, dhèu pajuu-paleha Ja'a sèra goa, te ngaa tasamia èèna ka, hud'i Ja'a pua ku dhèu lasi lole dènge ra j'ara dhu lèke nèti Ja'a.&gt;&gt; Te Lamatua pua dhèu rèti lii padhai Na ho lasi lole dènge dhèu. Na pama'ète nare le neo pake lii moa èèna, sèna ka dhèu bisa parcaya Ne. Nèngu pake j'ara ne, ho patabuli dhèu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>God's cleverness is really incredible. Even though humans consider themselves clever, nevertheless their own ideas/schemes are not enough/sufficient for them to be able to truly know God. Even though that is the case, nevertheless God2 has used His cleverness to open the way for humans. Cuz (elaboration) formerly, God2 had thought, that, &lt;&lt;Even though humans think/consider My emissaries (doublet) to just be stupid people, nevertheless, regardless, I must commission/send people to go tell them things that are true about Me.&gt;&gt; Cuz (elaboration) God2 has sent His spokespeople to speak (His message) to people. He had decided to use that message/instructions, so people could believe in Him. He use that way/means to save/rescue people from their wrongs (doublet). [CHECK lènge].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lènge "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 03:07:16Z" status="Anyone">risi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dhèu rai-haha ne pangee, na, j'ara Ama Lamatua ne, goa. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu pusi-pahae boe dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. Te dhèu Yahudi neo manèngi dhoka tadha-tadha malaa di, sèna ka bisa rèdhi koasa Lamatua. Aa dhèu Yunani neo nanene dhoka j'ara-j'ara hua iia dhu maso asa d'ara kahadhu ra, madhutu ngangee rèngu mesa ra.<bt>But humans viewed that way of God2's as stupid. That is why they didn't want to pay any attention (doublet) to His emissaries (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) the Yahudi people only just wanted to ask for various *miracles/amazing signs, so they could see God2's power. And the Yunani people only want to hear clever things that make sense to them, according to their own thinking. [EXEG: playing on particular cultural stereotype associated with the Greeks here, so not taken as 'gentiles'; Note: NLT connects this verse nicely with context as above.]</bt><v n="23" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa èdhi dhu j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua lati peka dènge dhèu, na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua pua le Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Nèngu pajaji mema karèi nèti uru ka, mai asa rai-haha ne. Ka dhèu leo paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.&gt;&gt; Ropa dhèu Yahudi tadèngi lii lolo ne'e, rèngu sisu, te madhutu a'abhu ra, Dhèu dhu Lamatua neo pua mai èèna, bisa boe madhe sèmi èèna. Ropa dhèu Yunani tadèngi lii lolo ne, ra pangee na, &lt;&lt;Lii lolo dhèu goa!&gt;&gt;<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless we-exc who are God2's apostles/emissaries, go around telling people, that, &lt;&lt;God2 sent Kristus, the Person whom He promised beforehand from long ago to send here to earth. Then other people nailed Him to death on a/the cross.&gt;&gt; When Yahudi people hear that story, they just want to reject it (out of hand), cuz (elaboration) according to their thinking/opinion, that Person whom God2 is going to send, can not die like that. When the Yunani people hear that story, they think, &lt;&lt;What a stupid story!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sisu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 03:25:10Z" status="Anyone">lawan, menentang</Message></Annotation><v n="24" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Na. Rèngu sèra cahag'e nèti dhèu Yahudi, aa cahag'e nèti dhèu Yahudi boe. Madhutu a'abhu rèngu, mamadhe Kristus dhu pad'elo le mi rèngu, na, koasa Ama Lamatua dènge boe too-lane, aa mamèu Na risi aa'i mèu-mèu.<bt>But there are people who God has chosen beforehand to be/become His possession. Some of them are from the Yahudi people, and some are from non Yahudi people. According to their thinking/opinion, Kristus' death has already shown/revealed to them that God2's power/authority is really without limit/boundary, and His cleverness is really incredible.</bt><v n="25" />Masi ka dhèu rai-haha pangee, na, j'ara Lamatua ne unu dhèu goa, te ngaa Nèngu mèu risi eele rèngu. Aa masi ka ra pangee, na, Lamatua dènge boe koasa, te ngaa koasa Na dedha risi eele nèti rèngu.<bt>Even though humans view/consider that way of God2's to be stupid, nevertheless He is still more clever/wise than they. And even though they think/assume God2 has no power/authority whatever, nevertheless His power/authority is still greater2 than theirs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />A'ari pasue! Sèna ka miu bisa me'a mèu lii padhai ja'a ne, sanèd'e mamuri miu, lod'o Lamatua hag'e nare miu, ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Na. Madhutu a'abhu dhèu rai-haha, ètu talora aae miu, abhu boe dhèu ae dhu d'èlu-mèu, abhu boe dhèu ae dhu dènge pangaru kapai, aa abhu boe dhèu ae dhu a'ari ra dhu dènge kolongara kapai.<bt>Dear siblings! So that you-pl can understand what I am saying here, remember your life/situation, when God2 chose you to become His possession. According to human assessment/evaluation/judgement, in your midst there are not many people who are clever, there are not many people of great influence, and there are not many people from families who have important name/reputations.</bt><v n="27" />Te ngaa Lamatua hag'e nare dhèu dhu madhutu ngangee dhèu rai-haha, na, tabhènga ana liku, sèna ka pamakae dhèu dhu pangee, na, rèngu d'èlu-mèu. Aa Na hag'e nare dhèu dhu madhutu dhèu rai-haha, dhèu dhu dènge boe koasa, sèna ka pamakae dhèu dhu pangee, na, rèngu dènge koasa.<bt>But God2 chooses to use people whom humans view/consider to be the most stupid/ignorant (idiom), to shame people who consider themselves to be clever/smart. And He also chooses to use people whom humans view/consider to have no power/authority whatever, to shame people who consider themselves to have power/authority.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabhènga ana liku: Sangat bodoh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z">tabhènga ana liku: Sangat bodoh</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabhènga ana liku,"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 03:34:53Z" status="Anyone">sangat bodo; bodo kerbau</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Hèia Na hag'e nare dhèu haha dhu dènge boe kolongara, aa dhu biasa dhèu pahaha si. Te Lamatua neo pake si, sèna ka dhèu dhu pangee, na, rèngu dhèu kapai, j'aj'i sèmi dhèu dènge boe pangaru ngaa-ngaa.<bt>So, He chooses small/insignificant people who have no name/reputation and who humans like to look down on/belittle them. Cuz (elaboration) God2 wants to use them to make people who consider themselves impressive/great/incredible, to become like they have no more significance/meaning. [NOTE: reordered for local worldview]</bt><v n="29" />Dènge j'ara èèna, bèli-camèd'a abhu boe dhèu èci sa dhu bisa tèb'a kakara ètu madha Ama Lamatua, peka na, nèngu dhèu kapai.<bt>In that way, later there will not be even one person who can beat his chest before God, saying that he is a great person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Te Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu bhoke pataleo j'ara, sèna ka miu bisa maso j'aj'i dhèu unu Kristus. Lamatua ka pake Yesus j'aj'i Dhèu dhu pala-bagi mamèu Na mi dedha èdhi. Yesus èèna ka dhu oti j'ara ho èdhi bisa padame dènge Ama Lamatua. Yesus èèna ka dhu tao èdhi ho bisa mamuri mola dènge mèci. Aa Nèngu ka dhu patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God himself is the one who opened the way (wide open) so you-pl could enter becoming Kristus' people. God2 is the one who made Yesus be the Person who divides/distributes out His cleverness/wisdom to us-inc. That Yesus is the one who opened the way so we-inc could be have a right relationship (make peace after relationship is damaged) with God. That Yesus is the one who makes us able to live straight (righteous) and clean/holy/pure. And He is the one who has freed/rescued us-inc from the power of sin.</bt><v n="31" />Èèna nuka sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>That is like what has been written in God's Holy Writings, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu d'èi pakapai kolongara dhèu,<bt>&lt;&lt;Whoever likes to boast/lift honour the name/reputation of a person,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">be'a risi pakapai kolongara Lamatua èdhi.<bt>it would be better if they boast/honour the name/reputation of our-inc Lord.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku pakapai iisi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't/They shouldn't elevate/boast/praise themselves!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 9:24</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èdhi hud'i lole paled'a-led'a ku mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i, mamadhe Lamatua Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha<bt>We-inc must tell clearly/openly to everybody (about) the Lord Yesus' death on the cross</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Uru èèna, lod'o ja'a dhiu asa miu, ja'a bhoke paled'a j'ara-j'ara Lamatua dhu uru èèna dhèu rai-haha ne re'a mèka. Te ngaa ja'a kèti boe lii sèra ho padedha iisi. Aa ja'a padhai boe pake lii dhu carui, sèna ka pad'elo mamèu ja'a unu ku.<bt>Dear siblings! Previously, when I came to/visited you-pl, I opened/revealed/explaining clearly to you God2's ways/things, which humans previously did not understand. But I didn't bring those words to elevate myself. And I also didn't use high/difficult language to show (off) my own cleverness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paled'a"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 04:02:28Z" status="Anyone">1) clearly, 2) lighten a heavily laden boat, so it floats</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Lod'o ja'a bera-bera dènge miu, ja'a pangee sèmi ne'e ka: ja'a pad'elo dhoka ca j'ara di, nuka Yesus Kristus. Nèngu ne, Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua pajaji mema karèi nèti uru ka, ho hia mai. Te ngaa ropa Yesus mai, dhèu paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Dhoka j'ara ne'e di, dhu ja'a ke'a mèu.<bt>When I was together with you, I was thinking like this: I only wanted to show/make known just one thing, that is Yesus Kristus. He is the Person whom God promised beforehand from long ago to send coming (serial verb construction). But when Yesus came, people nailed Him to death on the cross. Only just that thing, is what I know clearly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Uru èèna, lod'o ja'a bera-bera dènge miu, ja'a rasa mamèu ja'a d'ai boe, aa ja'a madha'u ka isi karèbha.<bt>Previously, when I was together with you, I felt my cleverness/intelligence was not sufficient, and I was also fearful to the point of shaking/trembling (from cold, sickness, fear, or anxiety).</bt><note reference="2:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:9</note><v n="4" />J'ara lii padhai ja'a, aa ngaa dhu ja'a lole, mud'a di. Te ja'a ko'o boe pake lii dhu karisi sèna ka pamako miu. Aad'o! Te ngaa ropa ja'a peka-padhai, na, lii padhai ja'a j'aj'i led'a, lula Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci ka dhu ator ja'a, aa koasa Na sab'a ètu ja'a kahèi.<bt>My way of speaking, and what I told, were just simple. Cuz (elaboration) I didn't try to use words which were excessive/over the top/fancier than necessary, to persuade/cajole you. No! But when I was speaking, it was clear because God2's *Holy Spirit was overseeing/regulating/controlling me, and His power/authority was also in/at me (=I had it).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bab'a iiki"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-02-25 04:15:39Z" status="Anyone">sangat pendek</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ja'a pangee, na, be'a boe ladhe miu parcaya Ama Lamatua, lula miu nanene lii padhai dhèu d'èlu-mèu di. Dhu be'a risi, ladhe miu parcaya Lamatua, lula Na pad'elo koasa Na mi dedha miu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I thought, it's not good if you believe in God, just because you heard a person's clever words. It would be better if you believe in God2, because He is showing/demonstrating His power/authority to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua aj'a-nori èdhi j'ara-j'ara mamèu dhu lèke<bt>God teaches (doublet) us-inc about things/matters that are truly clever</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Aa te ngaa, ladhe ji'i padhai lii dènge dhèu dhu parcaya èra le, ji'i aj'a rèngu pake lii padhai dhu dhèu bisa re'a mèu. Te ngaa dhu re'a mèu èèna, madhutu boe ngangee dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, do, madhutu ngaa dhu dhèu paredha sèra aj'a limuri ne. Te sèra sa, bèli-camèd'a ele iie aa'i si.<bt>Whereas, when we-exc were speaking with people whose belief was already strong, we taught them using words that they could understand clearly. But what they understood clearly, was not according to human's in this world's thinking, or according to people who are in positions of authority/government teach nowadays. Cuz (elaboration) those will later completely disappear/vanish. [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK referent of "those" in last sentence; people?/teachings?]</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa ji'i aj'a dhoka j'ara mamèu dhu mai nèti Ama Lamatua. Lula uru-uru sèra, lod'o rai-haha j'aj'i mèka, Lamatua pahuni j'ara sèra. Te ngaa limuri ne, Nèngu pama'ète le, sèna ka neo bhoke patalele lii pahuni èèna hia èdhi, ho èdhi kahèi abhu pala ètu d'ara kolongara Na dhu kapai risi eele.<bt>But we only taught clever things which come from God. because long ago, before the world came into being, God2 had hidden those things. But now, He has decided to reveal/unveil those secrets to us-inc, so that we-inc can also take part/have a share in His great/incredible name/reputation. [EXEG: CR, Ex.Summ. Tagbanwa BT]</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu paredha limuri ne, re'a mèu iia boe mamèu Lamatua. Te ladhe re'a tare'a, tatu ra paku pamadhe boe Kètu èdhi dhu dedha risi èèna, ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>But people who are now in authority/governing/ruling, they don't really understand God2's cleverness. Cuz (elaboration) if they understood, they would surely not have nailed to death that incredible Head of ours on the cross.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ètu d'ara sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua dhu suri lula-nèti rahasia Lamatua dhu uru èèna pahuni tèke, peka na,<bt>In the *Scriptures (God's Holy Writings) it is written about God2's secrets (loan) which used to be hidden, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Abhu j'ara dhu dhèu rai-haha dhae rèdhi mèka dènge musi madha ra,<bt>&lt;&lt;There are things that human eyeballs have never seen,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa abhu j'ara dhu dhèu rai-haha dhae tadèngi rèdhi mèka dènge ro'a dhilu ra,<bt>and there are matters that human earholes have never heard,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu dhèu rai-haha bisa ngee rèdhi boe.<bt>which humans cannot (possibly) comprehend (SVC=think about successfully).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa te ngaa, madhutu iia-iia na Lamatua sadia tèke le j'ara sèra aa'i-aa'i,<bt>However, in actual fact God2 has prepared beforehand all those things,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bagi mi dhèu dhu sue Nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>for people who love Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 64:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Uru èèna, mema dhèu re'a boe j'ara sèra, te ngaa limuri ne Ama Lamatua pake Roh Na ho bhoke paled'a hia èdhi.<bt>It is true that formerly, people did not understand those things, but now God has used His Spirit to unveil/reveal (them) clearly to us-inc.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Roh Lamatua èèna ne'a aa'i mèu-mèu. Te Nèngu parisa toke lutu d'ara iiki Lamatua kahèi.<bt>That Spirit of God understands all things. Cuz (elaboration) He also examines/investigates to the finest detail God2's innermost being (his small insides/conscience).</bt><v n="11" />Èdhi èci-èci ka dènge roh ètu d'ara èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi dhèu rai-haha, èci-èci ka dènge ngangee aa tatao na. Aa abhu boe dhèu leo èci sa dhu ne'a mèu d'ara iiki èdhi, dhoka roh èdhi unu ti dhu ne'a. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge Ama Lamatua. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa kahèi dhu ne'a d'ara iiki Lamatua. Dhoka Roh Nèngu mesa Na ka dhu ne'a mèu.<bt>Each of us-inc have our own spirits in our insides. That is why we humans (each) think and do/behave differently (individuated). And there is no other person who knows precisely our-inc innermost being, only our own spirits that know. It is the same way with God. There is not one single person who knows God2's innermost being. Only His own Spirit clearly knows. [NOTE to daughter translations: Consider collocations and naturalness between /cuma kotong pung roh sandiri sa/ vs. /cuma kotong sandiri sa/. The latter is more natural, the former maintains the higher level parallel with last sentence. Don't force the parallel if it doesn't work.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èdhi dhu sèmi tare le Roh Lamatua, ka Nèngu ka dhu ator èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi madhutu boe ngangee dhèu ètu rai-haha ne. Lula Roh Lamatua ètu d'ara èdhi, nèti èèna ka èdhi tadhe aa'i j'ara dhu be'a, dhu Nèngu tao le hia èdhi.<bt>We have received God2's Spirit, and He is the one who oversees/regulates/controls us. That is why we do not follow/do according to the thinking of people in this world. Because God2's Spirit is in our insides, that is why we can know/recognise all good things which He has done for us.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />J'ara sèra ka dhu èdhi tema padhue-padhai. Te ji'i lole j'ara-j'ara dhu Roh Lamatua aj'a-nori ji'i. Ka ji'i se aj'a boe pake lii dhu nèti mamèu madhutu a'abhu dhèu rai-haha. Te ngaa ji'i aj'a-nori pake lii dhu mai nèti Roh Lamatua mi dhèu dhu tadhe Nèngu.<bt>It is those things that we-inc often/normally talk about. Cuz (elaboration) we-exc tell/explain the things that God2's Spirit is teaching/has taught us-exc. So, we do not teach using words that are from cleverness according to human's thinking. But we teach using words from God2's Spirit, to/for people who know Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 00:55:25Z" status="Anyone">nèti here is bawa, not dari</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu tadhe boe Roh Lamatua, ropa na nanene lii padhai ji'i, nèngu d'èi boe sèmi. Lula nèngu ngee, na, &lt;&lt;Ngaa kèna? Maso boe d'ara kahadhu!&gt;&gt; Aa te ngaa, masi ka tasamia èèna ka, dhèu ne bisa boe ne'a j'ara sèra, te nèngu dhu mamuri pa'èki boe dènge Roh Lamatua.<bt>But if there is a person who does not know God2's Spirit, when he hears what we are saying, he is not going to receive/accept it. Because he is thinking, &lt;&lt;What's that? It doesn't make any sense (lit: doesn't enter the brain)!&gt;&gt; When in fact (background explanation), no matter what, that person cannot understand those things, cuz (reason/elaboration) he does not live bound/linked to God2's Spirit.</bt><v n="15" />Dhèu dhu mamuri pa'èki dènge Roh Lamatua, heka re'a j'ara sèra aa'i-aa'i, aa bisa re'a mia ka dhu lèke. Te ngaa dhèu leo pajiko rare boe ngangee dhèu sèmi sèra.<bt>People who live bound/linked to God2's Spirit, only.then can they understand all those things, and know which (of options) are true/right. But other people cannot successfully measure/evaluate the thinking of people like them.</bt><v n="16" />Bisa tasamia? Te abhu dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua, peka na:<bt>How could they? Cuz (elaboration) it is written in the Scriptures, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu bisa re'a ngangee Ama Lamatua?<bt>&lt;&lt;Who is it that is able to understand God's thinking?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Do, cee ka dhu bisa ator Lamatua,<bt>Or, who is it that can oversee/regulate/control God2,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho Ama Lamatua tao madhutu lii holo-nori dhèu èèna?<bt>so that God does according to that person's advice/instructions?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Abhu boe ca dhèu sa!&gt;&gt;<bt>There is not even one person!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 40:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Madhutu iia-iia na, èdhi te'a j'ara se'e, lula Kristus ka dhu soru-bara sèna ka èdhi bisa pangee madhutu ngangee Nèngu.<bt>In actual fact, we-inc can understand those things, because Kristus is helping (doublet) us so we can think according to His thinking.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu parcaya hud'i sab'a d'ara èci hia Lamatua, aa baku patao-palaha<bt>We-inc believers must work w/one insides (in harmony, same purpose) for God2, and not be arguing/disputing (doublet)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patao-palaha"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:13:09Z" status="Anyone">= paloa-padui (Lena sonde tahu)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Lod'o ja'a ètu èèna era, miu nuka sèmi dhèu dhu dhae pa'èki èra mèka dènge Roh Lamatua. Lula miu madhutu dhodhoka dad'èi d'ara miu dhoo-dhoo di, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu rai-haha dhu leo sèra. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a bisa boe padhai lii dènge miu, nuka sèmi padhai lii dènge dhèu ee'a, te miu nuka sèmi ana iiki sa.<bt>Dear siblings! When I was still there, you-pl were like people who were not yet bound/linked strongly with God2's Spirit. Because you only knew how to follow your own desires/passions, the same as other humans. That is why I could not speak with you-pl, as with adults/mature/fully developed, cuz (elaboration) you were just like little children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhoo-dhoo"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:17:28Z" status="Anyone">cuma ; dhoo (2-homonym) = kutuk</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu ee'a"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:19:20Z" status="Anyone">dewasa</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ja'a hud'i aj'a miu j'ara-j'ara dhu carui boe, lula miu bisa mèka sèmi mere j'ara dhu carui, nuka sèmi ana iiki dhu bisa mèka ra'a sisi. Miu hud'i kadhii ku, sama sèmi dhèu ee'a dhu tema ra'a sisi. Te ngaa limuri ne, miu nuka sèmi ana rara iisi hiu era, dhu me'a dhoka minu susu di.<bt>I had to teach you about things that are not difficult/insignificant things, because you were not yet ready to receive/accept difficult/complex/significant things, just like small children who cannot yet eat meat. You should be strong, like an adult who often/normally eats meat. But now you are still like infants who only know how to drink milk.</bt><note reference="3:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ibrani 5:12-13</note><v n="3" />Lula ngangee miu cakaraa dhèu dhu neo dhoka madhutu dad'èi d'ara di. Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu risi nèti miu, miu tèka d'ara aa patao-palaha leli! Nèti èèna ka, ja'a peka na, miu me'a dhoka madhutu dad'èi miu dhoo-dhoo. De sèmi èèna na, miu sama sèmi dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Because your thinking like people who only know how to follow their own desires/passions. If there is someone who is more/greater (physical, social, spiritual) than you, you are jealous/vengeful, and argue/dispute pointlessly! That is why I said you only know how to follow your own desires/passions. So (consequently), you are merely like other humans in this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu risi nèti miu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:31:02Z" status="Anyone">lènge = lebih (not used yet) has sense of paling</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Lula miu cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, re Paulus!&gt;&gt; Aa cahag'e dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, re Apolos!&gt;&gt; Lod'o-lod'o miu padhai lii sèmi èèna, miu pad'elo, na, miu èci èèna ka dènge dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Because, some of you are saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am via Paulus!&gt;&gt; And there are some who say, &lt;&lt;I here, am via Apolos!&gt;&gt; Each time you talk like that, you are showing/demonstrating that you are just the same as other humans.</bt><note reference="3:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 1:12</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Miu nuka sèmi oka<bt>You are like a garden</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Madhutu iia-iia na, Apolos èèna, cee? Aa ja'a, Paulus ne, cee? Te ji'i dua mi se, dhoka ana pua-paleha di. Ji'i dhoka pad'elo j'ara ho miu bisa parcaya Kristus. Apolos pakako sasab'a madhutu paredha Kètu èdhi. Aa ja'a sèmi èèna kahèi!<bt>Whereas is fact, that Apolos, who is he? And I, Paulus here, who am I? Cuz (elaboration) the two of us-exc, are only *servants (people who are ordered around). We merely/only showed the way so you-pl could believe in Kristus. Apolos carried out his work/responsibilities, following/obeying the orders of our Head. And I also did like that too!</bt><v n="6" />Ja'a ka dhu uru tèka lole dènge miu lula-nèti Kristus. Èèna nuka sèmi ja'a ka dhu sèle hini. Hèia Apolos mai aj'a-nori miu. Èèna nuka sèmi nèngu ka dhu bui-tatee hini dhu ja'a sèle kore sèra. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua ka dhu tao hini sèra muri j'aj'i kapai aae.<bt>I am the very first one who told you about Kristus. That is like I am the one who planted the seed(s). Then, Apolos came and taught (doublet) you. That is like he is the one who watered/cultivated (doublet) those seeds that I had planted. But God is the one who made those seeds grow until they were big.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bui-tatee"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:36:57Z" status="Anyone">siram</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:4-11, 24-28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />De dhèu dhu sèle hini sèra dènge boe kab'ua. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu bui. Dhodhoka èci di dhu dènge kab'ua, nuka Ama Lamatua. Lula Nèngu ka tao hini sèra muri, ka sub'u dènge sega.<bt>So (consequently), people who plant seeds have no value/meaning/ significance. And it is the same with those who water. Only one thing has value/meaning/significance, that is God. Because He is the one who makes those seeds grow and flourish (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sega"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:40:08Z" status="Anyone">flourish (plants)</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Dhèu dhu sèle, aa dhèu dhu bui-tatee, sab'a sama-sama, te sasab'a rèngu èci èèna ka. Aa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pakako sasab'a Lamatua, bèli-camèd'a Na b'ae rui-j'aj'èra ra.<bt>The person who plants, and the person who waters (doublet), they work together, cuz (elaboration) their work is one/the same. And, everyone who carries out God2's work, He will repay/reward their efforts (idiom: bone-suffering).</bt><v n="9a" />Te ji'i sama-sama dhèu sab'a nèti Lamatua. Aa miu nuka sèmi oka Lamatua, dhu Nèngu neo uri.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) we-exc together are God2's workers. And you-pl are like God2's field/garden which He is (wanting to/going to) cultivating.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Miu nuka sèmi èmu<bt>You are like a house</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9b" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, miu nuka sèmi èmu dhu Ama Lamatua patitu.<bt>In the same way, you are like a house which God builds.</bt><v n="10" />De Lamatua pad'elo le d'ara hua iia Na mi ja'a. Nèti èèna ka ja'a sama sèmi dholu. Ka Lamatua soru-bara ja'a ho ke'a mèu j'ara-j'ara nèti kapua, sèna ka ja'a tao era padhèdi dhu èra ètu d'ara mamuri miu. Hèia dhèu leo aj'a-nori miu kahèi, ho rèngu patitu mi era padhèdi dhu ja'a tao kore èèna. Te ngaa tuka èci-èci hud'i sab'a ku dènge d'ara kateme, ho rèngu patitu èmu dhu èra.<bt>Now [+discourse, not time], God2 has shown/demonstrated His goodness/ grace/kindness/generostiy to me. That is why I am like a master craftsman/construction supervisor. And God2 helped (doublet) me so I knew/understood things from the beginning, so I built a strong foundation in your lives. So/then other people also teach you, so that they are building on top of that foundation which I have (successfully-implied by SVC) made. But each craftsman/builder must work wholeheartedly/carefully to build a strong/enduring house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dholu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 01:55:30Z" status="Anyone">kepala tukang</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Era padhèdi dhu èra èèna, abhu le. Nuka Yesus Kristus. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu leo bisa boe tao era padhèdi leo ètu d'ara miu, te Lamatua dhu tao tèke le era padhèdi dhu lèke.<bt>The strong foundation is already there. That is Yesus Kristus. That is why nobody (else) can build a different foundation in your insides, cuz (elaboration/reason) God2 has already put in place/established the true foundation.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Tatu abhu dhèu dhu neo patitu kahèi ètu era padhèdi èèna pake rupa-rupa nèu. Abhu dhu neo pake nèu dhu kab'ua, sèmi hualaa, doi pudhi do hadhu kale'e. Abhu dhu pake nèu biasa, nuka sèmi aj'u, j'u'u do rèu hidhu.<bt>Surely there are people who also want to build on that foundation using various kinds of materials. There are those who want to use valuable materials such as gold, silver, or precious/shiny stones. There are those who want to use common material such as wood, grass, or alang-alang (long kunai grass).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 02:08:00Z" status="Anyone">bahan bangunan</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Te ngaa sasab'a tuka èci-èci ka bisa te'a, aa dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra bisa re'a sasab'a rèngu èèna, be'a do aad'o. Te lod'o èle rai-haha, Lamatua neo sèku ne, sama sèmi Na pake ai ho pad'elo, na, sasab'a dhèu sèra, bisa taha do aad'o.<bt>But each craftsman/builder's work will become clear/obvious/visible, and everyone will be able to know that work of his, (whether it is) good or not. Cuz (elaboration) at the end of the world, God2 wants to test him (test character, work), like He uses fire to show whether each person's work endures/lasts, or not.</bt><v n="14" />Ladhe uji nare sasab'a nèti ca dhèu pake ai, aa nèu dhu na pake bisa taha, bèli-camèd'a Lamatua b'ae rui-j'aj'èra na ètu sorga.<bt>If/When a person's work has been tested2 using fire, and the material he used still endures/lasts, God2 will pay his reward (doublet) in heaven.</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa ladhe uji nare sasab'a dhèu pake ai, aa ai na'e aa'i nèu dhu nèngu pake patitu ètu era padhèdi èèna, na, Lamatua hia boe dhèu ne ngaa-ngaa. Te ngaa tuka ne abhu mamuri era, masi ka sèmi dhèu dhu rai kalua nèti d'ara èmu ai na'e.<bt>But if a person's work has been tested2 using fire, and the fire consumes that material which he used to build on the foundation, na, God2 will not give that person anything. But that craftsman will/can still get life/salvation, even though it is like a person who flees from a house that is burning down. (implied: nearly dying).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Miu sama sèmi èmu sabaj'a unu Lamatua<bt>You-pl are like God's worship house</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Miu hud'i me'a ku, dhu peka na, miu sama sèmi èmu sabaj'a Lamatua, aa Roh Na dhu pea ètu d'ara.<bt>You-pl must understand, that you are like one of God's *worship houses, and His Spirit is also living inside.</bt><note reference="3:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 6:19, 2 Korintus 6:16</note><v n="17" />Aa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pa'ele iie èmu sabaj'a Lamatua, nuka era pea Na, na mage-mage! Bèli-camèd'a Lamatua pa'ele iie ne kahèi! Te èmu sabaj'a Lamatua èèna mola-mèci. De miu hud'i mola-mèci ku kahèi.<bt>And if there is a person who ruins/defiles/damages God2's house of worship, that is that place where He is living, na, watch out/careful! God2 will also ruin/defile/damage him! Cuz (elaboration) God2's house of worship is clean/holy/pure (doublet). That is why you-pl must also be holy (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Miu baku tipu ngi'u miu unu mi! Ladhe abhu ca dhèu dhu pangee, na, nèngu d'èlu-mèu aa ne'a aa'i madhutu mamèu dhèu ètu rai-haha lod'o limuri ne, èèna peka na, nèngu ne'a boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa. Ladhe èu mase'a le, peka na, èu me'a boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa, heka èu mulai me'a kèna.<bt>You should not deceive yourselves! If a person considers him/herself to be clever/wise, and understand everything according to the understanding of the people in the world nowadays, it is clear that you don't understand anything. If you are aware that you don't understand anything, only.then can you begin to learn/understand.</bt><v n="19" />Ngangee dhèu ètu rai-haha taa limuri ne, Ama Lamatua peka na, goa. Te ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci dhu suri tèke, peka na:<bt>The thinking of people in the world nowadays, God considers/views that as stupid/ignorant. Cuz (elaboration) in the Scriptures it is written, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, nèngu d'èlu-mèu,<bt>&lt;&lt;There are people who consider themselves as clever,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa èèna na Lamatua pake hari ngangee na dhu karehe sèra,<bt>but God2 will use their own dirty/defiled schemes/thinking,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">j'aj'i mi sasii, ho sii pa'ele iie hari nèngu!&gt;&gt;<bt>as snares to trap them back to destruction/ruin!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasii"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 03:12:11Z" status="Anyone">jerat, perangkap; gèso 1 = manis tinggi (teh, kopi) ; 2 = kuah santan</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ayub 5:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ètu era leo dhu suri kahèi, peka na,<bt>In another place it is also written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua èdhi dhu ne'a le ngaa dhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra pangee,<bt>&lt;&lt;Our-inc Lord already knows what it is that the clever people are thinking,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa dhèu dhu hud'i re'a ku neo tao ne tasa mere mia,<bt>and people who should know what to do,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu dhu ne'a nare le, na, rèngu dhoka ngee iia d'ara di.&gt;&gt;<bt>He already knows the things they are thinking are futile/pointless/in vain.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="3:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 94:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21-22" />De miu baku padedha dhèu èci sa, dhu peka na, nèngu èèna lènge aa'i dhèu. Te Lamatua ka dhu ded'e dhèu, ho ator miu. Aa'i-aa'i sèra j'aj'i le unu miu. De dhèu dhu ator miu sèra, sama sèmi: ja'a, Apolos, dènge Petrus,<bt>So (consequently), you should not lift up/praise/boast about someone, saying, he is superior to everyone. Cuz (elaboration) God2 is the one who elevates/appoints people to lead/manage you-pl. Every(thing/body) has already become your property/possession. So (consquently), people who lead/manage you, such as: me, Apolos, and Petrus,</bt><note reference="3:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani, suri peka na, <span class="Italic">Kefas. </span>Kefas èèna, ngara leo nèti Petrus.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, <span class="Italic">Kefas</span>. Kefas is Petrus' other name.</bt></note>ji'i se j'aj'i unu miu. Aa aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne unu miu kahèi, masi ka miu mamuri do miu madhe, masi ka deo ne'e do lod'o dhu mai, aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i unu miu kateme aae.<bt>we-exc are your possession. And everything in this world is also your possession, whether you are alive or dead, whether now or later, everything has become your full possession. [NOTE: commentaries are all over the place on this. Fee says, "One wonders whether Paul himself had all this in mind when the sentence began....You do not belong to them; they belong to you, as your servants, because “you - and they - are Christ's, and Christ is God's.”" So, don't push your UNS's too hard on this one.]</bt><v n="23" />Aa miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Kristus. Aa Kristus unu Ama Lamatua!<bt>And you-pl are/have become Kristus' possession. And Kristus is God's possession!</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kristus pua dhèu pajuu-paleha Na lasi asa mia-mia<bt>Kristus' sends His emissaries/apostles to go all over the place</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />De miu baku koa-kad'iri ji'i, te ji'i dhoka ana pua-paleha Kristus di. Aa Ama Lamatua lèka ji'i, sèna ka j'aga paie-iie j'ara-j'ara dhu uru èèna pahuni tèke.<bt>[NOTE: higher level cohesion with 3:21-22.] So (consequently), you must not praise (doublet) us-exc, cuz (elaboration) we are merely Kristus' servants. And God trusts us to carefully guard/be responsible for the things that were previously hidden.</bt><v n="2" />Dhèu dhu madhenga mèdha-panyau lamatua na, nèngu hud'i j'aj'i ku dhèu dhu tao madhutu ngaa dhu lèke.<bt>A person who guards his master's possessions, he must be a person who does according to what is right/true.</bt><v n="3" />Tasamia dènge ja'a? Ja'a sab'e madhutu ngaa dhu lèke, do aad'o? Ja'a ko'o boe ke'a, miu nile ja'a tasa mera mia. Aa ja'a pusi-pahae boe kahèi dhèu leo nile ja'a sèmi ngaa sa. Ja'a ke'a boe nile ngi'u ja'a unu ku kahèi.<bt>How about me? Do I work according to what is right/true, or not? I don't want to know how you evaluate/ assess/judge me. And I also don't care (doublet) how other people assess me. I also don't care2 how I assess myself.</bt><v n="4" />Te masi ka d'ara iiki ja'a peka na, ja'a be'a le, tatu boe sasoa na, ja'a be'a. Dhu mèci ka, Lamatua ka dhu nile ja'a tasa mera mia.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) even if my small insides (conscience) tells me I am good, it is still not certain that it means I am good. What IS important, is how God2 assesses me.</bt><v n="5" />De miu baku tao ngi'u sèmi dhèu pama'ète lii langu ho nile dhèu leo sèra. Mate mamai hari Lamatua, te Nèngu ka dhu èèna na bhoke patalele aa'i mèu-mèu. Nèngu ka pasabhoka aa'i bhabhelu-katub'a dhu dhèu tao pahuni ètu d'ara maroga. Nèngu neo bhoke paled'a j'ara-j'ara dhu dhèu ngee ètu d'ara ra. Hèia Ama Lamatua neo peka aa'i j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a, dhu dhèu tao le.<bt>So (consequently), you-pl should not be making yourselves out to be judges to assess other people. Wait for the Master to come back, cuz (elaboration) He is the one who will open/ reveal/ unveil everything. He is the one who pulls out the evil things that people have hidden in the dark. He is going to unveil the things that people think in their insides. So God is going to tell/make known the good things which people have done.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Ja'a dhu padhai lii lula-nèti ja'a dènge Apolos, nuka sèmi ja'a j'aj'i mi conto ho miu bisa aj'a nèti ji'i, nuka: <span class="Italic">Tao madhutu j'ara-j'ara dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua. Baku tao dhu leo.</span> Ladhe miu madhutu ka j'ara se'e, miu baku bia re èci sa, aa padedha iisi lula madhutu ca dhèu, aa pahahe dhèu leo.<bt>Siblings! I am talking about myself and older brother Apolos, like I am giving an example (loan) so you can learn from us, like this: <span class="Italic">Just do according to the things that are written in God2's Holy Writings. Don't do differently.</span> If you do according to those things, you don't need to be partisan/favouring one party (over another), and talk big (boast) because (you) are following one (certain) person, and belittling/viewing desparagingly other people.</bt><v n="7" />De tasamia? Miu pangee, na, miu risi nèti dhèu leo, do? Baku! Te aa'i-aa'i dhu miu unu, miu abhu nèti Ama Lamatua. De ladhe sèmi èèna, nga tao ka miu nged'e ej'a ai, nuka sèmi miu ad'u-ue unu mi?<bt>So (consequently), how is it? You think you're better/more than other people, huh? Don't (do that)! Cuz (elaboration) everything that you possess, you obtained from God. So (consequently), if that is the case, why is it that you are proud/arrogant (idiom: lifting hands), like you yourselves are the ones who accomplished (doublet) it?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nged'e ej'a ai"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 03:45:14Z" status="Anyone">kepala besar (lit: ej'a ai = lift up hands (or feet))</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Nuka sèmi aa'i-aa'i dhu miu parluu, miu abhu le. Nuka sèmi miu kaja le! Miu tao ngi'u mi, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu kapai sama sèmi dhèu aae sa, aa ji'i soru-bara boe ciki sa. Madhutu iia-iia na, Lamatua ka dhu hia aa'i-aa'i dhu miu parluu. Te ngaa ladhe miu tare'a-re'a j'aj'i dhèu aae, ele boe ji'i ngèd'u paredha sama-sama dènge miu, si?<bt>It is as if everything that you need, you have already obtained/gotten. It's like you're already rich! You have made yourselves like big/important people, such as kings, and we-exc didn't help (doublet) in any way. Whereas in fact, God2 is the one who gave everything that you needed. But if later you really do become kings, perhaps we-exc could govern together with you-pl, right? [+facetious]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua-paleha ji'i, ho la'a asa mia-mia ètu rai-haha ne, sèna ka lole dènge dhèu j'ara-j'ara Kristus. Te ngaa ca tèka-ca tèka sa ja'a pangee, na, Lamatua pua ji'i titu re limuri tèka, sama sèmi ana bèdho dhu tatae abhu huku madhe. Hèia Na hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, aa dènge ana-ana pajuu Na ètu sorga mai laladhe ji'i.<bt>God has commissioned us to go all over this world, to tell people about Kristus. But once in awhile I think God2 has ordered us to stand at the very end (of the line, least importance), like prisoners who are waiting for their punishment of death. Then He lets/allows everyone on this earth, and His *angels (underlings in heaven), for them to view/watch (event/spectacle/TV) us-exc.</bt><v n="10" />Miu kapai titu kèna, nga! Te abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, miu d'èlu-mèu, lula pa'èki dènge Kristus. Te ngaa rèngu pangee, na, ji'i goa titu kèna, lula ji'i j'aj'i dhèu unu Kristus. Ele boe rèngu ngee, na, miu èra risi, aa ji'i se roe aala-aala. Ele boe ra ded'e miu padedha-dedha, te ngaa ro'o boe pusi-pahae ji'i ciki sa hèi. Seli-kolane, nga!<bt>You are so great/impressive/incredible, nga [+irony]! Cuz (elaboration) there are people who consider you-pl to be clever, because you are bound/linked to Kristus. But they consider us-exc to be most stupid/ignorant, because we are Kristus' people. Perhaps they think that you must be the strongest, and we are just weaklings. Perhaps they elevate/praise/honour you, but they don't even care/consider us at all. It's really too much!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roe nyab'e-nyab'e-roe aala-aala: noe talalu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z">roe nyab'e-nyab'e-roe aala-aala: noe talalu</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Toke d'ai deo ne'e, ji'i manganga dènge koko-kamango. Mèdha-papake ji'i kaha'i-kaheru. Dhèu loe boe game ji'i. Ji'i nuka sèmi dhèu dhu dènge boe era pea.<bt>Until now, we-exc have been hungry and thirsty. Our clothes are worn (doublet). People keep beating us. We are like people who have no homes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jara ponai"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 04:01:23Z" status="Anyone">kuda yg suka jalan, bapinda-bapinda, jalan sembarangan</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Ji'i sab'a dènge kacui-aai ji'i unu mi toke d'ai èi kabhèsu hae. Ladhe dhèu padhai-kakoli ji'i, ji'i dhoka b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i manèngi, sèna ka Ama Lamatua tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a hia miu.&gt;&gt; Ladhe dhèu paj'èra ji'i, na, ji'i b'ala boe, dhoka mau-mau di.<bt>We have worked hard (sweated) with our own hands. If someone says something (negative overtones) about us, we only respond saying, &lt;&lt;We-exc ask that God do various good things to you-pl.&gt;&gt; If/when people make trouble for us, na, we don't respond and are just silent. (put up with it).</bt><note reference="4:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:3</note><v n="13" />Ladhe dhèu padhai pa'ele iie kolongara ji'i, ji'i dhoka dhaa dènge rèhu mare di. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, ji'i se nuka sèmi kaj'alu do mamumu dhu core eele.<bt>If/when people slander our good name, we just choose to respond with a smile. Even that being the case, nevertheless people still consider/view us as waste/dregs/pulp, or filthy rubbish, which should be thrown out/discarded.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rèhu mare "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 04:13:08Z" status="Anyone">muka senyum</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mamumu "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-02 04:14:58Z" status="Anyone">sampah ; sota = ampas sota nyiu, sota lèngi</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Ibrani 11:38</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ja'a suri j'ara se'e, neo boe pamakae miu. Te ngaa ja'a neo pasanèd'e miu, lula ja'a sue miu nuka sèmi ana matana ja'a sa. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a peka dènge miu, ho lèpa asa j'ara dhu mola.<bt>I write these things, not to shame you. But I want to warn/admonish/reprimand you, because I love you like my own children. That is why I am telling you, so you can return to the straight/right path.</bt><v n="15" />Masi ka dhèu riho-riho dhu bisa pad'elo j'ara hia miu lula-nèti Kristus, te ngaa dhoka ja'a mesa ku dhu j'aj'i ama miu. Te ja'a ka dhèu uru j'ara dhu peka-padhai dènge miu Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Yesus Kristus. Nèti èèna ka, miu parcaya Ne. Ja'a tao j'ara èèna, lula ja'a dhu pa'èki mèno dènge Ne.<bt>Even if there were thousands of people who could show you the way about Kristus, nevertheless there is only myself who is your father. Cuz (elaboration), I here, was the first person who told you about Yesus Kristus' Good Story. That is why you came to believe in Him. I did that because I am bound/linked well/tightly with Him (=in Christ).</bt><v n="16" />De ja'a manèngi, sèna ka miu madhutu j'ara mamuri ja'a ne.<bt>So (consequently) I ask that you carefully follow the way I live my life.</bt><note reference="4:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 11:1, Pilipi 3:17</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Nèti èèna ka ja'a pua Timotius dhiu soru-bara miu. Ja'a sue ne, sama sèmi ana matana ja'a. Ja'a lèka ne, te nèngu kahèi mamuri pa'èki dènge Lamatua èdhi. Èèna na nèngu soru-bara miu ho pasanèd'e miu nèti mamuri ja'a. J'ara mamuri ja'a sèmi èèna, lula ja'a pa'èki dènge Yesus Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua hia mai. Èèna ka dhu ja'a aj'a-nori dènge dhèu sarani dhu pakaboko ètu mia-mia.<bt>That is why I sent Timotius to help (doublet) you. I love him like my own child. I trust him, cuz (elaboration) he also lives bound/linked with our-inc Master. He will help you to remember my way of life. My life was like that because I was bound with Yesus Kristus, whom God2 has sent. And that is also the same as what I taught to the Christians (baptised people) who gather in many places/everywhere/all over the place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Abhu nèti miu dhu pangee, na, ja'a lake kore boe dhiu dènge miu. Nèti èèna ka rèngu nged'e titu kèna.<bt>There are those among you who think, that, it will not work out for me to come there. That's why they have already become big-headed (proud, arrogant).</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa ladhe Lamatua èdhi d'èi, nèbhu boe ja'a d'ai kota Korintus. Ho èèna na ja'a ke'a mèu, na, dhèu sèra padhai lii padedha iisi, do, rèngu tare'a dènge koasa!<bt>But if our-inc Master wants, it won't be long before I arrive at the city of Korintus. So then I will know directly/truly, whether these people are only just elevating themselves, or, they really do have power/authority!</bt><v n="20" />Te Ama Lamatua èèna Dhèu Aae dhu unu koasa. Ka dhèu Nèngu hèb'a mènyi boe, ho pa'èra dhèu ètu d'ara lalèka ra, te ngaa rèngu pake koasa dhu lèke.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God is the King who has power/authority. So His people don't use oily mouths to strengthen people in their faith, but they use real power/authority.</bt><v n="21" />De dad'èi miu tasamia? Ladhe ja'a dhiu, na, ja'a tao lii sakaa aa huku miu? Do, ja'a dhiu pad'elo sasue dènge d'ara be'a?<bt>So (consequently), what do you-pl want to do? If I come, na, should I speak harshly and punish you? Or, should I come showing/demonstrating love and good insides (gracious/ gentle)?</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abhu dhèu ètu talora juma'at dhu ad'u j'ara karehe dènge dhèu bhèni<bt>There are people/person in the congregation who are doing bad ways with women (fooling around sexually)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a tadèngi, na, ca dhèu nèti juma'at miu dhu ad'u j'ara karehe dènge dhèu bhèni. Ngaa dhu nèngu ad'u-ue ne bhelu risi nèti dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua. Lula nèngu j'unu pa'èci dènge ina bhala na!<bt>I have heard that there is someone in your congregation who is doing bad ways with women. What he is doing is more evil than people who don't know God. Because he keeps sleeping united with his own stepmother! [EXEG: stepmother: see Ex. Summ. CEV, TEV]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ina bhala"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-04 00:40:08Z" status="Anyone">mama tiri</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 22:30</note><v n="2" />Te ngaa miu pamone-pabhèni, sèmi juma'at miu mola-mèci le! Te ngaa madhutu iia-iia na, miu hud'i makae ku, aa d'ara pèd'a. Dhèu sèmi èèna, babège eele ne pakaj'èu!<bt>But you-pl are so arrogant (doublet), as if your congregation is pure/holy (doublet)! The right thing, is that you should be ashamed, and troubled/distressed/upset. A person like that, you must evict him far (=complete separation)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Masi ka èdhi pakaj'èu èci dènge èci, te ngaa d'ara ja'a dhoka ètu miu di. De ja'a pama'ète kore le lii langu dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae èèna, nuka sèmi ja'a dhu ètu èèna le.<bt>Even though we-inc are mutually far from each other, nevertheless my insides are there among you. [NOTE: 1st sentence resonates with a well known proverb] So (consequently), I have already decided that person's case who is doing shameful things, just like I am right there with you.</bt><v n="4" />Ja'a dènge hak ho pama'ète sèmi èèna, lula Yesus j'aj'i Kètu èdhi, aa ja'a dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. De miu hud'i madhèdi pa'èci ku ho pama'ète lii langu èèna pake kolongara Kètu èdhi. Aa d'ara ja'a sama-sama dènge miu kahèi.<bt>I have the right to make a dicision like that, because Yesus is our-inc Head, and I here am His apostle/emissary. So (consequently) you must sit down together to make a decision on that case, using the name/reputation of our Head. And my insides will also be together with you.</bt><v n="5" />Hèia miu hud'i saraka dhèu ne asa dhèu aae nidhu, sèna ka nèbhu-nèbhu na core eele j'ara bhelu-katub'a nèti d'ara na. Sèna ka ladhe Kètu èdhi mai hari, na, Nèngu patabuli dhèu ne'e nèti koasa sasala-sasigo na.<bt>So/then you must turn over/give up that person to the king of the evil spirits, so that eventually that person will get rid of the evil things which are in his insides. So that later, when our-inc Head comes back, na, He can save/give life to/rescue that person from his wrongs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Be'a boe ladhe miu nged'e! Baku bhèlu, na, èdhi pakihu bibit roti ciki di ho bisa pakapai adonan aa'i-aa'i. Bibit roti, nuka sèmi bhabhelu dhèu. De ladhe soro tèke dhèu ad'u-ue bhabhelu ètu talora aae miu, bèli-camèd'a dhèu sarani leo sèra madhutu tao bhelu kahèi!<bt>It is not good if/when you-pl talk big (arrogant)! Don't forget that we mix just a little yeast (lit. bread seed) to make the whole dough (loan) rise. That yeast is like a person's evil. So (consequently), if (you) permit him to do evil in your midst, other Christians will also go along doing evil!</bt><note reference="5:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Galati 5:9</note><v n="7" />Babège eele dhèu bhelu èèna nèti juma'at miu, sèmi uru èèna dhèu Yahudi sèra core eele ragi aa'i-aa'i nèti èmu rèngu sèra ho neo ra'a kalela Paska. Dènge j'ara ne, miu bisa j'aj'i hari nuka sèmi dhèu dhu d'ara na abhu heka bhelu-katub'a. Miu hud'i j'aj'i ku sèmi èèna. Uru èèna, dhèu roro ana kahib'i-kalèbho sèna ka tao badha korban kalela Paska. D'ai limuri ku, rèngu pamadhe Dhèu Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, sèna ka j'aj'i korban dhu pamèu d'ara èdhi.<bt>Evict that evil person from your congregation just like long ago the Yahudi people (completely) got rid of all the yeast in their houses preparing to eat the Paska feast. In that way, you-pl will be able to again become like a person who has no evil in his insides. You must become like that. Formerly, they ritual slaughtered a lamb (sheep offspring) as an animal *sacrifice for the Paska (Passover, Easter) feast. Later on they killed God's Holy Person, to be a/the sacrifice which makes our insides clean/ holy.</bt><note reference="5:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:5</note><v n="8" />Uru èèna, dhèu Yahudi ra'a gee-j'ara nèti roti dhu pake boe ragi ètu d'ara lod'o kalela Paska. Limuri ne, èdhi nuka sèmi roti dhu pake boe ragi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi hud'i j'aga paie mamuri èdhi sèna ka baku tao ia ka j'ara-j'ara dhu bhelu, aa baku papèd'a d'ara dhèu leo. Èdhi hud'i padhai lii dhu lèke taruu. Hèia ropa dhèu ladhe rèdhi mamuri èdhi, ra peka na, tatao èdhi madhutu d'ara mola.<bt>Formerly, the Yahudi people ate the Paska feast using trail bread which didn't use yeast2. Now, we-inc are like that bread which doesn't use yeast. That is why we must guard our lives carfully to not do evil things, and not make other people angry/vengeful/upset. We-inc must keep saying what is true. So/then people will see our lives and say that our deeds/behaviour/character follows straight/true insides.</bt><note reference="5:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 13:7, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 16:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ca hari ni, ja'a suri kèdhi le sasuri dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku pa'èci dènge dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu nèngu boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Formerly, I once wrote, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't mix/get involved with people who do shameful things (sexually) with a person who is not their spouse.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />A'abhu ja'a ne peka boe, na, miu baku pa'èci dènge dhèu <span class="Italic">aa'i-aa'i</span> ètu rai-haha ne, dhu pusi-pahae boe Ama Lamatua, do dhèu manga'a, do dhèu kapod'e-kabèli dhu mana'u rare mèdha-panyau dhèu, do dènge dhèu sogo-tagu nidhu. Te ladhe sèmi èèna, miu hud'i tao iisi mi pakaj'èu nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>It is/was not my intention, that you shouldn't mix with <span class="Italic">everyone</span> in this world who doesn't care about God, or greedy people, or deceivers who trick people taking their things, or people involved in traditional worship. Cuz (elaboration) if (we did) like that, you would have to separate yourselves from everybody on this earth. [EXEG: Gk harpaks has 2 senses 1) swindler, 2) robber. Note KJV ‘extortioner’, NLT/AGNT/ NASB/NIV ‘swindlers’, CEV ‘who cheats’, TB ‘penipu’. This contrasts with TEV ‘thieves’ and NRSV ‘robbers’. For some odd reason LN only gives the second sense, which even the CEV overrides. BAGD gives both and says the first sense “perhaps better” captures the sense of the word. Now add to that the local Timor worldview, where most readers would say “I'm safe, cuz I'm not a robber.” Whereas as with ‘swindler’ there's more chance of evoking the desired response “Uh-oh. Touché. I'm in trouble.” (Keep in mind this foreshadows the truly good news in 1 Cor. 6: 9ff where these types “cannot inherit the kingdom of heaven, but such WERE some of you…”)]</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne nuka: miu baku pa'èci dènge dhèu dhu peka na, nèngu dhèu sarani, aa te ngaa nèngu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu nèngu boe, do dhu manga'a, do dhu sogo-tagu nidhu, do dhu pahahe kolongara dhèu, do dhu mahu, do dhu kapod'e mèdha-panyau dhèu. Èdhi baku pa'èci dènge dhèu sèmi sèra. Aa loe eele ka madhèdi mi'a-minu pa'èci dènge dhèu sèmi sèra!<bt>But what I am talking about is this: you should not mix with a person who says he is a Christian, whereas in fact, he is doing shameful things (sexually) with someone not his/her spouse, or he is greedy, or he is involved in traditional worship, or he is slandering/ belittling someone's name, or he is a drunkard, or he is deceiving to take someone else's things. We should not mix with people of that sort [recap for emphasis]. Don't sit and eat with them anymore [implies: if you do, you have no problem with their behaviour]!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loidoros: verbally abusive person methusos: drunkard|i(11)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">loidoros: verbally abusive person methusos: drunkard<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>sunesthiw: eat with someone LITERALLY: But now I write to you not to associate with anyone called a brother who practices sexual immorality, or is greedy, or an idolator, or verbally abusive, or a drunkard, or a swindler.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pae'a "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-04 01:19:30Z" status="Anyone">contact batin, ciptakan hubungan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Miu dènge hak ho lee mamuri dhèu sarani. Te ngaa ja'a dènge boe hak, sèna ka pama'ète lii langu dhèu dhu parcaya boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>You-pl have the right to read/assess the life of Christians. But I have no right to make decisions about the cases of people who don't believe in God.</bt><v n="13" />Te Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka bèli-camèd'a pama'ète hia dhèu dhu parcaya boe Ne. De miu baku bhèlu, ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua dhu suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu peka na, nèngu dhèu unu Lamatua, te ngaa loe boe tao bhabhelu, na, babège eele ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God himself will decide about people who don't believe in Him. So (consequently) you shouldn't forget that God2's Scriptures which write, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who refers to himself as being God2's person, but he keeps doing evil things, just evict him!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="5:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 13:5, 17:7, 19:19; 22:21,24; 24:7</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu parcaya baku pagalaa èci dènge èci ètu madha hakim<bt>Believers should not accuse each other before a/the judge (loan, signaling formal legal system)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Ladhe ca dhèu sarani pagalaa dènge a'ari na dhèu sarani, nga tao ka lami asa pengadilan ètu madha hakim dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua? Tasamia ka j'aj'i sèmi èèna? Be'a risi lami asa madha dhèu-dhèu parcaya, sèna ka rèngu uri lii langu miu!<bt>If one Christian has a dispute with a fellow Christian, why do you-pl go to court (loan) before judges who don't know God? How can it be like that? It would be better to go before the believers, so they can handle/settle your dispute!</bt><v n="2" />Nuka sèmi dhu dhae me'a mèka, peka na, dhèu-dhèu parcaya, bèli-camèd'a rèngu ka dhu pama'ète lii langu dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. De tasamia ka miu mesa mi bisa boe uri lii langu dhu ana iiki-iiki?<bt>It's as if you don't yet know that the believers are the ones who will decide the cases for every person on this earth. So (consequently), how is it that you are unable to handle/settle tiny little matters yourselves?</bt><v n="3" />Dhu mola-mola ka, ladhe bèli-camèd'a èdhi ka dhu uri lii langu ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga. De tatu hud'i miu ku dhu uri lii langu dhu bèli-bèli j'aj'i ètu talora aae miu.<bt>In actual fact, we-inc are the ones who in the future will decide the cases of God2's angels. So (consequently), surely you are the ones who must handle the daily disputes among yourselves.</bt><v n="4" />Risi-risi hari, ladhe miu dhèu parcaya pagalaa lula-nèti j'ara dhu ana iiki-iiki sèra, nga tao ka miu pake dhèu pama'ète lii dhu dhèu-dhèu sarani pakab'ua boe si?<bt>Furthermore, if you believers have a dispute about tiny little things, why is it that you use a judge whom Christians don't respect?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />De ja'a neo peka ca j'ara dhu pamakae miu. Sèmi ngaa? Nuka sèmi ètu talora aae miu abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu d'èlu-mèu uri lii langu dhu ana iiki-iiki sèra, sèmi lii langu dhu cèu nèti a'ari èdhi.<bt>So (consequently), I want to talk about a matter which should make you ashamed. How is that? It's like in your midst, there is not one person who is clever/wise enough to handle (these) tiny little matters, such as the disputes with arise/appear among our-inc siblings. [EXEG: Scholars are divided as to whether this parenthetical statement “I say this to your shame” refers to the preceding or the following statement (see Ex. Summ.). One scholar on Gk discourse (JEG) makes the comment “pròs entropeén hymíin: shame, humiliation. Could refer to what Paul already said, but more likely he is saying that now he wants to say something that will really shame them.”][NOTE to daughter translations: the ov transition into 5 with “Sakarang” seems too strong/abrupt, so I've softened it to “Naa,…” which signals a slightly softer shift. Many daughter lgs don't have an equivalent, but the MTTs usually have found a regular strategy where “Naa” occurs in the KM.]</bt><v n="6" />Te ngaa nèti talora miu abhu dhèu parcaya dhu ère nèti a'ari na dhèu parcaya asa madha dhèu pama'ète lii langu! Aa te ngaa dhèu pama'ète lii langu ne dhu parcaya boe Lamatua!<bt>But among you one believer is dragging off his sibling believer in front of a judge! Whereas in fact, that judge doesn't believe in God2!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Lèke boe, sina ma? Miu dhu segi boe le èèna, ladhe miu èci dènge èci lami pagalaa asa era pama'ète lii langu. Be'a risi, a'ari èu èèna soro tèke ne, ladhe na tao sala mi dedha èu. Aa ladhe a'ari èu dhèu parcaya mana'u nare mèdha-panyau èu, be'a risi hud'i laa nare!<bt>That is not right/true/correct, right? You-pl have already lost, if one of you goes to court with another. It would be better, to just let your-sg sibling be if he does wrong to you. And if your sibling believer is stealing your-sg things, it would be better/best to just let him take those things!</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa miu dhèu parcaya èci tao sala mi a'ari miu. Aa èci mana'u èci. Aa te ngaa miu sama-sama dhèu parcaya!<bt>But one of you believers is doing wrong to his sibling. And one is stealing from another. When in fact, you are both believers!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Miu nuka sèmi me'a boe j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i! Te dhèu dhu ro'o boe tao dhu lèke, tatu bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Mage soro tèke dhèu tipu miu, sèna ka miu ad'u-ue sasala! Dhèu dhu tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu nèngu boe, dhu sogo-tagu nidhu, dhu bersina, mone dhèu dua dhu pa'èci nuka sèmi dhèu èmu-kamali,<bt>It is as if you don't understand these matters! Cuz (elaboration) people who don't like to do what is right, will not be able to enter becoming God's people. Don't allow yourselves to be deceived, so that you do wrong! People who who do shameful ways with a person who is not their spouse (Gk pornoi), who are involved in traditional worship, who commit adultery (Gk moixoi), men who mutually sleep with men as a spouse [CHECK phrasing w/UNSs], [NOTE: last two combined in KM; EXEG: combination of Gk /malakoi/ and /arsenokoitai/ together are taken as passive and active members in homosexual intercourse; separately they could be taken as "effeminate" and "male prostitute", but not when the two terms occur together--BADG and a wealth of recent literature support this. Paul seems to be deliberately explicit--clearly the active member is wrong, but don't think those of you who participate passively are free from guilt, no!]</bt><v n="10" />dhèu mana'u, dhèu manga'a, dhèu rinu mahu, dhu padhai lii pakarehe kolongara dhèu, dhu pakapod'e ho rare mèdha-panyau dhèu, te dhèu aa'i-aa'i sèmi se'e se, tatu bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua!<bt>people who steal, those who are greedy, those who drink (until) drunk, those who slander other people's name/reputation, those who deceive to take other people's things, cuz (elaboration) every person of that sort cannot possibly be able to enter becoming God2's people/possession!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Mema, uru èèna miu cahag'e sèmi èèna kahèi! Te ngaa Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo miu, hèia pamèu miu. Aa Nèngu bhoke le j'ara kahèi, sèna ka miu bisa pabe'a hari dènge Ne. Na tao j'ara se'e, lula miu pa'èki dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, aa lula miu pa'èki dènge Roh Lamatua kahèi.<bt>It's true that formerly some of you really were like that also! But God has wiped away your wrongs to make you clean/holy/pure. And He has also opened the way so you could be in a mutually right relationship with Him again. He did all that, because you are bound/linked with our Head, Yesus Kristus, and because you are also bound/linked with God2's Spirit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe èu j'aga paie ngi'u èu, èu pakab'ua Lamatua<bt>If you take careful care of your body, that shows you respect/honour God2</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ja'a dènge hak sèna ka tao aa'i mèu-mèu. Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a neo tao sèra, tatu boe be'a hia ja'a. De masi ka ja'a dènge hak sèna ka tao aa'i mèu-mèu, te ngaa ja'a ko'o boe j'ara dhu karehe koasa nare ja'a.<bt>I have the right to do anything/everything. But everything that I want to do, it is not yet sure that it is good for me. So (consequently), even though I have the right to do anything/everything, nevertheless I don't want things that are bad/evil to hold power/authority over me.</bt><note reference="6:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 10:23</note><v n="13" />Conto sèmi, dhèu peka na, &lt;&lt;Nganga'a parluu kabake, aa kabake parluu nganga'a.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa sanèd'e, te bèli-camèd'a Lamatua palaho aa'i dua-dua ra. Conto dhu leo hari, èdhi bisa boe soro ngi'u èdhi sèna ka bisa tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu-kamali èdhi boe. Èdhi unu ngi'u ne, sèna ka sab'a hia Lamatua èdhi. Aa Lamatua èdhi ladhe-leru ngi'u èdhi.<bt>For example, someone said, &lt;&lt;Food is needed for the stomach, and the stomach needs/is needed for food.&gt;&gt; But remember [warning], cuz (elaboration) God2 will destroy both of them. Another example, we cannot surrender/turn over our bodies so that we could do shameful things with someone who is not our spouse. We got our bodies so we could work for our Master. And our Master is the one who looks after/ministers to our bodies.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="brwma: food, solid food koilia: stomach|i(13)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">brwma: food, solid food koilia: stomach<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>katargew: abolish, wipe out, do away with, put an end to, destroy swma: body<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>porneia: prostitution, unchastity, fornication, every kind of unlawful sexual intercourse LITERALLY: Food is for the stomach, and the stomach for food. But God will destroy both of them. The body is not for sexual immorality, but for the Lord, and the Lord is for the body.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ropa Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus madhe, Ama Lamatua ka pamamuri hari Ne. De ladhe èdhi madhe, Nèngu dènge koasa kahèi ho pamamuri hari èdhi.<bt>When our Head Yesus Kristus died, God brought Him back to life. So (consequently), when we die, He also has the power/authority to bring us back to life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ngi'u miu j'aj'i mi unu Kristus, nuka sèmi miu bagian nèti ngi'u Kristus. Tatu j'ara ne, miu me'a le! De ladhe ja'a pake bagian nèti ngi'u Kristus, ho laku pa'èci dènge ngi'u nèti bhèni kajeo, na tasamia? Baku sèmi èèna! Te èèna na lèke boe!<bt>Your-pl bodies are Kristus' possession, just as if you are a part of Kristus' body. Surely you already know that matter! So (consequently), if I use a part of Kristus' body, to go join/unite with the body of a prostitute/whore, how is that? Don't do it! Cuz (elaboration) it is not right/appropriate!</bt><v n="16" />Tatu miu me'a le, ladhe dhèu tao j'ara makae ho j'unu pa'èci dènge bhèni kajeo, na, dua-dua pakihu kee j'aj'i mi èci. Te dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Rèngu dua ra pa'èki le j'aj'i mi èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>Surely you already know, that if a person does shameful ways to sleep joined/united with a prostitute, the two of them are bound/linked2 (doublet) together as one. Cuz (elaboration) it is written in the Scriptures, saying, &lt;&lt;The two are bound together as one.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="6:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:24</note><v n="17" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu mamuri d'ara èci dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, j'aj'i le èci dènge Nèngu, sama sèmi dua ra dhu pa'èki ètu d'ara roh èci.<bt>But a person who lives one-insides (in accord, harmony) with our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, has become joined/united with Him, just like the two of them are bound/linked with the same spirit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ladhe èu abhu tebho tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu èu boe, na, rai pakaj'èu! Dhèu ad'u-ue sasala rupa-rupa dhu pa'ele iie rèngu unu ra, aa pa'ele iie dhèu leo kahèi. Te dhèu dhu karihu kaj'alu pa'ele iie ngi'u nèngu unu na.<bt>If you-sg have time/opportunity to do shameful ways with a person who is not your spouse, na, run far away (complete separation)! People do various sorts of wrongs that ruin/defile their own selves, and also ruin/defile other people as well. But a person who plays evilly/defiled (is sexually promiscuous), ruins/defiles his own body.</bt><v n="19" />Ngi'u èu èèna, nuka sèmi èmu sabaj'a Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Roh Nèngu èèna ka, dhu pea ètu d'ara miu, te Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka hia Roh Na mi dedha miu. Nèti èèna ka, miu dènge boe hak ciki sa hèi, ho j'aj'i lamatua dhu ator ngi'u miu unu mi. Te ngaa, nga tao ka miu mamuri sèmi pame'a boe sa dènge j'ara se'e?<bt>Your-sg body is like God2's Holy Spirit's house of worship. That Spirit of His, is the one who is living in your-pl insides, cuz (elaboration) God himself is the one who gave His Spirit to you-pl. That is why you do not have the right for just yourselves anymore to be boss/lord/master with say-so rights to manage/control each of your own bodies. But why is it that you are living as if you do not know this matter? [NLT]</bt><note reference="6:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 3:16, 2 Korintus 6:16</note><v n="20" />Kristus sui nare le miu dènge kab'ua titu kèna. De miu hud'i mamuri ku dènge pakab'ua ngi'u miu unu mi, ho pad'elo, na, miu pakab'ua Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>Kristus has *redeemed/bought back you at a high cost. So (consequently), you must live with respect for your own bodies, to show that you also respect/honour God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu èmu-kamali<bt>Spouses</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a neo suri j'ara-j'ara dhu miu pakarèi ètu d'ara sasuri miu èèna, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Dhu be'a ka, dhèu mone baku leo-èmu, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>I want to write about the issues which you asked about in your letter, saying, &lt;&lt;How about it? Is it better if a man doesn't marry, or (what)?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Sèmi ne'e: lula abhu lod'o taleo ae, dhu dhèu bisa manahu asa d'ara tatao dhu sala ètu d'ara pa'èci mone dènge bhèni, nèti èèna ka be'a risi dhèu mone èci hud'i dènge ku dhèu èmu nèngu mesa na. Sèmi èèna kahèi, dhèu bhèni hud'i pa'èci ku dènge dhèu èmu nèngu mesa na.<bt>It's like this: because there are many opportunities where a person can fall (physically, socially, morally, spiritually) into doing wrong in joining uniting with a male or female, that is why it is better/best if one man has his own wife/spouse. In the same way, a woman should join/unite with her own husband/spouse.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Mone dhu dènge le dhèu èmu! Mage mo'o boe j'unu pa'èci dènge dhèu èmu èu. Aa dhèu bhèni dhu dènge le dhèu èmu! Mage mo'o boe j'unu pa'èci dènge dhèu èmu èu.<bt>Husbands [lit: men w/spouses]! Do not refuse to sleep joined/united with your-sg spouse. And wives [lit: women w/spouses]! Don't refuse to sleep joined/united with your-sg spouse.</bt><v n="4" />Te bhèni dhu leo le èmu, hia le ngi'u na sèna ka j'aj'i unu dhèu èmu na. Aa mone dhu leo le èmu, hia le ngi'u na ho j'aj'i unu dhèu èmu na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the woman who has married has given her body to become her spouse's possession. And the man who has married has given his body to become his spouse's possession.</bt><v n="5" />De miu baku patula-pajuku, lula dua-dua mi dhu dènge hak hua! Te ngaa ladhe miu neo sabaj'a di, ho mo'o boe ngee j'ara dhu leo-leo, na, j'unu pa'èci boe d'ara ciki oo'e èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Sad'i dua mi mere lii èci ku. Aa ladhe sabaj'a mere, na, be'a risi pakaboko hari dènge ka. Te ladhe aad'o, na, bisa j'aj'i be'a boe! Te dhèu aae nidhu bisa dadugu-rariu dhèu dhu taha rare boe d'ara.<bt>So (consequently) don't keep refusing (doublet) each other, because both of you have those rights! But if you-pl are wanting to just pray, and don't want to be thinking about other matters, (you) can not sleep joined/united together for a short time. That's ok/doesn't matter/not a problem. As long as the two of you talk it over first, and are in agreement. And when the praying is over, it is best for the two of them to gather back together quickly/right away. If not, na, that can be not good! Cuz (elaboration) the king of evil spirits can easily tempt (doublet) people who are not strong in restraining themselves.</bt><v n="6" />J'ara ne mai nèti a'abhu ja'a di, nèti boe atora Lamatua.<bt>This matter just comes from my opinion, not God2's regulation. [Check what "ini hal" refers to].</bt><v n="7" />Madhutu ngangee ja'a, be'a risi dhèu baku leo-èmu, nuka sèmi ja'a dhu dènge boe dhèu èmu. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua hia dhèu karunya pamèci dènge nèngu. Nèti èèna ka, abhu dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua hia si leo-èmu, aa abhu cahag'e dhu Na hia si leo boe èmu.<bt>According to my thinking, it is best if a person doesn't marry, just like I have no spouse. But God has given each person a *unique.gifting which is fitting for him/her. That is why there are people whom He has them marry. And there are some others whom He has them not marry.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ja'a neo peka dènge dhèu mone do dhèu bhèni dhu leo mèka èmu, aa dènge bhèni balu, na, be'a risi miu baku leo-èmu, nuka sèmi ja'a ne.<bt>I want to tell/inform the men or women who have not yet married, and the widows, that, it is best if you don't marry, just like me.</bt><v n="9" />Te ngaa ladhe taha mere boe, hua iia leo èmu ka. Dhu hua iia risi ladhe dhèu leo-èmu, te aad'o na, dad'èi d'ara na pa'ele iie ngi'u nèngu unu na.<bt>But if (you) are not able to control/restrain yourself, it would be better to just marry. It is better for (that) person to marry, cuz (elaboration) if not, na, his own inner desires/lust/passion can ruin/destroy him/her.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ne'e ne mai boe nèti ngangee ja'a mesa ku. Te ja'a neo peka ngaa dhu Lamatua èdhi paredha le mi dhèu dhu leo le èmu, na, bhèni bisa boe pa'ia-pa'ela dènge dhèu èmu-kamali na.<bt>This is not from my thinking alone. Cuz (elaboration) I want to make known what our-inc Master has commanded people who are already married, saying, a woman may not divorce (doublet) her spouse.</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa ladhe nèngu tèke eele dhèu èmu na, be'a risi leo ia ka èmu. Hua iia nèngu la'e padame dènge mone dhu j'aj'i dhèu èmu na. Sèmi èèna kahèi mone, bisa boe pa'ia-pa'ela dènge dhèu èmu-kamali na.<bt>But, if she abandons her spouse, she should not remarry again. It would be best for her to make relational peace with the man who is/was her spouse. In the same way also, a man may not divorce (doublet) his spouse. [EXEG: CEV undertranslated ‘reconcile’ here.]</bt><note reference="7:10-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:32, 19:9, Markus 10:11-12, Lukas 16:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ne'e ne madhutu ngangee ja'a, mai boe nèti Lamatua èdhi. Aa mi dhèu leo, ja'a neo padhai lii sèmi ne'e: ladhe abhu mone dhèu sarani dhu dhèu èmu na parcaya boe Kristus, na, baku ia eele ne, ladhe dhèu èmu na neo mamuri taruu dènge nèngu.<bt>This is according to my own thinking, not from our Master. And as for other people, I want to say this: if there is a Christian man whose spouse does not believe in Kristus, na, he should not divorce2 her, if his spouse wants to continue living with him.</bt><v n="13" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge bhèni dhu dhèu èmu na parcaya boe Kristus, na, baku ia eele ne, ladhe mone ne d'èi era sèna ka dua ra mamuri pa'èci taruu.<bt>In the same way also, if there is a woman whose spouse doesn't believe in Kristus, na, she should not divorce2 him, if her husband still likes for them to continue living together.</bt><v n="14" />Te mone dhu parcaya boe Kristus, bisa mola-mèci, lula nèngu dhu pa'èki le dènge bhèni dhu j'aj'i dhèu èmu na. Aa bhèni dhu parcaya boe Kristus, bisa j'aj'i mola-mèci kahèi, lula nèngu dhu pa'èki dènge mone dhu j'aj'i dhèu èmu na. Te ladhe aad'o, na, ana-ana rèngu bisa boe mola-mèci. Te ngaa dènge j'ara ne, rèngu bisa mola-mèci ètu madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a man who doesn't believe in Kristus also becomes clean/pure/holy (doublet), because he is bound/linked with the woman who is his spouse. And a woman who doesn't believe in Kristus also becomes clean (doublet), because she is bound with the man who is her spouse. If not, na, their children would not be clean/holy. But in this way, they can be clean/holy before God.</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu bhèni do dhèu mone dhu parcaya boe Kristus, dhu la'e tèke eele dhèu èmu-kamali na dhu parcaya, na hud'i nèngu sène. Ka dhèu èmu dhu parcaya, pa'èki heka dènge ne. Te Ama Lamatua paroa miu sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, ho miu mamuri padame èci dènge èci.<bt>But if there is a woman or man who doesn't believe in Kristus, who abandons his spouse who believes, na, just let it be. So/then the spouse who believes is no longer bound/linked to him/her anymore. Cuz (elaboration) God has called you-pl to be His people, so you can live in relational peace with each other.</bt><v n="16" />Dhèu bhèni dhu parcaya, dhu leo le èmu aa'i-aa'i! Ele boe miu bisa hia mamuri mi dhèu èmu miu. Aa bisa aad'o kahèi. Sèmi èèna kahèi dhèu mone dhu parcaya dhu leo le èmu sèra! Ele boe miu bisa hia mamuri mi dhèu èmu miu. Aa bisa aad'o kahèi. Miu me'a iia mèka.<bt>Women who believe who have married! [NOTE: Gk is singular. Dhao plural for genre reasons.] It might be that you-pl can save/rescue your husbands. It also might not. Similarly for men who believe who have married.! It might be that you can save/rescue your wives. It also might not. You don't know yet for sure/precisely.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Madhutu paie-iie j'ara mamuri Lamatua<bt>Follow carefully God2's Life Way</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa mamuri dhèu èci-èci tasa mera mia lod'o Ama Lamatua paroa nare miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, mamuri taruu sèmi èèna. Baku ub'a hari, te Ama Lamatua dhu ator nare le sèmi èèna. Ja'a aj'a-nori atora ne ètu juma'at aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless however each person's life/situation was when God called you-pl to become His person, continue to live that way. There is no need to change it again, cuz (elaboration) God is the one who arranged it like that. I teach this regulation/instructions in all congregations. [NOTE to daughter translations: vs. 17, 20, 24 should be worded similarly enough that it is clear they are making the same point. Fee characterises it as "change is not to be the rule; rather, one is urged to stay in one's social condition at the time of one's conversion."; NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Conto, ladhe miu suna le sèna ka pad'elo, na, miu dhèu Yahudi, hèia lod'o limuri miu tadèngi Ama Lamatua paroa nare miu, na, baku pasili, peka na, miu suna le. Aa dhèu dhu dhae suna mèka ropa tadèngi Ama Lamatua paroa si, sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, na, suna ia ka. Lula rèngu dhu j'aj'i le dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>For example, if you-pl have been circumcised to show/ demonstrate that you are a Yahudi person, and only later you know that God called you, na, you don't have to deny/refuse to acknowledge that circumcision. And the person who was not yet circumcised when (they) heard God calling them to become His possession, na, (they) don't need to get circumcised as a sign that they have become God2's people. [NLT]</bt><v n="19" />Ladhe dhu suna le, èèna j'aj'i boe mi ngaa èci sa. Aa suna mèka èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Dhu dènge kab'ua ka, nuka èdhi madhutu lii paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>If (you) have been circumcised, that has no significance. And if (you) have not yet been circumcised, that also has no significance. What does have value/worth is: we-inc do according to what God commands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teresis: keeping, observance entoln: commandment, order|i(19)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">teresis: keeping, observance entoln: commandment, order<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>LITERALLY: Circumcision is nothing, and uncircumcision is nothing, but the keeping of God's commandments.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Lod'o Ama Lamatua hag'e nare miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, Lamatua pua boe miu suna, do baku suna. De hud'i ka laa sèmi èèna. Baku ub'a ia ka.<bt>When God chose you to become His people, He did not order you to get circumcised or not. So (consequently), just let you-pl be like that. (You) don't need to change anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ja'a hia hari conto èci. Ladhe èu j'aj'i ènu lod'o Ama Lamatua paroa èu, na, hud'i laa sèmi èèna, ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Te ngaa ladhe sèmi èu dhu ènu boe, na, hud'i laa! Ladhe bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu bebas, ngaa-ngaa tao boe kahèi.<bt>I'll give another example. If you-sg were a slave when God called you, na, just let you be like that, there is no problem/issue/it's OK. But if perchance [+hypothetical] you can become a free person (lit: not a slave), na, then go ahead and do that! If you can't become a free (loan) person, that's also OK.</bt><v n="22" />Te ropa Lamatua paroa ca dhèu ènu j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, ènu ne j'aj'i le sèmi ca dhèu dhu bebas, dhu sab'a hia Lamatua na ètu sorga. Aa lod'o Ama Lamatua paroa ca dhèu bebas j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, dhèu ne j'aj'i ana pua-paleha Kristus.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) when God2 calls a slave to become His person, that slave has already become a free person who works for his Master above. And when God calls a free person to become His person, that person now becomes Kristus' servant (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'i beko heka"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-04 04:10:33Z" status="Anyone">tidak terikat lagi ; ka'i = hook ;</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Kristus tihe pama'ète nare le miu dènge kab'ua titu kèna! De miu baku j'aj'i ènu hia dhèu leo.<bt>Kristus has paid off/paid in full for you-pl with an incredibly high price! So (consequently) you should not become a slave to another/different person.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="time: price, value agorazw: buy, purchase|i(23)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">time: price, value agorazw: buy, purchase<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>LITERALLY: You were bought for a price; do not become a slave of men.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Lod'o Ama Lamatua paroa nare miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, mamuri miu tasamia èèna ka, hud'i laa sèmi èèna. Baku ub'a ia ka. Hud'i laa sèmi èèna ka, hia mi Lamatua.<bt>Dear siblings! When God called you-pl to become His people, whatever your situation was, just leave it like that. You don't need to change anymore. Just let it be like that, for God. [NOTE to daughter translations: phrasing similar to vs.17, 20.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu leo mèka èmu<bt>Regarding people who don't marry</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Miu karèi ja'a lula-nèti dhèu kalora iisi dhu j'unu pa'èci rèdhi mèka dènge dhèu èci sa. Ama Lamatua peka boe ngaa-ngaa dènge ja'a nèti j'ara èèna. Te ngaa miu bisa sèmi ngaa dhu ja'a peka-padhai, lula Ama Lamatua pad'elo rasa kasia mi ja'a. Madhutu a'abhu ja'a sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>You-pl are asking me about single people who have never slept joined/united with anyone. God has not told me anything about that matter. But you can accept what I say, because God has shown His mercy to me. My thinking is like this:</bt><v n="26" />limuri ne èdhi abhu j'aj'èra rupa-rupa. De mamuri dhèu tasa mera mia èèna ka, hud'i laa sèmi èèna. Dad'èi ja'a sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Now we-inc get/experience all sorts of troubles/difficulties. So (consequently), however a person life/situation is, let him/her just be like that. What I mean is this:</bt><v n="27" />ladhe èu pa'èki dènge dhèu èmu èu, na, baku ia eele ne. Ladhe èu dhu pa'èki heka dènge dhèu èmu èu, na, tenge ia ka bhèni leo, sèna ka leo ia ka èmu.<bt>If you-sg are bound/linked with your spouse, na, don't release/get rid of her. If you are no longer bound with your spouse anymore, na, (you) don't need to keep looking to marry a different woman. [EXEG: Gk /luw/ (below in Gk notes) implies this is about remarriage, not just singleness. AGNT, Fee, Ex.Summ. #2.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dew: bind, tie gunaika: wife|i(27) (27)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">dew: bind, tie gunaika: wife<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>zetew: seek, look for try to obtain, strive for, aim at, desire, wish luw: free, set free, release, unravel (secrets), discharge/release (from contract)<span class="Italic">(27) (27) </span>LITERALLY: Are you bound to a wife? Do not seek to release her. Are you free from a wife? Do not seek a wife.</Message></Annotation><v n="28" />Te ngaa ladhe èu leo hari èmu, na, èu sala boe ngaa-ngaa. Aa ladhe bhèni dhu pa'èci rèdhi mèka dènge dhèu mone leo-èmu, nèngu ad'u-ue boe sasala ngaa-ngaa. Te ngaa sanèd'e, dhèu dhu paleo èmu, bèli-camèd'a paraga dènge j'aj'èra rupa-rupa ètu rai-haha ne. Dad'èi ja'a sèna ka miu baku susa sèmi èèna.<bt>But if you do remarry, you have not done any wrong. And if a woman who has never joined/united with a man marries, she has not done any wrong. But remember [caution/warning], a person who marries will get/experience all sorts of trouble in this world. My intention/desire is so you-pl don't have those troubles. [NOTE to daughter translations: "troubles" in vs 26 and vs. 28 are different lexemes in the Gk.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Madhutu ngangee ja'a, nuka: lod'o oe èle rai-haha ne dètu ae le. De mone dhu dènge dhèu èmu, mage ladhe dhoka dhèu èmu nèngu di, te ngaa laladhe kahèi asa Lamatua.<bt>Dear siblings! According to my thinking, this is how it is: the time for the end of the world is really close. So (consequently) for a man who has a spouse, he shouldn't just look at/pay attention to only his spouse, but he should also attend to God2. [NOTE on vs.29-31: This structure encouraged by Marge Crofts from Baluchi translation in Pakistan, linking to higher level context. See particularly cohesion with vs.32-35]</bt><v n="30" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, ladhe abhu dhu tangi, be'a risi pa'èra d'ara ho baku tangi, sèna ka laladhe asa Ama Lamatua. Ladhe abhu dhu karej'e-karae, be'a risi baku karej'e seli, te ngaa laladhe asa Ama Lamatua. Ladhe abhu dhu hèli ngaa-ngaa, be'a risi tao mamuri na nuka sèmi dhèu dhu dènge boe unu, sèna ka laladhe asa Ama Lamatua.<bt>In the same way also, if there is someone who is crying/mourning, it is best if s/he strengthens himself/pull self together to not cry, so that s/he can focus on God. If there is someone who is happy (doublet), it is best to make himself not overly happy, so that s/he can focus on God. If there is someone who is able to buy anything, it is best if s/he live like a person who has no possessions, so that s/he can focus on God.</bt><v n="31" />Ladhe abhu dhu pake mèdha-panyau nèti rai-haha ne, be'a risi tao ngi'u na, nuka sèmi dhèu dhu mamuri na dhu maena boe mi mèdha-panyau rai-haha ne, sèna ka na laladhe dhoka asa Ama Lamatua di. Lula j'ara mamuri rai-haha ne bèli-camèd'a ele.<bt>If there is someone who uses wealth/possessions from this world, it is best to make himself like a person who does not depend/hope on this world's things, so that s/he can focus only on God. Because this world's way of life will disappear/vanish.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ja'a d'èi sèna ka miu baku pangee ae-ae. Te dhèu dhu leo boe èmu, lod'o nèngu ae ho na tao madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Sèna ka nèngu bisa tenge j'ara ho sab'a pakarej'e d'ara Lamatua.<bt>I want for you-pl to not be worrying. Cuz (elaboration) a person who does not marry, his/her time is more, so s/he can do according to to God's desires/the things of God. That is why s/he can look for ways to work which make God2's insides happy.</bt><v n="33-34" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu leo le èmu, hud'i taru kira dad'èi rai-haha ne. Nèngu kahèi hud'i taru kira ku mi dad'èi Ama Lamatua, te ngaa nèngu hud'i tenge j'ara ho pakarej'e d'ara dhèu èmu na kahèi. J'ara se'e se ka tao ngangee na j'aj'i mi kajari.<bt>But a person who is already married must also focus on/give attention to the desires/issues of this world. S/he wants to focus on God2's desires/issues, but he must also look for ways to make his spouse happy. That is what makes his thinking be divided.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sèmi èèna kahèi, bhèni dhu dènge heka dhèu èmu, aa bhèni kalora iisi. Rèngu taru kira dad'èi Ama Lamatua, sèna ka bisa mamuri mola-mèci ètu d'ara dènge ngi'u aae. Te ngaa bhèni dhu leo le èmu, d'ara na kajari. Nèngu taru kira ka mi dad'èi Lamatua, te ngaa na tenge j'ara ho pakarej'e d'ara dhèu èmu na kahèi.<bt>It is the same way also, for women who no longer have a spouse, and single women. They focus on God's desires/issues, so they can live clean/holy/pure in their insides and in body. But a woman who is married, her insides are divided. Cuz (elaboration) she wants to focus on God2's desires, but she must also look for ways to make her spouse happy.</bt><v n="35" />Ja'a lole j'ara se'e, sèna ka nèti babe'a hia miu. Ja'a ko'o boe ho miu lèke sasii. Dad'èi ja'a ka, miu tao dhu lèke, aa tangare asa dad'èi Ama Lamatua, sèna ka ngangee miu baku kajari.<bt>I am telling these things to you, so you can get the benefit/goodness. I don't want you to be ensnared/trapped. My desire is for you to do what is right/true, and focus on God's desires, so your thinkng is not divided.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ladhe dhèu mone dhu lii d'ai le bhèni dhu d'ai umur paleo èmu, na, hud'i laa ra paleo, ladhe mone ne d'èi heka pamata. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, rèngu tao boe j'ara sala. Te ladhe ra mate panèbhu, mage dhoka mone èèna taha nare boe d'ara, hèia nèngu tao j'ara dhu lèke boe.<bt>If there is a man who has a candidate wife who is old enough to marry, na, just let them marry, if that man is not able to control/restrain/wait himself. They are not doing anything wrong like that. Don't let it get to the point that the man cannot restrain himself, and so in the end, that man's passions rise does things that are not right.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii dai le"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-09 00:21:32Z" status="Anyone">batunangan</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2010-11-03 02:55:23Z">ta'u'a = rasa bosan, pikiran berubah, luntur, kecewa **</Message></Annotation><v n="37" />Te ngaa ladhe mone ne bisa taha nare d'ara, nèngu baku laka-seti ho kab'i lai-lai. Te ne'a ngaa dhu nèngu neo tao. Masi ka nare nèbhu, dènge boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>But if he is able to control/restrain himself, he should not force to marry quickly. Cuz (elaboration) he knows what he wants to do. So even if he endures/lasts/holds out for a long time, that's also good. [EXEG: see NLT, but calon bini in Gk. both verses, so 36: can't control &gt; marry; 37: can control + clear (ministry) vision, so wait]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="histemi: stand hedraios: firm, steadfast|i(37) (37)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">histemi: stand hedraios: firm, steadfast<span class="Italic">(37) (37) </span>anagken: necessity, compulsion LITERALLY: But the one who stands firm in his heart, not having compulsion, but has power over his own desires, and that one decides in his own heart to keep his own fiancee, he does well;<span class="Italic">(37)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="38" />De dhèu mone dhu leo dènge bhèni na, èèna be'a. Aa dhu leo boe èmu èèna, be'a risi hari.<bt>So (consequently), a man who marries his candidate wife, that is good. And those who don't marry, that is even better.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhèni balu<bt>Widow ladies</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Bhèni dhu leo le èmu, pa'èki toke madhe dènge dhèu èmu na. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu èmu na madhe, nèngu bisa leo hari dènge dhèu mone leo, sad'i mone ne dhèu dhu parcaya Kristus kahèi.<bt>A woman who has married is bound until death to her spouse. But if her spouse has died, she can remarry a different man, as long as her new man is also a person who believes in Kristus.</bt><v n="40" />Madhutu a'abhu ja'a, be'a risi bhèni balu ne, leo ia ka èmu. Ja'a pangee, na, lii holo ne cèu nèti Roh Lamatua dhu ètu d'ara ja'a kahèi.<bt>Following my thinking, that widow is more fortunate/in a better state of affairs if she doesn't marry anymore. I think this advice is from God2's Spirit which is in me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="makarios: fortunate, happy givwmen: opinion, judgment|i(40)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">makarios: fortunate, happy givwmen: opinion, judgment<span class="Italic">(40) (40) </span>dokew: think, consider LITERALLY: But she is more fortunate if she remains thus, according to my opinion, and I think I also have the Spirit of God.<span class="Italic">(40)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nganga'a dhu dhèu pake ropa sogo-tagu nidhu<bt>Food which people have used when traditional worshiping</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 4:35,39; 6:4)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a neo lole lula-nèti sisi dhu dhèu pake sogo-tagu nidhu. Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti dhu te'a ae le j'ara se'e. Dhu j'aj'i mi lii langu, ka ladhe dhèu ne'a ae, na, nèngu bisa nged'e, te na pangee, na, nèngu d'èlu-mèu risi nèti dhèu leo sèra. De be'a risi, èdhi mamuri dènge pasue di. Te j'ara pasue ne'e ka tao dhèu aa'i-aa'i asa tabha èra ètu d'ara parcaya ra.<bt>I want to talk about meat which people have used in traditional worship. We-inc all already know much about these matters. The problem/issue/dispute is, if a person knows alot, s/he can be arrogant, cuz (elaboration) s/he thinks s/he is more clever than other people. So (consequently) it is best for us to just live mutually loving. Cuz (elaboration) that way of mutual loving is what make everyone be increasingly strong in their faith.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, ne'a mèu, èèna peka na, mamèu nèngu dhae d'ai mèka.<bt>If there is a person who considers themself to already know, that shows that his understanding is not yet complete.</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu sue Ama Lamatua, tatu Lamatua tadhe ne. Ne'e ka dhu lèke mola-mola.<bt>But if there is a person who loves God, surely God2 already knows him. That is what is right/important.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="agapaw: love, cherish ginwskw: know, acknowledge|i(3)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">agapaw: love, cherish ginwskw: know, acknowledge<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>houtos: this, this one LITERALLY: but if anyone loves God, this one is known by him.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />De ladhe dhèu na'a sisi dhu sogo-tagu le mi nidhu, èdhi aa'i-aa'i te'a, na, nèngu dhoka pahaha iisi mi mèdha sogo-tagu ètu rai-haha di, te ngaa pahaha boe iisi mi Lamatua dhu lèke. Te èdhi te'a, na, &lt;&lt;Abhu dhoka Ama Lamatua èci di dhu lèke.&gt;&gt; aa, &lt;&lt;mèdha sogo-tagu aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu sogo-tagu, dènge boe kab'ua.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), if a person eats meat which has been used in traditional worship, we-inc all know that, s/he is only worshipping trad.worship things in this world, but is not worshipping the true God2/Master. Cuz (elaboration) we-inc know that, &lt;&lt;There is only one true God.&gt;&gt; and, &lt;&lt;all trad.worship things that people worship have no value/ meaning.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="5" />Abhu mèdha ae-ae ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha ne, dhu dhèu peka, na, &lt;lamatua rèngu&gt; do aad'o na, &lt;kètu rèngu&gt;.<bt>There are many things in the sky and on earth which people refer to as &lt;their lord2/god2&gt; or &lt;their head&gt;.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa bagi èdhi, Ama Lamatua dhoka èci di.<bt>But for us-inc, there is only one God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu èèna, Ama èdhi.<bt>He is our Father.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i nèti Nèngu.<bt>Everything is sourced/comes into being from Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi tao hia mi Nèngu.<bt>Everything we do is for Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Kètu èdhi dhoka èci di,<bt>And our Head, is only one.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nuka Yesus Kristus.<bt>That is, Yesus Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua pake Yesus,<bt>God used Yesus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lod'o Na paj'aj'i aa'i-aa'i.<bt>when He created everything. [CEV, HCE, Ex. Summ. "It means that Jesus is the agent of creation [Ho, TNTC, TG]. God created all things by means of Jesus Christ [NIC2, TG]."; Fee "Jesus is the one through whom God both created and redeemed."]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa èdhi mamuri,<bt>And we are living,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Yesus ka dhu hia èdhi.<bt>because Yesus is the one who gave us (life). [CHECK if object of give comes through.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu dhu re'a boe j'ara se'e. Rèngu loe boe pangee mèdha sogo-tagu sèra, hèia ngangee rèngu èci èèna ka dènge ngangee rèngu uru sèra. Nèti èèna ka, ropa ra'a sisi dhu sogo-tagu nidhu, rèngu pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Nganga'a ne j'aj'i le korban ho pake sogo-tagu nidhu! Ladhe ja'a ku'a mèdha ne'e, na, ja'a pa'èki era dènge j'ara-j'ara dhu bhelu!&gt;&gt; De ne'e ne ka dhu pa'ele iie ngangee rèngu, toke rèngu bisa heka unu ngangee madhera, lula d'ara rèngu èra boe.<bt>[HCE] But there are people who don't know those things. They still keep thinking about those trad.worship things, just like their thinking before. That is why, each time they eat meat which people have used for trad.worship, they are thinking, &lt;&lt;This food has been a sacrifice to use for traditional worship! If I eat this stuff, I am still bound/linked with those evil things!&gt;&gt; So (consequently), it ruins/ destroys/ damages their thinking, to the point that they cannot think long anymore (wise, see implications), because their insides are not strong.</bt><v n="8" />Nga tao ka sèmi èèna? Nganga'a bisa boe nèti èdhi asa madha Ama Lamatua, si? Ladhe ta'a boe, èdhi asa boe bhelu, sina ma? Aa ladhe ta'a, tao boe èdhi j'aj'i dhèu be'a, si?<bt>Whis it like that? Food cannot bring us before God, right? If we don't eat (it), we don't become increasingly evil, do we? And if we eat it, it doesn't make us become good people, right?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa mage-mage! Masi ka èu dènge hak sèna ka ad'u-ue madha j'ara èci, tatu boe j'ara ne nèti babe'a hia èu. Ladhe sèmi abhu a'ari ca dhèu dhu parcaya èra boe, ladhe nèdhi èu tao j'ara èèna, hèia na manahu, na, èèna be'a boe!<bt>But be careful! Even if you-sg have the right to do something, it is not yet sure that that matter is good for you. If perchance [+hypothetical] there is a believing sibling whose insides aren't strong, if he sees you are doing that matter, so/then he falls/stumbles, na, that is not good!</bt><v n="10" />Èu dhu me'a le, j'ara ne j'aj'i boe mi ngaa èci sa. Te ngaa ladhe a'ari dhèu parcaya dhu d'ara na èra boe, ladhe nèdhi èu mu'a ètu d'ara èmu sogo-tagu, na pangee sèmi ngaa? Tatu na pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ja'a ku'a nganga'a sogo-tagu èèna, ngaa-ngaa tao boe, masi ka nganga'a èèna ra pae'a le nidhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>You already know that matter has no significance. But if the believing sibling whose insides are not strong, sees you eating in a house of trad.worship, what/how is s/he going to think? Surely s/he will think that &lt;&lt;If I eat food of trad.worship, there is no issue/problem, even if that food has been used in trad.worship.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="exw: have gnwsis: knowledge|i(10) (10) |reidwleion:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">exw: have gnwsis: knowledge<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>eidwleion: idol's temple katakeimai: recline (to eat)<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>suneidesis: consciousness, awarenesss, conscience, scruples asthenes: weak, powerless, morally weak<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>oikodomew: build, strengthen eidwlothutos: meat offered to an idol<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>esthiw: eat LITERALLY: For if someone sees you, having knowledge, reclining (to eat) in an idol's temple, won't the weak one's conscience be strengthened to eat meat offered to idols?<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Èu me'a le j'ara ae-ae. Te ngaa ladhe èu tao sèmi èèna, èu asa paroe d'ara dhèu dhu èra mèka. Aa te ngaa dhèu èèna, a'ari èu dhèu parcaya. Kristus madhe hia nèngu kahèi!<bt>You-sg already understand many things. But if you do that, you weaken the insides of the person who is not yet strong. And in fact that person is your believing sibling. Kristus also died for him/her!</bt><v n="12" />Hua iia pangee sèmi ne'e: ladhe a'ari èu dhu d'ara èra mèka ad'u-ue j'ara èci dhu madhutu ngangee rèngu sala lula tatao èu, na, èu tao le sasala hia rèngu. Aa èu tao sasala mi Kristus kahèi.<bt>It's best to think like this: if your-sg sibling whose insides are not yet strong, does something that they consider wrong because of your deeds/behaviour, you have done wrong to them. And you have also done wrong to Kristus.</bt><v n="13" />De ladhe ja'a ku'a nganga'a dhu tao a'ari ja'a dhèu parcaya manahu asa d'ara sasala, be'a risi ja'a baku ku'a sisi sèmi sèra, toke d'ai ja'a madhe. Te ja'a ko'o boe rèngu manahu asa d'ara sasala.<bt>So (consequently), if I eat something which makes my believing sibling fall into wrong, it is best that I not eat meat like that, even if it until I die. Cuz (elaboration) I don't want for them to fall into wrong.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lod'o Lamatua pua dhèu unu Na, Nèngu hia hak dènge koasa kahèi<bt>When God2 sends/commissions His people, He also gives them rights and power/authority</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Baku pangee, na, ja'a dènge boe hak ho suri sèmi ne'e hia miu. Te Ama Lamatua pua ja'a laku lole dènge dhèu lula-nèti Nèngu. Ja'a dhu kèdhi le Kètu èdhi, Yesus èèna. Ja'a dhu pa'èki mèno dènge Ne. Hèia miu aa'i-aa'i parcaya Nèngu kahèi, lula sasab'a-la'a ja'a ne.<bt>[cf The Message, MC, HCE, pos-neg] Don't think that I have no right to write this way to you-pl. Cuz (elaboration) God commissioned me to go tell people about Him. I have also seen Yesus, our-inc Head. I am bound/linked with Him continually. And so you all also believe in Him, because of my work. [EXEG: This verse sets off a defense (vs.1-27) against people who try to undermine Paul's claim to apostleship. At a low level “Have I not seen Jesus our Lord?” could be taken as a one-off event in the past, with no connection to the following “Are you not my work in the Lord?” At a high level, a point that runs through the whole section is Paul's continuing fathfulness and endurance, and how that impacted the Corinthians. This is hinted at by NLT “Isn't it because of my hard work that you are in the Lord?”, by CEV “and have led you to have faith in him”, and made explicit by HCE “I stay tight wit da Bos, an all you guys...”]</bt><v n="2" />Masi ka dhèu leo ro'o boe sèmi rare ja'a j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua, te ngaa tatu miu me'a, na, Lamatua ka dhu pua ja'a dhiu peka-padhai lii moa Na asa miu. Ladhe miu neo me'a mèu, na, lee mamuri miu di. Te miu dhu pa'èki era dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus!<bt>Even if other people don't accept me as God2's apostle, nevertheless you-pl surely know that God2 has commissioned me to tell/make known His message to you. If you want to know more certainly, na, just read/evaluate your own life/situation. Cuz (elaboration) you are still bound with our Head, Yesus Kristus!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ja'a neo dhaa mi dhèu dhu pèci sasala mi dedha ja'a, sèmi ne'e:<bt>I want to respond back to the people who like to accuse me of wrong, in this way:</bt><v n="4" />miu ngee, na, ja'a dènge Barnabas dènge boe hak ho abhu nganga'a-nganginu nèti dhèu dhu ji'i aj'a-nori si, do?<bt>Are you-pl thinking that I and Barnabas have no right to accept food-drink from the people we-exc teach, or (what)? [EXEG: see vs. 6]</bt><v n="5" />Miu pangee, na, ji'i dènge boe hak ho leo dènge dhèu bhèni Kristen, dhu la'a sama-sama pakako sasab'a Lamatua ètu era leo, do? Madhutu iia-iia na, dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dhu leo sèra, rèti kahèi dènge dhèu èmu ra. Ari Lamatua Yesus sèra tao sèmi èèna. Petrus mesa na sèmi èèna kahèi!<bt>Are you thinking that we don't have the right to marry a Christian woman, who can accompany us to carry out God2's work in other places, or (what)? In fact, God2's other apostles are taking their spouses. The Lord's younger.siblings also did that. Petrus himself is also doing that!</bt><note reference="9:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;Kefas&gt;. Kefas èèna, ngara leo nèti Petrus.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, &lt;Kefas&gt;. That Kefas, is Petrus' other name.</bt></note><v n="6" />Do, miu ngee na, dhoka ja'a dènge Barnabas di dhu hud'i sab'a tenge doi-dhari, sèna ka bisa mamuri ho aj'a-nori dhèu?<bt>Or, do you think that only I and Barnabas alone must work for money, so we can live to teach people? [EXEG: NLT, CEV]</bt><v n="7" />Ngangee miu sèmi èèna, mai nèti mia? Ladhe sèku sordad'u sèra. Rèngu pusi boe hèli nganga'a-nganginu dènge mèdha-papake. Ladhe sèku dhèu sab'a ètu oka anggor. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu kai, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu baku mu'a hua anggor sèra!&gt;&gt; Aa ladhe sèku dhèu madhenga badha. Dhèu ne dènge hak ho nare susu nèti kahib'i-kalèbho dhu nèngu j'aga.<bt>What is the basis for your thinking? Have a look at soldiers. They are not concerned about buying their food and clothes. Have a look at a person who works in a grape orchard. There is nobody who forbids him, saying, &lt;&lt;You-sg are not allowed to eat those grapes!&gt;&gt; Have a look at herders. That person has the right to take milk from the sheep he is guarding/watching. [EXEG: focus on workers--if labourers in secular occupations are paid, why not apostles?]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ja'a padhai lii ne madhutu boe ngangee ja'a dhèu rai-haha ne. Te Atora sèra nèti Ama Lamatua dhu peka sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>I am not talking like that according to my thinking as a human. Cuz (elaboration) God's Laws/Regulations also say the same.</bt><v n="9" />Ètu atora Musa, dhu suri peka na, &lt;&lt;Ropa sapi j'èli are ho hag'e eele lamusi nèti huri na, baku kape hèb'a na, sèna ka bisa na'a.&gt;&gt; Miu pangee, na, Lamatua soro tèke sèna ka dhoka sapi di dhu bisa na'a, do?<bt>In Musa's regulations/law it is written, saying, &lt;&lt;When a cow is stepping on grain to separate the grainheads from the stalks, don't tie closed its mouth so that it cannot eat.&gt;&gt; Do you think that God2 wants to allow it so that only the cows are the ones who can eat, or (what?) [ALT: some RLs can't do the double negative, so ALT: jang ika mati dia pung mulu ko biar dia bisa makan sa.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kape "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-09 02:54:33Z" status="Anyone">tutup, cover over as hand over mouth</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 25:4, 1 Timotius 5:18</note><v n="10-11" />Aad'o! Lamatua peka na, Nèngu taru kira èdhi kahèi. Te dhu suri tèke, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu kabèli rai, aa dhèu dhu hag'e eele lamusi nèti huri na, ropa ra sab'a, rèngu re'a kahèi, èèna na abhu pala ra.&gt;&gt; Sèmi èèna kahèi, be'a risi dhèu pajuu-paleha dhèu Kristen sèra, bisa abhu pala nèti rui-j'aj'èra ra. Te lod'o ji'i aj'a-nori miu j'ara-j'ara nèti Roh Lamatua èèna, ji'i nuka sèmi ca dhèu sab'a oka-tedhe dhu sèle hini. De lod'o ji'i aj'a ngare, ladhe ji'i abhu nganga'a-nganginu do ngaa hari nèti miu, ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Te j'ara na sèmi èèna ka!<bt>[see NLT] No! God2 says He is watching over/attending to us-exc! Cuz (elaboration) it is also written, saying, &lt;&lt;The person who turns the soil, and the person who separates the seeds from the grainhead, when they are working, they also know that they will get their portion/share.&gt;&gt; In the same way, it is good if Christian apostles/emissaries can receive their portion from their sweat/efforts. Cuz (elaboration) when we are teaching you-pl things from God2's Spirit, that is the same as a farmer who is planting in the field. So (consequently), when we have finished teaching, na, there is no problem/it is OK if we receive food-drink or anything else from you-pl. Cuz that is what is appropriate!</bt><note reference="9:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Roma 15:27</note><v n="12" />Dhèu leo dhu aj'a-nori miu, dènge hak sèna ka abhu dhua-èi dènge mèdha-panyau nèti miu, si? Aa ji'i tasamia? Ji'i dènge hak risi eele nèti rèngu!<bt>Other people who teach you have the right to receive food2 and other things from you, right? So, as for us-exc, how is it? We have more rights than they!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhua-èi "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-09 03:07:35Z" status="Anyone">Fig. = food-drink</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa miu me'a le. Ji'i se pake ngèdhi boe hak ho laka-seti miu. Ji'i pa'èra ètu rupa-rupa j'ara, sèna ka baku magee miu. Te, dènge j'ara ne'e, miu d'èi nanene Lii Lolo Be'a Yesus Kristus dhu ji'i peka-padhai dènge miu.<bt>But you already know. We-exc have never used our right to force you. We have endured all sorts of things (negative implications), so (we) would not make any barriers/hindrances for you. Cuz (elaboration) in that way, you liked to listen to Kristus' Good News which we told to you.</bt><v n="13" />Pangee ku laa! Ama-ama agama dhu sab'a ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi, mamuri nèti persembahan dhu dhèu rèti. Aa dhèu dhu sab'a ètu mei korban, ra'a sisi nèti badha dhu dhèu rèti.<bt>Have a think! The *priests who serve in the Yahudi people's *Temple (Central House of Worship), they live from the *offerings (loan) which people bring. And people who serve at the *altar (sacrifice table), they can eat the meat from the animals which people bring.</bt><note reference="9:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:1</note><v n="14" />Sèmi èèna kahèi, Lamatua dhu moa, na, dhèu dhu sasab'a ra peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a Kristus, rèngu bisa mamuri nèti rui-j'aj'èra nèti sasab'a-la'a ra. Dhu lèke kèna.<bt>In the same way also, God2's has instructed that people whose work/responsibility it is to tell/make known Kristus' Good News, they can live from the sweat/efforts/rewards of their work. That is what is right.</bt><note reference="9:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:10, Lukas 10:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Masi ka ja'a dènge hak ho mamuri sèmi èèna, te ngaa ja'a d'èi boe tao sèmi èèna. Ja'a suri boe sasuri ne sèna ka miu hia ja'a ngaa-ngaa. Nèbhu nare sange ne'e, ja'a pakako sasab'a Lamatua hia miu, te ngaa manèngi boe ngaa-ngaa nèti miu. De hua iia risi ja'a madhe, ladhe dhèu pangee, na, ja'a manèngi ngaa-ngaa nèti miu.<bt>[NLT] Even though I have the right to live like that, nevertheless I don't like to do that. I did not write this letter with the intention that you-pl give me anything. For a long time now I have carried out God2's work for you without asking for anything from you. So (consequently), it would be better for me to die, than for people to think that I have begun to ask anything from you.</bt><v n="16" />Masi ka ja'a lole taruu dènge dhèu lula-nèti Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua, te ngaa èèna j'aj'i boe mi ngaa sa èci, dhu ja'a bisa padedha iisi. Ja'a hud'i lole ku dènge dhèu lula-nèti Lamatua, te Lamatua ka dhu pua ja'a sèmi èèna. Ladhe ja'a sab'a boe madhutu sasab'a ja'a, na dui kore j'aj'èra! Te tatu pasae kore hahuku.<bt>Even if I continue to tell people about God2's Good News, nevertheless that is not a basis/reason/excuse for me to be able to talk big. I must tell people about God2, cuz (elaboration) God2 is the one who commissioned me to do that. If I don't work (v) according to my work (n)/responsibilities, na, I am in real strife/ danger! Cuz (elaboration) surely I will bear/ experience punishment. [CHECK: Does speaker attitude come through?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hedha ritu-ritu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-09 03:17:27Z" status="Anyone">padedha iisi (rare)</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ladhe ja'a sab'a sasab'a ne lula madhutu dhoka dad'èi ja'a mesa ku, na, ngaa dhu ja'a abhu sèra, nuka sèmi gaji dhu dhèu sab'a sèra abhu. Te ngaa ladhe ja'a sab'a sasab'a ne, lula Lamatua pua ja'a, èèna leo. Te Lamatua lèka ja'a ho j'aga mèdha-panyau Na dhu kab'ua.<bt>If I work this work only because of my own liking, na, whatever things I get, are like wages which workers receive. But if I work this work because God2 has commissioned me, that is different. Cuz (elaboration) God2 is trusting me to guard/watch over His valuable possessions/wealth/things.</bt><v n="18" />De ladhe sèmi èèna, upa ja'a ngaa? Ja'a parluu boe gaji. Ja'a padhue-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua, dhu manèngi boe ngaa-ngaa. Ne'e ka dhu tao ja'a karae, nuka sèmi ja'a abhu le upa. De masi ka ja'a unu rupa-rupa hak, nuka sèmi dhèu leo dhu sasab'a ra padhue-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a èèna, te ngaa ja'a pake aa'i boe hak sèra.<bt>So (consequently), if that is the case, what is my reward2? I don't need wages! I tell God2's Good News and don't ask for anything. That is what makes me feel satisfied/happy2, like I am getting my reward. So (consequently), even though I have various rights like other persons who has the job/responsibilities to tell that Good News, nevertheless I myself do not use all those rights.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ja'a ne, dhèu bebas dhu sab'a madhutu dad'èi d'ara ja'a. Dhèu dènge boe hak ho pua ja'a tao ne'e, do, tao èèna. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa ja'a tao ngi'u nuka sèmi ènu, ho dhèu aa'i-aa'i abhu hak ho paleha ja'a. Dènge j'ara ne, ja'a bisa soru-bara dhèu ae, sèna ka ra madhutu Ama Lamatua taruu.<bt>I here, am a free (loan) person who works according to what I like. People don't have the right to order me to do this, or do that. Even that being the case, nevertheless I make myself like a slave, so that all people have the right to order me around. In that way, I can help (doublet) many people to keep following God. [EXEG: kerdeésoo: "win people as Christians" fits with Verses 20 &amp; 21. But Verse 22 also brings in Christians who are weak in faith. Could mean "make and keep people as Christians to the end". "close to God" may be a way to cover both]</bt><v n="20" />De ladhe ja'a pa'èci dènge dhèu Yahudi, na, ja'a tao iisi sèmi dhèu Yahudi, sèna ka soru-bara dhèu Yahudi ho ra tadhe Lamatua. Ladhe ja'a pa'èci ka dènge dhèu dhu kèpe pa'èra Atora Lamatua, ja'a tao madhutu Atora Lamatua, ho ja'a bisa soru-bara si, sèna ka ra tadhe mèu Lamatua, (masi ka ja'a ke'a, na, tao madhutu Atora èèna, bisa boe pabe'a ja'a dènge Lamatua).<bt>So (consequently), when I am joined with the Yahudi people, I make myself like a Yahudi person, to help (doublet) Yahudi people know God2. When I am joined with people who hold firmly to God2's Law, I do according to God2's Law, so I can also help (doublet) them to know God2, (even though I already know that doing according to that Law cannot make me be in a reciprocally right relationship with God2).</bt><v n="21" />Ladhe ja'a pakaboko dènge dhèu dhu re'a boe Atora Lamatua, ja'a j'aj'i sèmi rèngu ho lere kèti si asa Lamatua. (Ja'a patabuli boe Atora Lamatua dhu Na hia mai re Musa, te ngaa ja'a mamuri pake Atora Kristus)<bt>When I am gathered with people who don't know God2's Law, I become like them, to lead them to God2. (I don't release/get rid of God2's Law which He handed down via Musa, but now I live using Kristus' Law.) [EXEG: without reference to Musa, makes it sound like Paul is throwing off God's (higher) law.]</bt><note reference="9:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 22:34-40, Markus 12:28-34, Lukas 10:25-28, 1 Korintus 13:1-8</note><v n="22" />Dènge dhèu dhu d'ara èra boe, na, ja'a tao iisi sèmi dhèu dhu d'ara èra boe kahèi, ho ja'a bisa pamako si sèna ka mai asa Ama Lamatua. Dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, ja'a tao iisi sèmi rèngu, sèna ka, ladhe bisa, kèti cahag'e asa madha Lamatua.<bt>For people whose insides are not strong, I also make myself like a person whose inside isn't strong, so that I can coax/cajole them to come to God. For all people, I make myself like them, so that if possible, I can bring some to God2.</bt><v n="23" />Ja'a tao j'ara aa'i-aa'i se, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa lèka Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne'e, èdhi bisa abhu pala dhu be'a nèti madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i, dhu Lamatua hia èdhi.<bt>I do all these things, so that all people can believe in God2's Good News. In that way, we can have a share in all good things, which God2 gives to us. [HCE; EXEG: "all people" from v22 and context; "I" &gt; "we-exc" shift from implications of "fellow-partaker"]</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\BK00157C.tif" rtfFormat="width:3.5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dhèu Yunani hia solo juara mi dhèu dhu segi<bt>The Greeks gave a champion's hat to the person who won</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ja'a pakasame dènge pa'uji rai. Dhèu ae-ae madhutu pa'uji rai, te ngaa dhu abhu juara dhoka dhèu èci di. De miu èci-èci mi hud'i rai pa'èra-èra ku ho j'aj'i juara hia Lamatua.<bt>I'll give an example from a running competition. Many people participate in running, but the one who gets champion one, is only just one person. So (consequently), each of you-pl must run with all your strength to become a/the champion for God2. [NOTE to daughter translations: Similarly, you must work with all your strength to.... Kupang is an urban society and has sports vocab. The vernaculars are unlikely to, so the first round of daughter translations are going to need to do some exploratory work to fill out the topic (of comparisons)]</bt><v n="25" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhutu pa'uji, hud'i madhutu ku paredha nèti dhèu dhu aj'a rèngu, si? Dhèu se sab'a bia sèmi èèna, lula neo abhu solo juara dhu bèli-camèd'a ele iie. Te ngaa èdhi sab'a sèna ka abhu upa dhu taha toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>All people who participate in the competition must follow/obey the commands of the person who teaches them, right? They work hard in that way, so they can get a champion's hat which will wither. But as for us, we work to get a reward2 which will endure forever. [EXEG: Fee: self-control in focus.]</bt><v n="26" />De ja'a rai leli boe. Te ngaa ja'a tenge j'ara ho rai pa'èra-èra toke d'ai lane. Ladhe pasoro ja'a sèmi dhèu tuka paj'ubhu, na, ja'a j'ubhu leli boe, te ngaa hud'i j'ubhu palèke ku.<bt>So (consequently), I do not run aimlessly/any old way. But I make a hard effort to run strongly to the finish line. If you compare me to a boxer, na, I don't punch aimlessly/flailing, but I hit connecting.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paj'ubhu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-09 03:52:42Z" status="Anyone">box, tinju</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ja'a pa'èra d'ara, aa aj'a ngi'u sèna ka bisa taha taruu. Te be'a boe ladhe ja'a peka dènge dhèu leo lula-nèti Ama Lamatua, aa te ngaa ja'a mesa ku sisu atora, hèia Lamatua kalua eele ja'a nèti d'ara pa'uji rai èèna.<bt>I prepare myself, and teach my body so I can endure/persevere/last. Cuz (elaboration) it is not good if I tell other people about God, but in fact I myself have violated the rules, so God2 disqualifies me from the running competition.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mage pamud'e dènge mèdha pae'a nidhu<bt>Watch out for/Be careful with trad.worship2 things!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Mage miu bhèlu eele lii lolo dhu uru èèna, lod'o bèi-baki èdhi ètu era dhu dhèu pea boe. Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u j'ara hia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, pake ra'i-liru dhu kako uuru nèti rèngu. Aa Ama Lamatua hag'e eele èi dhasi, hèia ra kako d'ai cabèka dhasi dènge sod'a.<bt>[NLT] Dear siblings! You-pl must not forget about that story long ago when our-inc ancestors were in the place where nobody lived (=wilderness). God showed the way for all of them, using a cloud that went in front of them. Then He separated the sea water, and they walked until coming out on the other side of the sea safely.</bt><note reference="10:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 13:21-22, 14:22-29</note><v n="2" />Dhasi dènge ra'i-liru se, nuka sèmi lii pakasame sa. Te bèi-baki èdhi sèra lèka Musa nuka sèmi ama ho lere si, ka ra madhutu ra'i-liru, aa maso asa d'ara dhasi palere-lere dènge ne. Èèna sama sèmi èdhi dhu parcaya Kristus hèia abhu sarani, dhu peka na, èdhi j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, aa ti nanene Ne.<bt>[HCE] That sea and that cloud are an example/ comparison/ allegory/parable. Cuz (elaboration) our ancestors trusted in Musa like a father/leader to lead them, so they followed that cloud, and went into the sea water together with him. That is like we who trust/believe in Kristus, so/then (we) get *baptised (method neutral), to show that we have become His people, and we listen to/obey Him.</bt><v n="3" />Bèi-baki èdhi aa'i-aa'i ra, ra'a nganga'a dhu Roh Lamatua sadia tèke hia ra.<bt>All our ancestors ate the food that God's Spirit prepared/made available for them. [NOTE on vs.3-4: "the same" omitted (explicit to implicit) for naturalness, and information load. But note it is still implied by the use of /aa'i-aa'i/ in this construction.]</bt><note reference="10:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 16:35</note><v n="4" />Aa rinu nèti èi dhu Roh Lamatua sadia hia ra kahèi. Èi dhu rinu èèna kalua nèti hadhu aae dhu Roh Lamatua paj'uj'u tèke. Rèngu lasi asa mia-mia èèna ka, hadhu èèna dhu ètu èèna le. Madhutu iia-iia na, hadhu èèna, nuka Kristus.<bt>And (they all) also drank the water that God's Spirit prepared/made available for them. The water that they drank, came out of a large rock which God's Spirit had shown them. Wherever they went, na, that rock was already there. In actual fact, that rock was Kristus.</bt><note reference="10:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 17:6, Sensus 20:11</note><v n="5" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua d'èi boe dènge tatao dhèu ae sèra. Ka ropa ra kako palème era mamoo dhu taleo èèna, dhèu ae madhe. Ka ra padhane si palème era.<bt>[CEV; HCE] But God did not like the deeds/behaviour of those many people. So, when they were walking around in that wide lonely place, many people died. And/So they buried them in many places. [EXEG: Gk katestroótheesan is distributive: God killed them, some in one place and some in another, so that everywhere they went they had to bury people in each place]</bt><note reference="10:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 14:29-30</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />J'ara aa'i-aa'i se ho j'aj'i mi conto, sèna ka èdhi baku d'èi tao j'ara bhelu sama sèmi rèngu.<bt>All those things happened as an example, so we-inc wouldn't have a desire to do evil like them.</bt><note reference="10:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 11:4</note><v n="7" />Baku pae'a nidhu sèmi rèngu cahag'e. Ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci, dhu suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Isra'el madhèdi ra'a-rinu pesta ètu madha patung sapi iiki ci'u. Ka ra sogo-tagu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't be involved in trad.worship, like some of them were. In the Scriptures it is written, saying, &lt;&lt;These Isra'el people sit eating-drinking festively in front of the statue of a calf (cow offspring). Then they trad.worshipped it.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="10:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 32:6</note><v n="8" />Èdhi baku tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu dhèu èmu-kamali boe èdhi. Te uru-uru sèra, rèngu tao j'ara makae sèmi sèra ka, hèia dua nguru tèlu riho dhèu madhe ètu d'ara ca lod'o doko èèna ka.<bt>We-inc must not do shameful things (sexually) with a person who is not our spouse. Cuz (elaboration) long ago, they did shameful things like that, and there were 23,000 people who died in a single day. [CHECK doko w/UNSs]</bt><note reference="10:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 25:1-18</note><v n="9" />Èdhi baku ad'u-ue bhabhelu rupa-rupa, ho neo te'a, Kristus huku èdhi, do aad'o. Te dhèu Isra'el cahag'e neo sèku Ama Lamatua sèmi èèna ka, ka Na hia mege ae-ae dhu dènge raco sèna ka kadhi pamadhe si.<bt>We-in must not keep trying to do various sorts of evil, to find out if Kristus is going to punish us, or not. Cuz (elaboration) some of the people of Isra'el wanted to test God's mettle/character like that, so He sent many poisonous snakes which bit (like snake or chicken) killing them.</bt><note reference="10:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 21:5-6</note><v n="10" />Èdhi baku ka'uu-kamuki kahèi. Te dhèu Isra'el cahag'e re'a dhoka ka'uu-kamuki di, ka Ama Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na èci nèti sorga mai pamadhe si.<bt>We-inc must also not complain/grumble (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) some of the people of Isra'el kept complaining (about everything), so then God sent one of His angels to kill them.</bt><note reference="10:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 16:41-49</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />J'ara ne lèke mi dhèu Isra'el, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha hia mi èdhi. Ra suri se'e se, ho èdhi bisa te'a, sèna ka baku tao madhutu sasala rèngu. Te lod'o èle rai-haha ne dètu ae le.<bt>Those things befell the Isra'el people, to be a sign/example for us. They wrote (all) those things, so we would not do following their wrongs. Cuz (elaboration) the end of the world is very near.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Sanèd'e paie! Limuri ne èu ngee, na, èu èra le. Te ngaa baku pamud'e, sèna ka baku manahu.<bt>Remember carefully! [caution] Now you-sg are thinking that you are strong. But you must be careful, so that you do not fall.</bt><v n="13" />Lod'o-lod'o ngee mèdhi neo tao bhabhelu, te ngaa sanèd'e, te dhèu leo dhu paraga rèdhi le kahèi, dadugu-rariu sèmi sèra. Te ngaa èu bisa parcaya Ama Lamatua, sèna ka Na tao madhutu ngaa dhu Nèngu peka. Te Lamatua soro tèke boe èu ho abhu dadugu-rariu risi nèti a'èra èu. Ropa èu paraga dènge dadugu-rariu, Nèngu pad'elo j'ara kalua hia èu. Nèngu neo pa'èra èu, ho baku manahu.<bt>Each time you feel a desire to do evil, remember that other people have also encountered/ experienced temptation/ testing/trial like that. But you can trust in God for Him to do according to what He has said. Cuz (elaboration) God2 will not let you experience temptation more/beyond than your strength/ability/endurance. Each time you get/experience temptation, na, He shows a way out for you. He wants to make you strong, so you don't fall. [EXEG: temptation to do wrong, not testing, such as a spouse dying.][NOTE: Next to last sentence should be “He gives/provides a way out for you.” But /hia/ ‘gives/provides’ is related to prep /hia/ ‘to/for’ in same clause. Stylistically they really don't like /hia...hia/. Since the prep is harder to substitute, they changed verb to /padelo...hia/ ‘shows’, which may introduce wrong meaning/impression. (?) Suggestions? I think /hia...mi/ might be a better solution.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />De a'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ladhe dhèu neo laka-seti miu sèna ka sogo-tagu nidhu, na, pakeso nèti era èèna! Baku pamata!<bt>So (consequently) dear siblings! If someone wants to try and force pressure you to trad.worship (evil) spirits, na, just get out of there! Don't dawdle!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakeso"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 00:42:45Z" status="Anyone">ondor, pakaj'èu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ja'a padhai lii dènge miu dhu me'a ngee madhera. Hud'i laa miu mesa mi dadoo unu mi, ngaa dhu ja'a neo peka-padhai èèna, lèke tare'a.<bt>I am speaking to you-pl who know how to think long (wise, think through, examine implications). Go ahead and weigh/evaluate for yourselves what I am going to say is true.</bt><v n="16" />Pangee sèku j'ara ne: ladhe èdhi pakaboko sèna ka ta'a-tinu ètu mei Ama Lamatua, hèia tare galaa ho manèngi makasi mi Lamatua, ka tinu nèti galaa èèna, sasoa na, èdhi dhu pa'èki dènge Kristus. Ropa Na pasuti raa Na ka Na madhe, èèna sama sèmi èdhi madhutu madhe kahèi. Ladhe èdhi pamae roti èèna, hèia ta'e, sasoa na, èdhi dhu pa'èki dènge Kristus. De ropa Kristus madhe, èèna sama sèmi èdhi kahèi madhe sama-sama dènge Ne.<bt>Have a think about this: if we-inc gather together to eat at God's table, then take that glass to give thanks to God2, then we drink from that glass, it means that we are bound/linked with Kristus. When He spilled His blood to die, it is as if we also accompanied/participated in dying. If/when we break that bread, then we eat (it), that means that we are bound with Kristus. So (consequently), when Kristus died, that is like we also died together with Him.</bt><note reference="10:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:27-28, Markus 14:22-24, Lukas 22:19-20</note><v n="17" />Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti ta'e nèti roti cue. De aa'i-aa'i dhu rare pala nèti roti cue ne, nuka sèmi èdhi dhu pa'èki j'aj'i mi ngi'u èci, masi ka èdhi dhèu ae-ae.<bt>All of us-inc eat from the same (loaf of) bread. So (consequently), everyone who takes a portion from that same bread, is like we are bound/linked together becoming one body, even though we are many people.</bt><v n="18" />Pangee sèku dhèu Isra'el uru sèra. Ropa rèngu roro badha ètu dedha mei korban sèna ka pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua, ama agama dhu roro ne ka dhu bisa na'e sisi èèna. Sasoa na, rèngu pa'èki dènge Lamatua, aa pa'èki kahèi dènge dhèu dhu rèti badha ho j'aj'i mi korban.<bt>Have a think about the people of Isra'el long ago. When they ritually slaughtered animals on the sacrifice table to worship God, the priest who slit the throat is the one who got to eat its meat. That meant that they were bound/linked with God2, and they were also bound with the person who brought that animal to be a sacrifice. [NOTE to daughter translations: explication to make lexical cohesion to the section that this closes. NLT, HCE]</bt><note reference="10:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 7:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Madhutu a'abhu ja'a, tasamia? Lod'o dhèu dhu tadhe boe Lamatua neo hia mèdha-panyau rèngu j'aj'i mi mèdha sogo-tagu ra, èèna dènge boe kab'ua, do? Te mèdha sogo-tagu sèra, dhoka patung dhu madhe di! Aad'o! A'abhu ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: lod'o dhèu roro badha ho j'aj'i badha sogo-tagu, rèngu sogo-tagu nidhu bhelu. Te ngaa rèngu pahaha boe iisi mi Ama Lamatua dhu lèke. De ja'a ko'o boe ho miu pa'èki dènge nidhu bhelu sèmi sèra.<bt>What do I mean2? When people who do not know God2 want to give offerings to their trad.worship things, it has no value/ significance, or (what)? Cuz (elaboration) that trad.worship things is just a dead statue (loan)! No! What I mean2 is this: when a person slaughters an animal to be a sacrifice to their trad.worship things, they are trad.worshipping *evil spirits. But they are not worshipping the true God. So (consequently), I don't want you-pl to be bound/linked to evil spirits like those.</bt><note reference="10:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:17</note><v n="21" />Ladhe miu pa'èki dènge Lamatua, ka minu nèti galaa ètu mei Lamatua, na, miu bisa boe pa'èci dènge nidhu bhelu sèra, aa baku minu nèti galaa dhu ra pake pae'a nidhu. Te ladhe miu minu sèmi èèna, sasoa na, miu pa'èki dènge nidhu bhelu. Sèmi èèna kahèi, ladhe mi'a ètu mei Lamatua, miu bisa boe mi'a ètu mei nidhu. Goa, ee! Te sasoa na, miu pa'èki dènge nidhu bhelu sèra!<bt>If you are bound with God2, then (sequence) drink from that glass at God2's table, na, you can not join/unite with evil spirits, and must not drink from their glass when people are trad.worshipping2 (exil) spirits. Cuz (elaboration) that means that, you are bound/linked to those evil spirits. In the same way also, if you eat at God2's table, you may not eat at the table of the (exil) spirits. Stupid, ee! Cuz (elaboration) that means that you are bound/linked with those evil spirits!</bt><v n="22" />Madhutu a'abhu miu sèmi ngaa? Neo papèd'a d'ara Lamatua èdhi, do? Èèna bahaya! Ele boe miu ngee, na, miu èra risi Lamatua, do?<bt>What are you thinking? Do you want make our-inc Master jealous/upset/vengeful, or (what)? That's dangerous (loan)! Perhaps you think that you are stronger than God2, or (what)? [LEX: parazeelóumen: make God angry, making him resent those who do not give God the total loyalty that they have promised.]</bt><note reference="10:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 32:21</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tao aa'i mèu-mèu, sèna ka ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Lamatua<bt>Do everything to *glorify (elevate way up high) God2's name/reputation</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ele boe miu pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo tao ngaa èèna ka, bisa. Te èèna hak ja'a.&gt;&gt; Tare'a. Te ngaa sanèd'e, tatu boe j'ara aa'i-aa'i sèra nèti babe'a hia èu. Aa tatu boe j'ara aa'i-aa'i sèra, bisa soru-bara èu ho pa'èra d'ara mu.<bt>Perhaps you-pl might think, &lt;&lt;Whatever I want to do, I may do it. Cuz (elaboration) that is my right.&gt;&gt; True, But remember that surely not everything is good for you (lit: brings goodness to you). And surely not everything can help strengthen your insides. [Gk. TEXT: "For me" appears only in late manuscripts or in scribal emendations scribbled on top of old manuscripts. It is here because the local lgs are non-sensical without it, not because it is in later MSS.]</bt><note reference="10:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 6:12</note><v n="24" />Baku tenge dhoka leto pala ngi'u èu di. Be'a risi tenge oto hia dhèu leo kahèi.<bt>Don't just look for benefit/profit for your own self. It is better to also look for benefit2 for other people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />De ja'a manèngi sèmi ne'e: ladhe hèli sisi ètu d'ara pasa, na, mu'a laa. Baku pakarèi ia ka, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sisi pae'a nidhu, do?&gt;&gt; Do pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a bisa ku'a sisi ne, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), I ask/request like this: if (you) buy meat in the market, na, just eat it. (You) don't need to be asking around anymore, saying, &lt;&lt;Has this meat been used in trad.worship2, or (not)?&gt;&gt; Or think, that, &lt;&lt;May I eat this meat, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="26" />Lula ètu d'ara Sasuri Lamatua dhu suri tèke, peka na, &lt;&lt;Rai-haha dènge isi na aa'i-aa'i, unu Lamatua èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because in God2's Scriptures it is written, saying, &lt;&lt;The world and all its contents, belongs to our-inc Master.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="10:26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 24:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu parcaya mèka Kristus nèru miu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati ta'a asa èmu ja'a!&gt;&gt; Ladhe miu lami, na, mi'a ngaa dhu na hia miu. Baku pakarèi ia ka, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a bisa ku'a nganga'a ne'e, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>If there is a person who does not yet believe in Kristus, invites you, saying, &lt;&lt;Come, eat at (my) house!&gt;&gt; If you want to go, na, just go, and eat whatever they give you-pl. Don't ask, &lt;&lt;May I eat this food, or not?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="28" />(Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhu mai paka'uu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku mu'a ne'e ne, te sisi ne sisi sogo-tagu nidhu,&gt;&gt; be'a risi èu baku mu'a. Èu hud'i taru kira ku mi dhèu dhu mai peka lii deo na, ho baku pabia ne.<bt>(But if there is a person who comes and complains, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't eat this here, cuz (elaboration) this is meat used in trad.worship,&gt;&gt; it's better that you-sg not eat. You must pay attention to that person who came to speak just now, to not burden him/her. [EXEG: From the Gk, the issue is “whose conscience”. Almost all go with “the one who informed you” (Ex.Summ. NLT, CEV). So the issue for doughter trans is if they take KM /kabaratan/ as 1) have issues with (conscience), or 2) the social act of expressing objection. The first is the intended meaning. Note TB also uses /keberatan/. The problem with the suggestion of saying ‘Pay attention to what he believes to be right’ is this phrasing throws it into the sector of religious beliefs, and not ethical considerations, skewing the focus.] [ALT: ko jang bekin barát sang dia.]</bt><v n="29" />A'abhu ja'a, na, pangee paie-iie, madhutu ngangee dhèu deo na, bisa ku'e do aad'o. Baku ngee dhoka dhu be'a madhutu ngangee èu mesa mu.)<bt>What I mean is, think it through carefully, according to that person, is it OK for me to eat, or not. Don't just think what is good according to your own thinking.) [ALT: iko lu pung pikiran sandiri.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa te ngaa, ja'a bisa tao madhutu d'èi d'ara ja'a. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu leo pangee, na, be'a boe ladhe nèngu ad'u-ue ca madha j'ara, nga tao ka ja'a bebas boe sa hèi tao madhutu dad'èi d'ara ja'a, lula be'a boe bagi mi dhèu leo?<bt>Whereas in fact, I may eat according to my likes. But if another person thinks that it is not good for him to do something, why should I not be free to do according to my likes, just because that thing is not good for that other person?</bt><v n="30" />Ladhe ja'a manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, hèia ja'a ku'a, na, nga tao ka dhèu padhai pamanahu ja'a?<bt>If I give thanks to God, and then I eat, why should people talk making me fall/say bad things about me?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />De miu neo mi'a do, minu do, tao ngaa èèna ka, na, tao aa'i-aa'i sèna ka pakapai kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>So (consequently), if you-pl want to eat or, drink or, do whatever, na, do everything so you can honour God's name/reputation.</bt><v n="32" />Baku pasusa dhèu Yahudi, do dhèu Yahudi boe, do dhèu unu Lamatua dhu parcaya sèra.<bt>Don't make trouble for Yahudi people, or non Yahudi people, or God2's believers.</bt><v n="33" />Tao nuka sèmi ja'a tao. Te ja'a neo cob'a pakarej'e si ètu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i ra. Ja'a mesa boe tao dhu be'a hia ja'a di, te ngaa neo tao dhu be'a bagi rèngu aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka rèngu abhu sod'a kahèi.<bt>Do as I do. Cuz (elaboration) I keep trying to make them happy in everything. I don't just try to do what is good for me. But I try to do what is good for all of them, so they can also be saved2.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Miu ladhe mi ja'a, aa tao madhutu j'ara mamuri ja'a. Te ja'a ladhe mi Kristus, aa tao madhutu tatao Nèngu.<bt>You-pl look at me, and follow my way of life. Cuz (elaboration) I look at Kristus, and do according to/following His deeds/behaviour/character.</bt><note reference="11:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 4:16, Pilipi 3:17</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe tao ibadat, na, dhèu mone dènge dhèu bhèni hud'i pakab'ua ku madhutu atora ad'a<bt>If you do a worship.service, na, males and females must show respect according to the norms of adat (culture/customs)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ja'a koa-kad'iri miu, lula tasamia èèna ka miu sanèd'e taruu ja'a. Aa j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a aj'a-nori le miu, miu tao madhutu era. Be'a titu kèna!<bt>[EXEG: See Fee for whole section.] I praise (doublet) you-pl, because no matter what, you keep remembering me (=thinking of me). And all the things which I taught you, you are still doing accordingly. That's sooo good!</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa ca j'ara dhu ja'a neo pasanèd'e miu nuka: baku bhèlu j'aj'aj'i miu nèti mia. Dhèu mone dhu parcaya sèra, kèni na nèti Kristus, dhu j'aj'i Kètu ra. Dhèu bhèni j'aj'i nèti dhèu mone. Aa Kristus mai nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>But there is one thing that I want to remind/warn you of, that is: don't forget where your-pl origins/source are. Each man/male who believes, his keel (boat term for boat people; they key piece into which everything ties.) is from Kristus who is his head. Women originate from men. And Kristus came from God. [EXEG: Gk /kephale/ as source, not authority; see Fee, Nyland, Belzekian, CBE, etc.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèni "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 01:39:30Z" status="Anyone">lunas perahu, keel = source from which everything fits and emanates - island/boat people; works better than /kapua/ here.</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu d'èlu-mèu lii Yunani peka na, <span class="Italic">kefale </span>&lt;&lt;kapala&gt;&gt; sasoa na, 1) ngi'u unu kètu, dènge 2) j'aj'aj'i, kapua (sumber), kèni. Te ngaa lii Yunani, <span class="Italic">kefale</span> sasoa na, bukan &lt;&lt;dhèu rèd'u paredha&gt;&gt;.<bt>Experts in the Yunani language say, <span class="Italic">kefale</span> &lt;&lt;head&gt;&gt; means 1) head of a (physical) body, and 2) origin, root (source). But in the Yunani language <span class="Italic">kefale</span> does not mean &lt;&lt;person who rules&gt;&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Dhèu mone baku pahutu kètu na lod'o nèngu manèngi-mangaj'i, do, ropa na peka-padhai lii moa Lamatua. Te èèna sama sèmi nèngu pamakae Kristus, lula ne'a boe pakab'ua madhutu ad'a èdhi.<bt>A man should not cover his head when he is praying, or when he is telling/explaining God2's message. Cuz (elaboration) that is like he is shaming/bringing shame on Kristus, because he is not showing honour according to our-inc culture/custom norms.</bt><v n="5" />Te ngaa bhèni hud'i pahutu kètu na lod'o sabaj'a, do ropa nèngu lole lii moa Lamatua. Te ladhe aad'o na, èèna sama sèmi nèngu pamakae dhèu èmu na, lula ne'a boe pakab'ua madhutu ad'a èdhi. Aa nèngu pamakae ngi'u nèngu unu na, nuka sèmi dhèu bhèni dhu lusu pakahoni kètu na.<bt>But a woman must cover her head when she is praying2, or when she is telling God2's message. Cuz (elaboration) if not, na, that is like she is bringing shame on her spouse, because she is not showing honour according to our culture/custom norms. And she is also bringing shame on her own self, just like if/when a woman shaves her head bald.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lusu "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 01:48:04Z" status="Anyone">cukur (bekin polik)</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te ladhe abhu dhèu bhèni dhu d'èi boe pahutu kètu na, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha nèngu pakab'ua dhèu èmu na, be'a risi nèngu g'ute pabab'a rèu kètu na. Te ngaa ladhe nèngu rasa kètu na kahoni pamakae nèngu, hua iia nèngu pahutu kètu na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if there is a woman who doesn't want to cover her head as a sign, that, she shows honour to her husband, na, it would be better if she scissored her hair short. But if she feels her bald head would make her ashamed, it's just better for her to cover her head.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ngee sèku sèmi ne'e: dhèu mone parluu boe hutu kètu na, te Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i dhèu mone madhutu raropa Na. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu mone j'aj'i mi hua-hela dhu pad'elo dadedha Ama Lamatua. Aa dhèu bhèni kahèi j'aj'i mi hua-hela dhu pad'elo dadedha dhèu mone.<bt>Have a think about this: a man doesn't need to cover up his head, cuz (elaboration) God made man according to His model/pattern/type. That is why man is a product that shows/demonstrates God's glory (high-ness: several different UNS groups have equated this with Indonesian ‘glory’). And a woman is also a product which shows/demonstrates a man's glory/high-ness.</bt><note reference="11:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 1:26-27</note><v n="8" />Te lod'o Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i rai-haha ne, Na tao boe dhèu mone nèti dhèu bhèni. Te ngaa paj'aj'i dhèu bhèni nèti dhèu mone.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) when God made this world, He did not make man from woman. But He made woman from man.</bt><v n="9" />Aa Lamatua tao boe dhèu mone hia mi dhèu bhèni. Te ngaa Na pangèd'u dhèu bhèni mi dhèu mone.<bt>And God2 did not make man for woman. But He turned over/surrendered/gave woman to man.</bt><note reference="11:8-9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:18-19</note><v n="10" />De hua iia risi dhèu bhèni pahutu kètu ho dhèu re'a, na, nèngu pake hak na ho sabaj'a aa lole lii moa Lamatua, madhutu j'ara dhu lèke. Ana pajuu nèti sorga re'a sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>So (consequently), it is best/better for a woman to cover her head, so people know that she is using her right to pray and tell God2's message, according to what is right. Angels in heaven also know that. [EXEG choice: "as a sign of her authority to pray and prophecy" OR "as a sign that she is under someone's authority"; we take the first. See also CEV, NLT, NRSV take neutral line.]</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa ladhe rèngu pa'èki dènge Lamatua, bhèni dènge mone bisa boe èci-èci ka tao unu na.<bt>But if they are bound/linked with God2, females and males are not alone-alone themselves (are not independent of each other).</bt><v n="12" />Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i uuru ku dhèu mone. Hèia Na paj'aj'i dhèu bhèni nèti dhèu mone. Te ngaa èle èèna ka, dhèu bhèni ka dhu nara iisi dhèu mone. Aa Ama Lamatua ka dhu tao aa'i-aa'i, j'aj'i.<bt>God first made/created man. Then He made/created woman from man. But after that, the woman was the one who gave birth to men. And God is the one who made everything happen/ come into being.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Miu pangee sèku! Ladhe dhèu bhèni pahutu boe kètu ho sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua, madhutu a'abhu miu, na, be'a, do aad'o?<bt>So you should think about it! If a woman does not cover her head to pray to God, according to your-pl opinion, is that good, or not?</bt><v n="14" />Madhutu ad'a miu ètu kota Korintus, ladhe dhèu mone rèu kètu madhera, èèna pamakae nèngu, do?<bt>According to your adat/customs in the city of Korintus, if a man has long hair, does that bring shame on him, or (what)? [LEX: Gk. phýsis: nature (nowadays we would say "our culture"); see also Fee.]</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa bhèni dhu rèu kètu na madhera, be'a titu kèna, si? Lamatua hia ne rèu kètu madhera ho pa'abhe kab'a kètu na. Èèna ka dhu lèke mola-mola.<bt>But if a woman has long hair, that's really nice, right? God2 has given her long hair to protect her head. That's what is right. [NOTE: Last sentence is with reference to v.13-14 idea of natural and proper. This is good Rabbinic logic, but bad Greco-Roman logic.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhu loe boe pakarèi nèti j'ara ne'e, sanèd'e, te nèti ji'i dhu j'aj'i kètu juma'at, aa nèti juma'at-juma'at, ne'e ne dhu tema le j'aj'i ètu talora èdhi.<bt>But if there is someone who wants to keep arguing about this matter, remember that from us-exc who are congregational leaders, and from the various congregations, this is what is the norm among us.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku tao rupa-rupa ladhe ta'a ètu mei Lamatua<bt>Don't mess around when you are eating at God2's table (=communion) [CHECK if rupa-rupa here carries neg connot]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Limuri ne, ja'a neo padhai lii ca j'ara. Te ngaa lii ne koa-kad'iri boe miu. Te ropa miu pakaboko, miu tao boe j'ara dhu lèke, te ngaa miu asa tao maruru.<bt>Now, I am going to talk about another matter. But in this matter, I do not praise (doublet) you-pl. Cuz (elaboration) when you gather together, you are not doing according to what is right, but you are making things even worse/more chaotic.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Partama, dhu ja'a tadèngi, na, lod'o miu pakaboko tao kasasi, miu dhu mae-manyèla. Nèti lii dhu ja'a tadèngi sèra, tatu abhu cahag'e dhu lèke tare'a.<bt>First (loan), I have heard, that when you gather to have a worship.service, you are divided/split up (in factions). Some of what I have heard, surely has some truth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao kasasi"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 02:45:20Z" status="Anyone">bekin ibadat, includes all Kristen aliran, but not Islam (they mangaji)</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />(Mema, lula mamae-manyèla miu èèna ka, bisa te'a cee ka dhu tare'a-re'a nanene Lamatua èdhi, aa mia dhu nanene boe.)<bt>(Really, because of your-pl divisions, we can know who really listens to/obeys our Master, and who doesn't (want to) obey Him.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dokimoi Chap. 3:18?|i(19) (19) |rNRSV: Indeed,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z" status="Information">dokimoi Chap. 3:18?<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>NRSV: Indeed, there have to be factions among you, for only so will it become clear who among you are genuine.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te lod'o miu dhèu sarani pakaboko ho mi'a ètu mei Lamatua, miu hud'i sanèd'e ku mi Lamatua Yesus. Èèna ka dhu lèke. Te ngaa miu tao boe sèmi èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) when you Christians are gathered together to eat at God2's table, you must remember the Lord Yesus. That is what is right. But you are not doing that.</bt><v n="21" />Tadha na, nuka ropa miu madhèdi mi'a, abhu dhu mate boe dhèu leo, abhu dhu ra'a dènge gagoo, aa abhu leo dhu rinu mahu. Toke abhu dhèu cahag'e dhu abhu boe pala, ka ra manganga.<bt>The sign/evidence, is that when you are sitting and eating, there are those who don't wait for others, there are those who eat greedily, and there are others who drink (until) drunk. To the point that there are some people who don't get a share, so they are hungry.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagoo"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 02:54:35Z" status="Anyone">rakus</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Tasamia ka ne!? Miu dènge boe èmu ho mi'a-minu, do? Do, miu neo pa'ele iie kolongara juma'at Lamatua? Do, miu neo pamakae dhèu dhu unu aad'o sèra? Miu neo ja'a padhai lii tasamia hari? Neo sèna ka ja'a koa-kad'iri miu ètu d'ara tatao miu ne, do? Baku maena!<bt>How can this be!? Don't you have your own houses to eat-drink there, or (what)? Or, is your intention to ruin/damage the good name/reputation of God2's congregation/s? Or, are you wanting to shame the poor people? What do you want me to say? Do you want me to praise (doublet) you in your behaviour? Don't hope (=no way)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Roti dènge èi anggor èèna, j'aj'i mi tadha ho pasanèd'e èdhi nèti mamadhe Yesus<bt>That bread and the wine/grape juice, are signs that remind us-inc of Yesus' death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:26-29; Markus 14:22-25; Lukas 22:14-20)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lamatua Yesus ka dhu peka Unu na dènge ja'a j'ara ne, de ja'a peka hari dènge miu. Peka na, ropa dhèu pa'èra neo pamadhe Ne, mèda èèna Nèngu nare roti cue.<bt>The Lord Yesus himself is the one who told/made known this matter to me directly, so (consequently) I am telling it again/further to you. That, when people were preparing to kill Him, that night He took a (loaf of) bread. [NOTE: many commentators feels the wording of this verse is evidence of a very early creed in widespread circulation among Christians predating the writing of the gospels (which were written after most of Paul's letters. So the idea of passing on something he has received with authority needs to be clear.]</bt><v n="24" />Hèia Na sabaj'a manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mi'a roti ne, te ne'e ne ngi'u Ja'a, dhu mae hia miu. De miu hud'i mi'a roti ne, sèna ka sanèd'e Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He prayed giving thanks to God. Then2 Yesus told His *disciples (followers), saying, &lt;&lt;Eat this bread, cuz (elaboration) this is My body, which is broken/destroyed for you-pl. So (consequently) you must eat this bread so that you remember Me.&gt;&gt; [CHECK UNS if pamae can collocate with ngi'u]</bt><v n="25" />Ropa ra'a rare, Na tao sèmi èèna kahèi dènge galaa dhu isi èi anggor, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èi anggor ne, sasoa na, Ama Lamatua neo pa'èki lii padhadha hiu dènge miu. Ka Ja'a hud'i pasuti raa Ja'a toke madhe, heka lii padhadha èèna j'aj'i. Lod'o-lod'o miu minu èi anggor sèmi ne'e, miu hud'i ngee mèdhi ku mamadhe Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they had finished eating, He also did the same with a glass of wine/grape juice, saying, &lt;&lt;This wine means, that God is going to bind a new promise with you. And I must spill my blood (phrasing implies: for a cause) to the point that I die first, only.then will that promise happen/come into effect. Each time you drink this wine like this, you must remember My death.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="11:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 24:6-8, Yermia 31:31-34</note><v n="26" />Lod'o-lod'o miu tao j'ara sèmi ne'e, ho mi'a roti dènge minu nèti galaa sèmi ne'e, toke Kristus lèpa hari mai, èèna nuka sèmi miu palolo hari mamadhe Na.<bt>Each time you do like this to eat bread this way and drink from the glass this way, until Kristus comes back, that is like you are retelling about His death. [EXEG: who is speaking here? Jesus (referring to himself in third person as He so often does), or Paul commenting on it? The fact that at least 8 commentators actually address the issue means it's not black and white (even though they all favour Paul, see Ex. Summ.). The shift from 1s in vs.24-25 to 3s in vs.26 also favours Paul. All but one version consulted, and all commentators close the quote at the end of 25. This was queried/challenged by a couple of our MTT teams, so it's likely we're asking for trouble if we maintain the more poorly supported idea of taking the quote through 26, instead of ending it at 25. Revised.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe d'ara èu mola boe, na, baku madhèdi mu'a ètu mei Lamatua<bt>If your insides are not straight/right, na, don't sit and eat at God2's table</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Nèti èèna ka, lod'o dhèu ra'a roti dènge rinu nèti galaa èèna, sèna ka sanèd'e Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu d'ara na mola boe dènge dhèu leo, èèna na Ama Lamatua huku ne. Lula, èèna ngi'u dènge raa nèti Lamatua Yesus. De ladhe d'ara dhu mola mèka, na, nèngu nia boe na'a dènge ninu, lula j'ara èèna pahahe Lamatua Yesus.<bt>Because of that, when people are eating that bread and drinking from that glass to remember our Head, Yesus Kristus, but there is a person whose insides are not straight/right, God will punish him. Because, that is the Lord Yesus' body and blood. So (consequently) if a person's insides are not yet straight/right, na, it is not appropriate for him/he is not worthy to eat and drink there, because that is treating the Lord Yesus with contempt.</bt><v n="28" />Be'a risi ca dhèu-dhèu ka parisa uuru ku d'ara na. Ladhe d'ara na dhu mola le, heka bisa na'a roti aa ninu èi anggor kèna.<bt>It is better for each person to first examine his own insides. If s/he is sure that his insides are straight/right/honest, only.then can s/he eat that bread and drink that wine.</bt><v n="29" />Te ngaa abhu dhu ra'a dènge rinu dhu d'ara ra koe-kapengo. Te ra pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Mamadhe Yesus èèna, dènge boe kab'ua. Ngi'u Yesus dènge boe sasoa bagi mi ja'a.&gt;&gt; Dhèu sèmi se'e se, bèli-camèd'a dui rare pala ra, lula hahuku dhu sadia tèke le.<bt>But there are those who eat and drink with insides that are not crooked (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) they think, that, &lt;&lt;That death of Yesus', has no value/significance whatsoever. Yesus' body has no meaning for me.&gt;&gt; People like that bear/are responsible for their own risk, because punishment is ready/prepared for them.</bt><v n="30" />Nèti èèna ka, ètu talora aae miu sèra, abhu dhu èra boe, abhu dhu lèke papèd'a-tarègu, aa abhu dhu madhe le.<bt>That is why among you there, there are those who are not strong, there are those who are sickly (doublet), and there are those who have died.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi parisa paie-iie d'ara èdhi, èdhi abhu boe huku sèmi sèra.<bt>But if we examine carefully our insides first, we-inc do will not be punished like that.</bt><v n="32" />Ladhe Lamatua èdhi huku èdhi, Na tao sèmi èèna sèna ka aj'a-nori èdhi ho èdhi madhutu j'ara dhu lèke. Te Nèngu d'èi boe ladhe èdhi lèke huku sama sèmi dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>If our-inc Master punishes us, He does that to teach us to follow the right path. Cuz (elaboration) He doesn't want us to get punished, together with everyone (else) on this earth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />De a'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ladhe miu pakaboko ho mi'a-minu ètu mei Lamatua, èci hud'i mate ku èci.<bt>So (consequently), dear siblings! If/when you are gathered together at God2's table, one must wait for the other.</bt><v n="34" />Ladhe abhu dhu taha boe manganga, be'a risi mi'a uuru ku ètu èmu, sèna ka ropa miu pakaboko pa'èci, baku abhu dhu lèke huku.<bt>If there is someone who cannot restrain their hunger, it would be better to eat a bit at home first, so that when you are gathered together, you will not get punished.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">J'ara leo dhu miu karèi sèra, pe ja'a dhiu ku, heka ator si kèna.<bt>Regarding other matters/disputes which you have asked about, later when I come to visit, only.then will I handle them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Roh Lamatua pangèd'u koasa mi èdhi sèna ka tao rupa-rupa sasab'a-la'a<bt>God2's Spirit gives power to us-inc to do various sorts of jobs/responsibilities</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Dad'èi ja'a ka ladhe miu me'a mèu nèti koasa dènge karunya dhu Roh Lamatua pangèd'u mi èdhi, sèna ka èdhi pake.<bt>Dear siblings! I want you to understand about those power/s and unique.gifting/s (loan) which God2's Spirit has given/handed out to us-inc for us to use.</bt><v n="2" />Miu dhu me'a, na, lod'o miu dhae j'aj'i mèka dhèu unu Lamatua, miu sogo-tagu mèdha dhu lii aad'o sèra. Miu madhutu rèngu iia-iia d'ara.<bt>You-pl know that when you were not yet God2's people, you used to trad.worship various things that were dumb (unable to speak). You followed/obeyed them blindly/thoughtlessly.</bt><v n="3" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a neo ho miu me'a, na, tatu boe abhu dhèu dhu pa'èki dènge Roh Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhoo-saseo Yesus èèna!&gt;&gt; Aa tatu dhèu dhu pa'èki boe dènge Roh Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus èèna, Lamatua ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, I want for you to understand that, it is surely not possible for a person who is bound/linked to God's Holy Spirit to say, &lt;&lt;Curses (doublet) to Yesus!&gt;&gt; And surely it is not possible that there is someone who is not bound with God's Holy Spirit who says, &lt;&lt;Yesus [+known info] is my Master!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Roh Lamatua hia mi dhèu èci-èci ka dènge karunya na, sèna ka èci-èci dènge sasab'a-la'a ra. Te ngaa karunya sèra mai nèti Roh èci di.<bt>God's Spirit has given each person his/her own unique.gifting, so they carry out each of their different jobs/responsibilities. But (all) those unique.giftings, come from the same/one Spirit.</bt><v n="5" />Dhèu abhu karunya rupa-rupa ho lalau-lalo'o dhèu leo, te ngaa rèngu nanene dhoka Lamatua èci di.<bt>People get various sorts of unique.giftings to serve (doublet) people, but [contrary to expectation] they only hear/obey the same/one Master.</bt><v n="6" />Dhèu unu rupa-rupa sasab'a sèna ka pakako sasab'a Lamatua, èèna j'aj'i lula Ama Lamatua di dhu soru-bara rèngu ho ra pakako sasab'a-la'a sèra aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>People get/have various jobs/responsibilities to carry out God2's work, because God is the one who helps (doublet) them to carry out all those jobs.</bt><v n="7" />Ama Lamatua pad'elo Roh Na mi mamuri dhèu dènge j'ara dhu baka-leo hua, te ngaa dad'èi Na sèna ka aa'i-aa'i ra sama-sama abhu babe'a.<bt>God2 shows/demonstrates His Spirit in each person's life in different ways (distributive), but the purpose/intention is for all to get goodness/benefit/advantage together.</bt><v n="8" />Lamatua pangèd'u koasa Roh Na mi dhèu unu Na. Ka cahag'e abhu koasa, sèna ka ngangee madhera ho nori dhu lèke. Cahag'e abhu koasa ho peka paled'a ngaa dhu rèngu re'a dènge be'a.<bt>He gives His Spirit's power/authority to His people. Some receive power so they can think long (wise, implications), and so give advice which fits (the situation). Some receive power to tell/explain clearly what it is they understand.</bt><v n="9" />Cahag'e hari abhu koasa sèna ka parcaya pa'èra mi Ama Lamatua, lula rèngu dhu pa'èki pa'èra dènge Roh Na. Cahag'e hari abhu koasa ho puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a.<bt>Some others receive power to believe strongly in God, because they are bound/linked tightly with His Spirit. Some others receive power to heal (doublet) sick people.</bt><v n="10" />Cahag'e hari abhu koasa sèna ka tao tadha-tadha malaa dhu pad'elo dadedha Ama Lamatua. Cahag'e hari lole lii moa Lamatua mi dhèu unu Na. Cahag'e abhu koasa sèna ka re'a, roh mia ka mai nèti Ama Lamatua, aa mia ka dhu aad'o. Cahag'e hari, abhu koasa ho bisa padhai lii pake lii leo. Aa cahag'e hari, bisa peka sasoa nèti lii sèra.<bt>Some others receive power to do various sorts of *miracles (amazing signs) which show God's glory/high-ness. Some others receive power to tell God's message to His people. Some others receive power to be able to know which (of options) spirit is rooted in God, and which are not. Some others receive power so they can speak using various different/other languages. [EXEG: Ex. Summaries, #4, keeps the options open, as in the Gk.] Some others, receive power to tell/explain what those languages/messages/words means.</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa dhodhoka Roh èci di dhu bisa tao rèngu, sèna ka bisa pakako sasab'a-la'a ra. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu pangèd'u mi dhèu èci-èci, ka rèngu bisa sab'a madhutu dad'èi Roh Lamatua èèna.<bt>But there is only one Spirit who makes it so they/enables them all can do those job/responsibilities (indirect causation). He is the one who gives to each person so they are able to work according to God2's Spirit's will.</bt><note reference="12:4-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Roma 12:6-8</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ngi'u èci, te ngaa bagian na ae-ae<bt>One body, and its many parts (loan)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ja'a neo pasoro karunya sèra dènge ngi'u dhèu. Ngi'u èci, te ngaa bagian na ae-ae. Te ngaa bagian se, pa'èki j'aj'i ngi'u èci di.<bt>I want to compare those unique.giftings with a person's body. One body has many parts. But those (various) parts are linked as just one body. [NOTE: karunya for higher level cohesion with previous section.]</bt><note reference="12:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Roma 12:4-5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ne'e nuka sèmi dhèu unu Kristus sèra.<bt>That is the same as Kristus' people.</bt><v n="13" />Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti pa'èki dènge Roh èci di. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o èdhi abhu sarani, èdhi nuka sèmi ca suku. Masi ka èdhi dhèu Yahudi, do dhèu Yahudi boe, ènu do dhèu bebas, Ama Lamatua pala hia èdhi Roh èci di. Èèna nuka sèmi tinu èi dhu hia mamuri nèti madha èi èci di.<bt>We-inc are all linked with one Spirit. That is why when we were baptised, we became like one race/tribe/people group. Even though/whether we-inc are Yahudi people or non Yahudi people, slaves or free (loan) people, God distributes/gives us all the one/same Spirit. That is like we all drink water that gives life from the same well. [Nyland: The Source]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Tare'a, ngi'u ne nèti boe ca bagian di. Te na j'aj'i nèti bagian ae-ae.<bt>It is true that the body is not just from one part. Cuz (elaboration) it happens/comes to be from many parts.</bt><v n="15" />Ladhe sèmi haga èu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, kacui-aai boe. De ja'a j'aj'i boe bagian nèti ngi'u èu.&gt;&gt; Masi ka nèngu peka sèmi èèna, te ngaa nèngu j'aj'i bagian nèti ngi'u èu era. Tare'a, si?<bt>If perchance [hypothetical] your-sg foot said, &lt;&lt;I here, am not a hand. So (consequently), I am not a part of your body.&gt;&gt; Even if it spoke like that, nevertheless it is still a part of your body. That's correct, right?</bt><v n="16" />Aa ladhe dhilu èu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, musi madha boe. De ja'a ne j'aj'i boe bagian nèti ngi'u èu.&gt;&gt; Masi ka na peka sèmi èèna, te ngaa nèngu bagian nèti ngi'u èu kahèi.<bt>And if your ear said, &lt;&lt;I here, am not an eye. So (consequently), I am not a part of your body.&gt;&gt; Even if it spoke like that, nevertheless it is still a part of your body.</bt><v n="17" />Pangee sèku! Ladhe ngi'u èu dhoka musi madha di, tasamia èu bisa tadèngi? Aa ladhe ngi'u èu dhoka rèu dhilu di, tasamia ho èu bisa sangèd'u?<bt>Have a think! If your body was only an eyeball, how is it that you would be able to hear? And if your body was only an ear, how is it that you would be able to smell?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa miu me'a le, Ama Lamatua tao èdhi j'aj'i mi èci sama sèmi ngi'u èci, ka Nèngu ator bagian se madhutu dad'èi Na.<bt>But you already know, God makes us become like one body, and He arranges/regulates/controls each of the parts, according to His desires.</bt><v n="19" />Ladhe ngi'u ne dhoka ca bagian di, ngara na &lt;ngi'u&gt; boe, sina ma?<bt>If our-inc bodies were only one part, it's name is no longer &lt;body&gt;, right?</bt><v n="20" />Te dhu lèke ka, ngi'u èdhi ne, dènge bagian ae-ae. Se'e ka tao ne j'aj'i ngi'u kateme aae.<bt>But in truth, our bodies have many various parts. That is what makes it be one whole body.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Musi madha bisa boe pahahe kacui-aai, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a parluu boe èu!&gt;&gt; Aa kètu bisa boe peka dènge haga na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dale boe èu!&gt;&gt;<bt>An eyeball cannot view disparagingly/condescendingly a hand, saying, &lt;&lt;I don't need you-sg!&gt;&gt; And a head can't tell a foot, saying, &lt;&lt;I don't need2 you!&gt;&gt; [NOTE: high level speaker attitude from Fee &amp; Ex. Summ, plus context.]</bt><v n="22" />Dhu lèke mola-mola ka, nuka, abhu bagian nèti ngi'u dhu roe, aa dhu dènge kab'ua ae boe, te ngaa èdhi parluu rèngu kahèi.<bt>What is true, is that, there are parts of the body which we-inc consider/view weak and without much value/significance, but we still need them.</bt><v n="23" />Abhu bagian dhu èdhi pangee, na, rèngu se gaguna ra ae boe, te ngaa èdhi haduli si paie-iie. Aa abhu bagian dhu èdhi makae pacèu, ka pahutu pabe'a-be'a.<bt>There are parts that we consider/view as not having much use, but we still care for them well. And there are parts which we are embarrased to display, so we cover them up carefully.</bt><v n="24" />Te ngaa bagian dhu pamakae boe èdhi, èdhi tao boe si ngaa-ngaa.<bt>But if there is a part which doesn't make us ashamed, we don't do anything to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Ama Lamatua oru nare bagian aa'i-aa'i se ho j'aj'i mi ngi'u èci. Ka Nèngu ator sèna ka bagian dhu èdhi pangee, na, dhu dènge boe kab'ua, èdhi ladhe-leru si be'a-be'a,<bt>But God has gathered/collected all the parts to make one body. And/So He has arranged so the parts which we consider without value/ significance, we also care for (doublet) them well,</bt><v n="25" />te Lamatua d'èi boe ngi'u èdhi pahag'a. Dad'èi Na sèna ka bagian se èci soru-bara èci.<bt>cuz (elaboration) He doesn't like our bodies to be split up/separated (into unconnected parts). He wants for all parts, one to mutually help (doublet) each other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paloa-padui"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-10 04:35:21Z" status="Anyone">bertengkar</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ladhe bagian èci paraga dènge susa, na, aa'i-aa'i ra susa kahèi. Aa ladhe ra pakab'ua èci, na, aa'i-aa'i karej'e kahèi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if one part gets/ encounters trouble, na, all (the rest) also feel/experience trouble. And if one is receiving honour/respect, na, all (the rest) also are happy too.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èci èèna ka dènge miu. Te miu sama sèmi ngi'u Kristus dhu kateme. Dhèu parcaya èci-èci nuka sèmi ca bagian nèti ngi'u Kristus.<bt>It is the same way also with you. Cuz (elaboration) you-pl are like Kristus' whole body. Each believing person is like one part of Kristus' body.</bt><v n="28" />Te ètu talora miu dhèu parcaya, Ama Lamatua hia koasa sèna ka pakako rupa-rupa sasab'a, nuka:<bt>Cuz (elaboration) in the midst of you believers, God gives power/authority to carry out various sorts of tasks/ responsibilities.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Partama, Lamatua pua-paleha dhèu cahag'e ho lasi lole lii moa Na.<bt>First (loan), He commissions (doublet) some people to go tell His message.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka dua, Na pake dhèu cahag'e, j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Nèngu.<bt>Second, He uses some people as His *prophets (spokespeople).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ka tèlu, Na hia dhèu cahag'e d'èlu-mèu ho aj'a-nori dhèu leo lula-nèti Nèngu.<bt>Third, He makes some people skilled in teaching people about Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Na hia koasa mi dhèu cahag'e, sèna ka bisa tao tadha-tadha malaa ho pad'elo dadedha Na.<bt>Then, He gives power to some people so they can do various sorts of miracles to show His glory/high-ness.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Cahag'e hari abhu koasa ho puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a.<bt>Some others get power to heal (doublet) sick people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Cahag'e hari abhu karunya ho soru-bara dhèu.<bt>Some others get unique.gifting to help (doublet) people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Cahag'e hari abhu karunya sèna ka uri dhèu ho sab'a sama-sama dènge be'a.<bt>Some others get unique.gifting to manage/ organise people so they can work together well.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Lamatua pangèd'u koasa mi dhèu cahag'e hari, ho bisa padhai pake rupa-rupa lii.<bt>And God2 gives2 power to some other people, so they can speak using various sorts of languages. [LEX: Gk. génee gloossóon: see note on Verse 10]</bt><note reference="12:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Epesus 4:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />De ngangee miu tasamia? Ama Lamatua pua dhèu aa'i-aa'i ho lasi peka-padhai lii moa Na, do? Aad'o. Na hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i mi dhèu rèti lii padhai Na, do? Aad'o. Na hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i d'èlu-mèu ho aj'a-nori, do? Aad'o. Na hia koasa mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka tao tadha-tadha malaa, do? Aad'o.<bt>So (consequently) what are you-pl thinking? Does God commission everyone to go tell His message, or (what)? No. Does He make everyone become His spokesperson, or (what)? No. Does He make everyone skilled in teaching, or (what)? No. Does He give power to everyone so they can do miracles, or (what)? No.</bt><v n="30" />Na hia koasa mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i sèna ka puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a, do? Aad'o. Na hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i ho bisa padhai pake rupa-rupa lii, do? Aad'o. Na hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i, ho bisa bhoke paled'a sasoa nèti lii se'e, do? Aad'o.<bt>Does He give power to everyone so they can heal (doublet) sick people, or (what)? No. Does He make everyone able to speak using various languages, or (what)? No. Does He make everyone able to reveal the meaning of those languages, or (what)? No.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />De miu hud'i bori mema-mema ho sèmi mere aa pake karunya dènge be'a dhu hia gaguna mi dhèu ae.<bt>So, You-pl must be prepared to receive and use the unique.giftings which are useful for many people. [EXEG: Ex. Summ: they can have an earnest desire for them and prepare themselves to receive them; collectively, not individually]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa ja'a neo pad'elo j'ara dhu hua iia risi hia miu.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless I still want to show you-pl a way that is better/the best.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sasue dhu lèke<bt>True love/Love that is right/correct/appropriate</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Ladhe sèmi ja'a bisa padhai lii pake lii aa'i-aa'i, nèti dhèu rai-haha do, lii nèti ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga, te ngaa dènge boe sasue ciki sa ètu d'ara ja'a, kolo-karisi na ngaa? Lii padhai ja'a sèra mola mèu lao, sama sèmi babha dhu lii cère-cère, do nuka sèmi dere dhu lii dhèru-dhèru di.<bt>If perchance (hypothetical) I could speak using all kinds of languages, from humans or, language from God2's angels, but I don't have even a little love in my insides, what good/benefit/advantage (doublet) is it? What I have to say is just empty (idiom), like a gong that just keeps cère-cère (clanging), or a barrel/drum that just sounds dhèru-dhèru (low pitched ring).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mola mèu lao"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 00:55:33Z" status="Anyone">kosong malompo ; babha = gong ; Sound = cère-cère ; dere = tambur ; domu-domu = bunyi tambur ; dhèru-dhèru = bunyi bas</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ladhe sèmi ja'a dènge karunya ho lole peka lii moa Lamatua mi dhèu unu Na, aa dhu ke'a aa'i rahasia, dènge ke'a aa'i j'ara-j'ara dhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu se re'a, aa ladhe lalèka ja'a èra mi Lamatua toke ja'a bisa pahari eele ledhe nèti era na, te ngaa ja'a dènge boe sasue ciki sa, na, gaguna na ngaa? Rui-j'aj'èra ja'a guna boe mi ngaa èci sa.<bt>If perchance I had a unique.gifting to tell God2's message to His people, and I knew all secrets, and I understood everything that knowledgeable people know, and if my faith in God2 is strong to the point that I am able to move a mountain from its place, but I don't have even a little love, what use is it? My efforts have no use whatsoever.</bt><note reference="13:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 17:20, 21:21, Markus 11:23</note><v n="3" />Ladhe ja'a pahie eele aa'i mèdha-panyau ja'a, ho sèna ka kab'ua ra panga'a dhèu unu aad'o, do, soro ngi'u ja'a sèna ka j'aj'i mi korban,<bt>If I sell off all my belongings, and then divide up all its money to give food to the poor people, or hand over/surrender my body as a sacrifice,</bt><note reference="13:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu sasuri lii Yunani, cahag'e dhu suri tabha, peka na, &lt;&lt;soro ngi'u ja'a j'aj'i mi korban tunu&gt;&gt;.<bt>There are some Yunani language writings which write additionally, saying, “hand over/surrender my body as a burnt sacrifice,”</bt></note>te ngaa ladhe ja'a dènge boe sasue ciki sa, gaguna na ngaa? Ja'a dènge boe j'ara dhu tao ja'a nged'e. Te sèra sa parcuma! Guna boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>but I don't have even a little love, what use is it? I have no way/basis/reason for boasting. Cuz (elaboration) it's pointless/in vain! There is no benefit/advantage.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="4" />Te sasue èèna, d'ara taleo.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) love is patient (wide insides). [DISCOURSE: Reordered so first point is broader]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, lii mako.<bt>Love is love is kind in speech. [Includes actions as well as words.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, d'ara kura boe.<bt>Love is not jealous (insides lacking toward s.o.).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, padedha boe iisi.<bt>Love does not elevate itself/boast.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, pamone-pabhèni boe.<bt>Love is not arrogant (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="5" />Sasue èèna, lii sakaa boe.<bt>Love is not coarse/ rude/ crude. [CHECK if better term that includes actions as well as words.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, neo boe pasegi ngi'u unu na.<bt>Love doesn't want/try to win themselves (insist on its own way).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, nasa malai boe.<bt>Love does not get mad quickly/easily.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, tèka boe d'ara.<bt>Love does not store liver (resentment/hate).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="6" />Sasue èèna, karej'e dènge ngaa dhu lèke,<bt>Love is happy/pleased with what is right,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa d'èi boe bia ca bèka.<bt>and doesn't like things that are not just/fair (heavy on one side).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="7" />Sasue èèna, taha taruu ètu d'ara madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Love endures in all circumstances.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, parcaya taruu.<bt>Love keeps trusting/ believing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, sanao-maena taruu.<bt>Love keeps hoping (doublet). [NOTE to daughter translations: even in Kupang, /baharap/ usually has to be fleshed out with a direct (e.g. hoping for the best in the other) or indirect object; here it works because of the structure of the context, but probably wouldn't if it was removed from context. Check your language carefully.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasue èèna, ma'ète boe.<bt>Love keeps lasting (does not break-something that continues lengthwise, including time).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="8" />Sasue dènge boe too-lane.<bt>Love is without a boundary.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te, ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua peka le, nèbhu-nèbhu parluu heka. Aa dhu dhèu padhai pake lii rupa-rupa, bèli-camèd'a parluu heka kahèi. Aa ladhe ngaa dhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra re'a, nèbhu-nèbhu guna heka kahèi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration), what the things that God2's spokespeople made known, will eventually not be needed anymore. And if a person speaks using various kinds of languages, eventually they won't be needed anymore either. And as for the things that knowledgable people know, eventually they will have no more use.</bt><v n="9" />Limuri ne dhu te'a dhoka ciki oo'e di. Aa ladhe èdhi j'aj'i dhèu tèti lii padhai Lamatua, èdhi peka dhoka j'ara dhu dhae tesa mèka.<bt>Now, we only understand a little. If we are God2's spokespeople, we only make known things which are not yet complete.</bt><v n="10" />Te ngaa ropa d'ai ka lod'o na, aa'i-aa'i sèra tesa dhe'i-dhe'i. Lod'o èèna j'ara-j'ara dhu tesa mèka, guna heka mi ngaa èci sa.<bt>But when it comes to the right/appropriate time, everything will become complete. At that time, things that are not complete, will also not have use anymore. [NOTE: needs to make sense in conjunction w/vs.11ff]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tesa dhe'i-dhe'i= tesa aa'i mèu-mèu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z">tesa dhe'i-dhe'i= tesa aa'i mèu-mèu = lengkap</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tesa dhe'i-dhe'i"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 01:40:09Z" status="Anyone">fully complete</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Conto sèmi: lod'o ja'a ana iiki era, ja'a padhai lii sama sèmi ana iiki. Ngangee ja'a sama sèmi mia dhu ana iiki pangee. Te ngaa limuri ne, ja'a dhèu ee'a le. Nèti èèna ka, tatao ja'a sèmi heka ana iiki.<bt>An example is like this: when I was still a small child, I spoke like small children. I also thought like small children normally think. But now I am an adult. That is why I don't behave like a small child anymore.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tatao ja'a sèmi heka ana iiki."><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2010-11-04 02:01:59Z" status="Anyone">Baby talk, /r/ goes to /l/</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Conto leo: limuri ne, èdhi tèdhi rango-rango era, dhae mèu iia mèka, nuka sèmi èdhi ladhe asa d'ara tèru dhu ahu. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu pe aa'i-aa'i se mèu aadha-aadha, nuka sèmi èdhi ladhe padètu iiki-iiki ètu madha èdhi. Ne'e ne, ja'a ke'a dhoka ciki di. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu bisa ke'a aa'i, nuka sèmi Ama Lamatua ladhe madhore d'ai adhe-usu ja'a.<bt>Another example: now, we-inc are able to see a little, but (things are) not clear, just like looking using a broken mirror. But eventually everything will become very clear (idiomatic). We will be able to see just like it is right in front of us. Now I only understand a little. But eventually I will be able to understand everything, just like God understands everything about my being/situation (idiomatic).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèdhi rango-rango"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 01:44:38Z" status="Anyone">suram, kabur-kabur</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhe madhore"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 01:49:09Z" status="Anyone">lia tembus ; adhe-usu = hati-jantung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />De limuri ne, abhu tèlu j'ara dhu èdhi hud'i tao, dhu taha taruu. Nuka:<bt>So (consequently), there are three things which we must do, which keep lasting. They are:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èdhi hud'i parcaya taruu Lamatua;<bt>we-inc must keep believing in God2;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èdhi sanao-maena taruu, na, pe Lamatua ator aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i be'a;<bt>we must keep hoping, that, He will arrange everything to (eventually) come out good/well; (indirect causation) [NOTE to daughter translations: we UNSed this stopping at /baharap tarús/; UNS's said "hope we get things /barang/"; problem is in Kupang and most lgs in Timor/Maluku, /baharap/ or its equivalent normally needs a direct object (believe what) or indirect object (believe in who); this explication is similar to HCE but adds God in an agentive role. Don't overtranslate this well-known passage if the lg or UNS responses don't require it.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa èdhi hud'i pasue taruu.<bt>and we must keep loving (each other).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nèti tèlu j'ara se, dhu dedha risi ka, <span class="Italic">sasue. </span>Lula sasue ka dhu hua risi nèti aa'i-aa'i.<bt>From these three things here, the most important one is <span class="Italic">love</span>. Cuz (elaboration) love is the best of all.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Roh Lamatua hia mi dhèu unu Na, sasab'a ra baka-leo<bt>God2's Spirit gives His people various different job/responsibilities</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Tenge j'ara sèna ka pasue ètu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i ra. Te abhu heka j'ara leo dhu dedha risi. Aa tenge j'ara kahèi, sèna ka Roh Lamatua hia miu koasa dènge karunya, ho bisa tao j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a. Aa dhu be'a, nuka, ladhe miu abhu karunya sèna ka lole lii moa Lamatua.<bt>Make an effort to mutually love in all matters. Cuz (elaboration) there is nothing else which is more important/higher. And also look for ways so God2's Spirit gives you-pl power and unique.gifting so you can do good things. And what is better/best, is, if you get unique.gifting to tell God2's message.</bt><v n="2" />Te ladhe dhèu dhu abhu karunya ho padhai lii pake lii leo, Roh Lamatua hia ne koasa sèna ka peka paled'a j'ara dhu mèu iia mèka. Te ngaa nèngu padhai lii boe dènge dhèu leo, te padhai lii dhoka dènge Lamatua di. Dhèu dhu pa'èci dènge ne ètu sèra, abhu boe èci sa dhu re'a lii padhai nèngu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration), if a person has a unique.gifting to speak using other language(s), God2's Spirit has/is giving him power to tell/explain/make known/clear2 things that are not yet clear1. [NOTE: &lt;other languages&gt; tests w/UNSs as working for other human languages, or what they call &lt;spirit language&gt;.] But he doesn't speak with other people, cuz (elaboration) he is only speaking with God2. There is nobody gathered/joined there who understands what s/he is saying.</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu abhu karunya ho lole lii moa Lamatua, na, nèngu peka lii moa ne mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu sèra. Nèngu pa'èra ku parcaya dhèu mi Lamatua, pa'èra d'ara dhèu, aa pakarej'e d'ara dhèu susa.<bt>But if a person has a unique.gifting to tell God2's message, s/he is giving the message to all the people there. He is building/strengthening people's faith in God2, strengthening/encouraging their livers, and comforting those in difficulty/strife.</bt><v n="4" />Dhèu dhu padhai lii pake lii leo, nèngu pa'èra dhoka ngi'u nèngu mesa na di. Te ngaa dhèu dhu padhue-padhai lii moa Lamatua èèna, nèngu pa'èra dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pakaboko dènge ne, sèna ka juma'at kateme asa tabha èra.<bt>A person who speaks using other languages, he just strengthens himself (alone). But a person who speaks telling/explaining God2's message, he strengthens everyone who is gathered with him, so the whole congregation becomes stronger.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Dad'èi ja'a, ladhe dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa padhai lii pake lii leo. Te ngaa ja'a d'èi risi, ladhe miu bisa lole lii moa Lamatua. Te dhèu dhu peka lii moa Lamatua èèna, guna risi nèti dhèu dhu dhoka padhai pake lii leo di. Ladhe padhai pake lii leo, èèna be'a, sad'i abhu dhèu dhu bisa peka paled'a sasoa na. Dènge sèmi èèna, lii moa sèra bisa asa pa'èra dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu juma'at, sèna ka re'a mèu.<bt>My liking/will is for all of you to be able to speak in other languages. But I would like it even better/more for you to be able to speak telling/explaining God2's message. Cuz (elaboration) the person who is telling God2's message, is more useful than the person who is merely speaking using other languages. If (we) speak using other languages, that is good, as long as there is a person who can tell openly/explain its meaning. In that way, that message can strengthen everyone in the congregation, so they can understand. [NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Pangee sèku j'ara ne. Ladhe sèmi ja'a dhiu ngad'o miu ho padhai pake lii dhu miu me'a boe sasoa na, miu abhu oto na ngaa? Aad'o, si? Te ngaa ladhe ja'a padhai lii dènge miu, be'a risi ja'a peka dènge miu dad'èi Lamatua. Be'a risi ja'a bhoke paled'a j'ara-j'ara dhu uru èèna mèu iia mèka. Be'a risi ja'a aj'a-nori miu ho me'a mèu risi hari j'ara sèra. Be'a risi ja'a pasanèd'e miu Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua. Be'a risi aj'a-nori miu. Dènge j'ara sèmi sèra, heka miu abhu oto kèna, si?<bt>Dear siblings! Have a think about these things. If perchance [hypothetical] I come to (visit) you, and I speak using a language that you don't understand it's meaning, what benefit/advantage do you get? There isn't any, right? But if I speak to you-pl, it is better if I tell/explain God2's will. It is better if I reveal things that were previously not clear. It is better if I teach you to understand things even better. It is better if I remind you about God2's Words/Sayings. It is better if I teach you. In that way, only then is it useful/beneficial for you, right? [NOTE: verse on effective communication.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge alat musiik. Se'e se mèdha madhe, te ngaa lii ra rupa-rupa. Pake sakino do, sasadhu do, gitar do, ladhe pangèci boe lii na, tatu dhèu re'a boe lii sod'a sèmi ngaa, si?<bt>It's also like that with musical instruments. They are not alive, but they are making various sorts of noises. Whether (you) are using a flute or, sasando [local stringed instrument] or, guitar (loan) or (whatever), if its note does not change/adjust, people will certainly not be able to know which song it is playing, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="para'u"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 02:12:04Z" status="Anyone">sonde tarator, sembarangan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèci"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 02:16:07Z" status="Anyone">= stel (with fingers)</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ladhe lii tèbhe mèu iia boe, na, tasa mera mia sordad'u bisa re'a, na, rèngu hud'i tao ngaa mi musu ra? Bisa boe, si?<bt>And if a trumpet/conch makes a sound that is not clear, how will the soldiers be able to know what they must do to their enemies? They can't, right?</bt><v n="9" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge miu. Ladhe miu padhai lii, pake lii dhu dhèu bisa boe re'a mèu, èèna nuka sèmi miu padhai lii dènge lai ngèlu. Parcuma, te dhèu bisa boe dhane rare lii padhai èu!<bt>It's the same way also with you-pl. If you speak, or use a language/words/speech that people cannot understand clearly, that is like you are just speaking with the wind. It's pointless/useless/in vain, cuz (elaboration) people can't catch your intent/purpose/meaning!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhane "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 02:47:12Z" status="Anyone">tangkap, tanggapi; padhane = kubur</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ètu rai-haha ne abhu lii ae titu kèna. Lii se, èci-èci ka dènge sasoa na.<bt>There are too many/so many kinds of languages in this world. Each language has its own (individual) meaning.</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa ladhe ja'a ke'a boe lii dhèu leo, bagi ja'a lii ne dènge boe kab'ua. Ja'a ke'a boe lii rèngu, aa rèngu re'a boe lii ja'a kahèi. Ji'i baga taa, aa j'aj'i sèmi dhèu leo rai kara sa.<bt>[NLT] But if I don't know another person's/other people's language, it has no value/worth whatsoever for me. I don't understand those languages/words, and they also don't understand my language/words. We are strangers/foreigners to each other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baga taa; satu merek = satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:49:20Z">baga taa; satu merek = satu sonde tau satu pung bahasa (bhs Sabu hela'u)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baga taa"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 02:49:29Z" status="Anyone">saling berdiam diri, tidak saling mengerti;</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2010-11-04 03:14:08Z">UNS not know, but reinforced by context, so team wants to leave it</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge miu. Miu neo abhu karunya dènge koasa nèti Lamatua. Èèna be'a. Te ngaa be'a risi ladhe miu tenge j'ara ho abhu koasa dènge karunya dhu miu bisa pake sèna ka pa'èra dhèu parcaya sèra!<bt>It's the same way also with you-pl. You want to get power and unique.gifting from God2. That is good. But it would be better for you to make an effort to get power and unique.gifting which you can use to help strengthen many believers!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />De dhèu dhu padhai pake lii leo, be'a risi nèngu sabaj'a manèngi sèna ka Lamatua hia ne karunya kahèi, ho peka sasoa nèti lii leo èèna.<bt>So (consequently), a person who speaks using a different language, it is/would be better if s/he prays asking God2 to also give him unique.gifting to explain the meaning of that different language.</bt><v n="14" />Ladhe ja'a manèngi-mangaj'i pake lii leo, ja'a sabaj'a pake d'ara ja'a, te ngaa ja'a ke'a boe ngaa dhu ja'a padhai lii èèna.<bt>If I am praying2 (doublet) using a different language, I pray1 using my insides, but I don't understand what I am saying. [NLT]</bt><v n="15" />De babe'a na, ja'a tao tasamia? Ja'a pake dua-dua, te ngaa èci-èci ka dènge lod'o na. Ja'a neo manèngi-mangaj'i pake d'ara ja'a, aa ja'a neo manèngi-mangaj'i pake lii dhu ke'a mèu kahèi. Ja'a neo sod'a pake lii sod'a koa-kio mi Lamatua nèti d'ara ja'a. Aa ja'a bisa sod'a kahèi, pake lii dhu ja'a ke'a mèu.<bt>So (consequently), it is good that I do how? I use both, but each of them in its (own appropriate) time. I want to pray using my insides. And I also want to pray using words that I clearly understand. I want to sing praise songs to God2 using my insides. And I can also sing using words that I clearly understand.</bt><v n="16" />Te ladhe èu pake lii leo ho koa-kio Ama Lamatua nèti d'ara èu, te ngaa abhu dhèu ètu sèra dhu re'a boe lii deo na, tasamia nèngu bisa d'ara èci dènge èu? Lod'o èu manèngi makasi mi Lamatua pake lii leo, tasamia dhèu èèna bisa nare lii èci dènge èu, ka na peka na, &lt;&lt;Lèke kèna!&gt;&gt; Bisa boe, si? Te nèngu ne'a boe lii padhai èu deo na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if you-sg use a different language to praise God from your insides, but there is a person there who doesn't understand what was just said, how can s/he be one insides (united, harmony, in accord) with you? When you are giving thanks to God2 using a different language, how is it that s/he can agree with you, and say, &lt;&lt;That's right!&gt;&gt; S/he can't, right? Cuz (elaboration) s/he can't understand your recent language/words/message.</bt><v n="17" />Èu bisa manèngi makasi sèmi èèna kahèi mi Lamatua. Te ngaa èèna pa'èra boe d'ara dhèu leo.<bt>It is possible for you to give thanks to God2 like that. But that doesn't strengthen/encourage another/the other person's insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ele boe miu me'a boe, te ngaa ja'a padhai lii pake lii leo risi nèti miu. Aa ja'a manèngi makasi mi Lamatua, lula Nèngu hia ja'a bisa padhai lii sèmi èèna.<bt>You-pl probably don't know (this), but I speak using other languages more than all of you. And I give thanks to God2, because He makes me able to speak like that.</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu parcaya pakaboko, na, be'a risi ja'a padhai lii dhoka lèmi hèb'a dhu bab'a te ngaa re'a mèu, sèna ka aj'a-nori si. Te ladhe ja'a padhai lii pamadhera-dhera pake lii leo, dènge pake lii riho-riho hèb'a dhu re'a boe, na, gaguna na aad'o.<bt>But if believers are gathered together, it is better that I speak using just five short words that they can really understand, so I teach them. Cuz (elaboration) if I talk really long using a different language, and use thousands of words that they don't understand, it is pointless/useless.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ladhe miu neo me'a mèu j'ara-j'ara, na, miu hud'i pangee nuka sèmi dhèu ee'a. Mage pangee sèmi ana iiki! Te ngaa re j'ara bhelu-katub'a, miu hud'i nuka sèmi ana iiki dhu re'a boe tao bhabhelu, lula d'ara ra dhu mèu aadha-aadha.<bt>Dear siblings! If you-pl want to understand something, you must learn to think like an adult/mature/fully developed. Don't be thinking like small children! But with (regard to) evil things, you must be like small children, who don't know how to do evil things, because their insides are clean. [NOTE on STRUCTURE: undo the complex chiasmus. a b a; one variable not children, infants, adults; another variable thinking, evil, (good), thinking] [CHECK last phrase wUNS]</bt><v n="21" />Ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua, dhu suri peka na,<bt>In God2's Scriptures, it is written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua èdhi peka, aku Nèngu na,<bt>&lt;&lt;Our-inc Master is speaking, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Ja'a neo pake dhèu dhu padhai lii pake lii leo sèra,<bt>&lt;I am going to use people who speak using other languages,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho padhai lii dènge dhèu Isra'el.<bt>so I can speak to/with the people of Isra'el.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Masi ka Ja'a peka tasamia èèna ka,<bt>No matter what I say,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa ro'o boe nanene Ja'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>nevertheless they don't want to listen to Me.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="14:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 28:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Nèti èèna ka, ladhe miu paraga dènge dhèu dhu padhai lii pake lii leo, èèna j'aj'i mi tadha hia dhèu dhu parcaya mèka Lamatua, sèna ka bisa rèdhi koasa Lamatua. J'ara ne'e soru-bara boe dhèu dhu parcaya le Kristus. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu lole lii moa Lamatua, na, ne'e ne ka soru-bara rèngu dhu parcaya le Kristus. Te ngaa soru-bara boe dhèu dhu parcaya mèka Kristus.<bt>Because of that, if you encounter a person who speaks using a different language, that is a sign to people who don't yet believe in God2, so they can see God2's power/authority. That does not help (doublet) people who already believe in Kristus. But if people speak telling/explaining God2's message, that helps people who already believe in Kristus. That does not help people who do not yet believe in Kristus.</bt><v n="23" />Ladhe sèmi miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu pakaboko, ka miu padhai lii pake lii baka-leo, hèia dhèu dhu parcaya boe, do, dhu ne'a boe j'ara se'e, maso dhiu asa talora aae miu, dhèu se ngee sèmi ngaa sa? Tatu ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ètu se'e se, huj'u aa'i mèu-mèu!&gt;&gt;<bt>If perchance [hypothetical] you-pl are all gathered together, and you are speaking using various other languages, then there is a person who does not believe, or a person who doesn't understand these matters, come into your midst, what are these people going to think? Surely they will say, &lt;&lt;These people here are completely crazy!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Aa ladhe sèmi miu aa'i-aa'i dhu padhue-padhai ho peka paled'a lii moa Lamatua, hèia dhèu dhu parcaya boe, do, dhu ne'a mèu mèka j'ara-j'ara se, maso dhiu asa talora miu. Tatu dhèu ne, neo nanene lii padhai miu. De, ngaa dhu miu peka-padhai sèra, pad'elo sasala na, toke neo parisa mamuri na d'ai lutu.<bt>And if perchance [hypothetical] all of you are recip-speaking explaining God2's message, and there is a person who doesn't believe, or a person who doesn't understand these matters, comes into your midst. Surely that person wants to listen to what it is you are talking about. So (consequently), what you are talking about shows him his wrongs, to the point that s/he wants to examine his own life carefully/in fine detail. [NLT, CEV, HCE]</bt><v n="25" />Ka bhabhelu dhu nèngu pahuni ètu d'ara na, èèna na bhoka patalele, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a. Ka na patitu kètu urutuu na, ho pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Tare'a-re'a Ama Lamatua ètu talora aae miu di!&gt;&gt;<bt>And the evil things that s/he has hidden in his insides will be unveiled (non-agentive) so everyone comes to know about them/for all to know. And then s/he will kneel to worship God, saying, &lt;&lt;Ira ii [+amazement]! Truly God is in your midst!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sabhoka "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-11 03:31:12Z" status="Anyone">buka tiba-tiba,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi tao, na, tao mola-mola. Baku dènge maruru<bt>Everything that we-inc do, na, do according to what is straight/right. Don't be chaotic/disorder/badly disorganised</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />De a'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ladhe miu pakaboko, èci-èci ka dènge karunya na. Abhu dhu sod'a koa-kio Ama Lamatua. Abhu dhu aj'a-nori dhèu lula-nèti Lamatua. Abhu dhu peka paled'a j'ara-j'ara Lamatua dhu uru èèna pahuni era. Abhu dhu padhai pake lii leo. Aa abhu dhu bisa peka sasoa nèti lii leo sèra. J'ara aa'i-aa'i se, rèngu hud'i tao ku ho pa'èra parcaya dhèu leo sèra.<bt>So (consequently) dear siblings! If you are gathered, each person has his (own) unique.gifting. There are those who sing praising (doublet) to God. There are those who teach (doublet) people about God2. There are those who unveil/explain things from God2, that were previously hidden. There are those who speak using other languages. And there are those who can explain what those other languages mean. All those things, they must do to strengthen other people's faith.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ladhe abhu dhu d'èi padhai lii pake lii leo, èèna be'a. Sad'i dua do tèlu dhèu di, baku pa'ae-ae. Dhèu èci padhai lii uuru, èle ku heka dhèu leo kèna. Aa hud'i abhu ku dhèu dhu peka sasoa na.<bt>If there is someone who likes to speak using another language, that is good. But just let there be two or three people, you don't need lots and lots (lit: don't cause.many-many). One person should finish speaking first, only.then another person (speaks). And there must be someone who can explain the meaning/ significance.</bt><v n="28" />Ladhe sèmi abhu boe dhu bisa peka sasoa nèti lii leo èèna, na, baku padhai lii pake lii leo ètu katanga madha dhèu ae-ae. Hud'i laa rèngu padhai lii ètu d'ara ra. Rèngu bisa padhai lii dènge Lamatua sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>If perchance [hypothetical] there is nobody who can explain the meaning of that language/message, na, (you) don't need to speak using other languages in front of many people (=crowd, congregation, gathering). Just let them speak that way in their own insides. They can also speak to God2 that way.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ladhe miu pakaboko, na, dua do tèlu dhèu di dhu padhai lii, lole lii moa Lamatua. Dhèu leo hud'i dadoo ku lii padhai nèti dhèu dhu padhai sèra.<bt>If you are gathered together, just let two or three people speak telling God2's message. (The) Other people must weigh/evaluate what those people are saying.</bt><v n="30" />Te ngaa ladhe Lamatua bhoke ca j'ara dhu uru èèna mèu iia mèka mi ca dhèu dhu madhèdi nanene ètu èèna, na, nèngu hud'i peka paled'a lii moa ne mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhèdi ètu èèna. Aa dhèu dhu padhai lii ètu madha, hud'i ae eele nèti lii padhai na, sèna ka hia dhèu dhu heka tadèngi lii moa Lamatua, ho na padhai lii.<bt>But if God2 has/is revealing a way for something that was previously not clear to one person who is sitting there listening, na, that person must openly tell/explain that message to everyone who is sitting there. And the person who is speaking in front must stop speaking, to allow the person who has just (now, recently) heard from God2, so s/he can speak. [EXEG: re: “in front”. neither the MTTs nor the UNSs were picturing the dynamics, or understanding “the first person” without it. RL considerations, irrespective of Brethren practices.]</bt><v n="31" />Dhu lèke ka, miu aa'i-aa'i mi bisa lole lii moa Lamatua. Te ngaa ladhe padhai lii, na, èci uru, ladhe èle heka dhèu leo kèna. Dènge j'ara ne, dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa nanene, bisa re'a j'ara, aa bisa pa'èra d'ara ra.<bt>The right/proper thing, would be for all of you to be able to tell/explain God2's message. But when speaking allow one person to speak first, and when (s/he is) finished, only.then his friend/companion. In that way, everyone can hear, everyone can learn, and everyone can strengthen/encourage their insides.</bt><v n="32" />Sanèd'e, te dhèu dhu lole lii moa Lamatua, hud'i ne'a ator ngi'u na. Ka èci pamata dènge èci, aa dhèu leo taha uru.<bt>Remember that a person who speaks telling/explaining God2's message, must also know how to manage/control/ regulate himself. So one can wait for another, and the other should restrain himself. [HCE]</bt><v n="33" />Te abhu boe maruru ètu Ama Lamatua, te ngaa mera dènge milu di.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) there is no chaos/disorder/disarray in/at God, but just order and peace/stability. [NOTE: compound end part modelled on CEV to fit context.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ètu mia-mia, ladhe dhèu parcaya pakaboko, hud'i sèmi ne'e ku:<bt>All over the place, if/when believers are gathered together, it should be like this:</bt><v n="34" />dhèu bhèni madhèdi mau-mau, bisa boe padhai lii pa'ae. Rèngu hud'i nanene kètu juma'at sèra. Te Atora Ama Lamatua peka sèmi èèna kahèi, si?<bt>Women sit calmly/quietly, (and) should not be many voicing (=talkative, talking a lot, jabbering). They must be listening to/obeying the leaders/heads of the congregation. Cuz (elaboration) God's Law says that, right? [EXEG from (Ex.Sum): not taken as absolute, since that would contradict 11:5, 13, 26, 31, etc.]</bt><v n="35" />Ladhe abhu bhèni dhu neo karèi j'ara èci, pe d'ai èmu ku heka karèi dhèu èmu na kèna. Te ladhe bhèni maruru ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a, sèra sa pamakae iisi ra!<bt>If there is a woman who wants to ask about something, let her wait until she goes home first, only then ask her spouse. Cuz (elaboration) if women are noisy/disruptive/ chaotic in a house of worship, that is shameful!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Madhutu a'abhu miu, tasamia? Te Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua mai boe nèti miu. Aa Lii Holo-Nori Na hia boe miu mesa mi ètu kota Korintus di! De pangee paie ku!<bt>What are you-pl thinking!? Cuz (elaboration) God's Words did not come from you! And His Words were not just given to you in the city of Korintus alone! Think carefully now! [NOTE: Construction of last sentence carries sense of corrective frustration--you should know better!]</bt><v n="37" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, nèngu bisa lole lii moa Lamatua, do pangee na, nèngu abhu koasa nèti Roh Lamatua, na, nèngu ne'a j'ara-j'ara dhu ja'a suri hia miu sèra, atora dhu ja'a tao boe, te ngaa paredha nèti Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus.<bt>If there is a person who considers themselves able to tell/explain God2's message, or, thinks s/he has received power/authority from God2's Spirit, na, he himself knows that, that matter which I am writing to you about, is not a regulation from me, but a command from Yesus Kristus, our-inc Head.</bt><v n="38" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu ro'o boe sèmi rare j'ara se, na, miu baku sèmi mere dhèu ne.<bt>If there is a person who does not want to accept these matters, na, you-pl should not receive/welcome that person.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Tenge j'ara sèna ka miu abhu koasa ho bisa peka paled'a lii moa Lamatua. Aa mage kai dhèu, sèna ka rèngu baku padhai pake lii leo.<bt>Dear siblings! Make an effort/strive so you get power to be able to speak telling God2's message/ instructions. And don't forbid people, saying, they are not allowed to speak using other languages.</bt><v n="40" />De ladhe miu pakaboko, na, pakako aa'i-aa'i madhutu mola-mola. Tao uuru ku èci, heka dhu leo kèna. Pakako aa'i-aa'i dènge be'a, madhutu madha j'ara na. Baku dènge maruru.<bt>So (consequently), if you are gathered together, na, carry out everything according to what is straight/right/ appropriate. One thing goes/happens first, and only then another. Carry out everything well, according to its way/as designed/as is planned/appropriate. Don't be chaotic/disorder/badly disorganised.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kristus mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na<bt>Kristus has come back to life from His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ja'a neo sèna ka miu sanèd'e Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua dhu uru èèna ja'a peka-padhai le dènge miu. Miu sèmi mere, hèia tao taruu madhutu Lii Lolo Be'a èèna.<bt>Dear siblings! I want you to remember God2's Good News which I have told you from long ago. You received/accepted it and have persevered in continuing to follow/obey that Good News.</bt><v n="2" />Te Lii Lolo Be'a èèna ka dhu bisa hia miu mamuri, sad'i miu kèpe pa'èra-èra. Te ngaa ladhe miu parcaya taruu boe Ama Lamatua, na, parcaya miu èèna ele iie d'ara.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that Good News is what can *save you/give you life, as long as you keep holding to it firmly. But if you don't keep believing in God, your faith is pointless/useless/in vain (idiomatic). [EXEG: in this context focus is on perseverence, whereas in v.14 it is on the truth of the resurrection. This is talking about having geniune faith (Ex.Summ.), not having believed the wrong thing (as per NLT)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ja'a aj'a le miu j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai risi eele, dhu uru èèna dhèu aj'a-nori ja'a. Nuka: Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai èèna, madhe le sèna ka patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi. J'ara ne'e j'aj'i madhutu Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua dhu suri tèke karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>I have also taught you various matters that are most important, which previously (other) people have taught to me. That is: Kristus, whom God has sent coming, died to save/rescue us-inc from the power of our wrongs, exactly like God2's Holy Writings have written from long ago. [EXEG: The Gk “foremost things” is plural, followed by an elaboration of a list that goes on for many verses. So in these RLs, making “that important matter” singular doesn't work in context nor match the Gk. The Gk /gar/ links to returning to elaborate on what he said in vs.1-2a (see Ex. Summ.). Note that both NLT and CEV choose to undertranslate /gar/.]</bt><note reference="15:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:5-12</note><v n="4" />Ra padhane Ne. Ka d'ai camèd'a èèna, Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne, lèke mola-mola sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua.<bt>They buried Him. Then the day after next, God2 brought Him back to life, exactly as God2's Writings have written beforehand.</bt><note reference="15:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 16:8-10, Mateos 12:40, Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 2:24-32</note><v n="5" />Èle èèna ka, Kristus pad'elo iisi Na mi Petrus.<bt>After that, Kristus showed Himself to Petrus.</bt><note reference="15:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani suri, peka, &lt;&lt;Kefas&gt;&gt;. Kefas èèna, ngara leo nèti Petrus.<bt>The Yunani language Bible writes, saying, &lt;&lt;Kefas&gt;&gt;. That Kefas, is Petrus' other name.</bt></note>Nèngu pad'elo iisi Na mi ana madhutu Na dhèu canguru dua sèra kahèi.<bt>He also showed Himself to His 12 *disciples (underlings).</bt><note reference="15:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 28:16-17, Markus 16:14, Lukas 24:34, 36, Yohanis 20:19</note><v n="6" />Aa ca tèka, Na pad'elo iisi Na mi lèmi ngasu risi dhèu parcaya. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i se ladhe rèdhi Ne dènge musi madha rèngu. Nèti rèngu se, ae dhu mamuri era, aa ciki di dhu madhe le.<bt>Then2 one time, He also showed Himself to more than 500 believers. All of them got to see Him with their own eyeballs! From those, there are many who are still alive, and only a few have already died.</bt><v n="7" />Ka Na pad'elo iisi mi Yakobis. Hèia Nèngu pad'elo iisi kahèi, mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Na aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Then He showed self to Yakobis. And then He also showed self to all His *apostles/emissaries. [NOTE for SU: vs. 3-7 can be read together as a Confession of Faith.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ja'a dhèu limuri tèka dhu ladhe kèdhi Ne. Te ja'a ne nuka sèmi ana dhu rara iisi limuri tèka.<bt>I am the one at the very end of the line/least value who also got to see Him. Cuz (elaboration) I am like the child who was born at the very end / after everyone else.</bt><note reference="15:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 9:3-6</note><v n="9" />Dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dhu leo sèra kapai risi nèti ja'a ne. Madhutu mola-mola, na, ja'a nia boe j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. Te uru èèna, ja'a ka dhu paj'èra dhèu unu Lamatua ètu mia-mia.<bt>God2's other *apostles are more important/greater than me. In actual fact/Actually, I am not worthy to be His apostle. Cuz (elaboration) previously, I am the one who caused torment and abuse/mistreatment to God2's people all over the place.</bt><note reference="15:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:3</note><v n="10" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi ja'a. Hèia Na tao ja'a j'aj'i sèmi ne'e ne. Ropa Nèngu tao j'ara be'a hia ja'a, Na core eele boe lod'o iia d'ara. Nèti èèna ka, ne'e ne ja'a sab'a bia risi nèti rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra! Ja'a mesa ku boe dhu sab'a, te ngaa d'ara hua iia Lamatua ka dhu sab'a ètu mamuri ja'a.<bt>But God showed His good insides (goodness/grace/ kindness/generosity) to me. So He is the one who made me to be as (I am) now. When He was doing good things to/for me, He was not just throwing away time pointlessly/in vain. That is why now I am the one who works harder than everyone! It is not me alone who am working, but God2's good insides which are working in my life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />De ladhe ja'a, do, dhèu pajuu-paleha dhu leo dhu aj'a-nori èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Te a'aj'a ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi èèna dhoka ca j'ara di. Ji'i peka-padhai taruu Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua mi dhèu. Nèti èèna ka, miu j'aj'i parcaya Lii Lolo Be'a dhu sama èèna.<bt>So (consequently) if I, or a different apostle who teaches like that, that is not important. Cuz (elaboration) all of our teachings are just the same thing. We keep telling people about God2's Good News. Because of that, you-pl came to believe in that same Good News.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu madhe, èèna na mamuri hari<bt>Dead people will come back to life/live again</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ji'i tema aj'a-nori, peka na, Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai èèna, mamuri hari le nèti mamadhe Na. De, nga tao ka miu cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu madhe sèra, mamuri hari boe?&gt;&gt; Ngangee èèna mai nèti mia?<bt>[CHECK carefully understanding of mamuri heka] We teach that Kristus, whom God sent, came back to life from His death. So (consequently), why is it that some of you are saying, &lt;&lt;Dead people don't come back to life again&gt;&gt;? What's the basis of that thinking?</bt><v n="13" />Te ladhe dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, sasoa na, Kristus mamuri hari boe kahèi!<bt>Cuz (elaboration), if dead people don't come back to life again, that means that Kristus also didn't come back to life!</bt><v n="14" />Aa ladhe Kristus mamuri hari boe, na, aa'i-aa'i dhu ji'i peka-padhai dènge dhèu, gaguna aad'o. Aa lalèka miu mi Kristus, parcuma kahèi!<bt>And if Kristus did not come back to life, everything that we-exc are telling people has no use. And your-pl faith in Kristus, is also pointless/useless/in vain!</bt><v n="15-16" />Aa ladhe tare'a dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, ji'i j'aj'i sakasii kapod'e-kabèli mi Ama Lamatua. Te ji'i tema aj'a-nori, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua ka dhu pamamuri hari Kristus!&gt;&gt; Mema tare'a dhu ji'i lole sèmi èèna ka. Te ngaa ladhe sèmi dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, sasoa na, Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari boe Kristus kahèi.<bt>And if it's true that dead people don't come back to life, we are also false witnesses/lying witnesses about God. Cuz (elaboration) we are in the habit of teaching (doublet) that, &lt;&lt;God is the one who brought Kristus back to life!&gt;&gt; We really do report that. But if perchance [hypothetical] dead people don't come back to life, that means that God never brought Kristus back to life either.</bt><v n="17" />Pangee sèku j'ara ne: ladhe Kristus mamuri hari boe, lalèka miu mi Ama Lamatua parcuma! Aa miu pasae taruu sasala-sasigo miu!<bt>Have a think about this: if Kristus did not come back to life, your-pl faith in God is pointless! And you are still shoulder-carrying your wrongs!</bt><v n="18" />Mesa boe èèna di, te dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu uru èèna pa'èki dènge Kristus, dhu madhe le, ladhe Kristus kèd'i boe nèti mamadhe Na, rèngu madhe pacèri nèti Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>And that's not all, cuz (elaboration) everyone who were bound/linked with Kristus, who have died, if Kristus never came back to life from His death, they died separated off/cut off from God.</bt><v n="19" />Kristus j'aj'i era sarai èdhi, lula te'a, na, Nèngu neo tao j'ara hua iia hia èdhi. Te ngaa ladhe èdhi sanao-maena ho Nèngu neo tao sèmi èèna dhoka ètu rai-haha di, na parcuma! Aa èdhi j'aj'i dhèu kasia risi eele nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra!<bt>Kristus is our place of hope2 (lit: leaning on/support), because we know that He wants to/is going to do what is good/best for us. But if our hope (doublet) that He wants to do like that only happens/is only in effect in this world, na, that is pointless/in vain! And we are the most pitiable people of all people!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarai "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-12 00:47:44Z" status="Anyone">sandar = sandar (badan di kursi) 2) depend on, hope, trust</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lula Kristus mamuri hari, ngaa ka dhu j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a?<bt>Because Kristus came back to life, what is going to happen later?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Aa te ngaa aad'o sèmi èèna, si? Te dhu lèke mola-mola ka: Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai èèna, mamuri le nèti mamadhe Na! Aa mesa boe Nèngu di, te èèna na dhèu-dhèu parcaya dhu madhe sèra, bèli-camèd'a mamuri hari kahèi. Kristus ne, nuka sèmi hua uru dhu pad'elo, na, rèngu dhu madhe sèra, bèli-camèd'a mamuri hari madhutu Nèngu.<bt>Whereas in fact, it's not like that, right? Cuz (elaboration) what is true is this: Kristus, whom God has sent coming [serial verb construction], has already come back to life from His death! And not only He alone, cuz (elaboration) later believers who die/have died will also come back to life. Kristus is like the first produce/result (agricultural imagery), which shows that those who die will come back to life following His (lead, example, experience). [CEV undertranslated here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hua uru"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-12 01:10:53Z" status="Anyone">the first fruit to be picked, (implication of offerred in church) ; hua uuru = one tree (among several) fruits before the others.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Uru-uru èèna, dhoka dhèu èci di, nuka Adam dhu sisu paredha Ama Lamatua. De hahuku na, nuka mamadhe. Hahuku ne noto mi èdhi dhèu rai-haha kahèi. Te ngaa limuri ne, abhu ca dhèu hari, nuka Kristus, dhu mamuri madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua. De, lula babe'a Nèngu ka dhèu madhe bisa mamuri hari!<bt>Long ago, it was only one person, that is Adam, who violated God's command(s). So (consequently) his punishment was death. That punishment also fell on/effected us-inc humans. But now, there is one other person, that is Kristus, who lived according to God's command(s). So (consequently) because of His goodness, dead people can come back to life! [EXEG/theology: from notes on Rom 5:12: Everybody since Adam has made the same kind of bad choice Adam made, back at the beginning. They all ended up sinning by just the same process as Adam ended up sinning. Spread throughout the human race -- not genetically, just because we are human and the first real human somehow screwed up our genes, or let loose some kind of moral virus, but because practically speaking, all the rest of us have fallen into the same trap as Adam, of not wanting to do things God's way.] [NOTE: still missing in the logical structure here: "to us who have also violated God's law.", but in next verse]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="noto "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-12 01:16:19Z" status="Anyone">jato, turun-temurun</Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu sisu paredha Lamatua, lèke huku madhe sama sèmi Adam kahèi. Te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pa'èki dènge Kristus, èèna na Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari si.<bt>Everyone who violates God2's commands is also effected by a punishment of death, just like Adam. But everyone who is bound/linked with Kristus, God will bring them back to life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Te ngaa èci-èci ka dènge lod'o na. Kristus dhèu partama dhu mamuri hari, nuka sèmi hua uru deo na. Aa pe Na lèpa hari mai asa rai-haha ne, dhèu unu Na sèra heka mamuri hari kèna.<bt>But each in his own time (idiomatic). Kristus was the first person to come back to life, like the aforementioned first yield/produce earlier. And later, when He has come back to this world, only then will His people also come back to life.</bt><v n="24" />Èle ku, heka rai-haha ne èle kèna. Lod'o èèna, Kristus j'aj'i Dhèu Aae dhu pa'ele iie koasa aa'i-aa'i, paredha aa'i-aa'i, aa mamèu aa'i-aa'i dhu pamusu dènge Lamatua. Nèngu j'aj'i kahèi Dhèu Aae dhu pangèd'u hari hak paredha Na mi Ama Na, nuka Ama Lamatua.<bt>After that, only then the end of the world. At that time, Kristus will be King who destroys all powers/authroities, all rule/commands, and all knowledge/science/ magic that is at enmity/enemies with God2. He will also be the King that turns His right to rule back over to God, His Father. [NLT + Ex. Summ.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te Ama Lamatua hud'i nèd'u paredha taruu, toke Na segi aa'i dhu lab'a Kristus, sèna ka ra pahaha iisi mi Nèngu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God must hold rule continually, until He conquers all who oppose Kristus, so they surrender/submit to Him. [NOTE to daughter translations: some mesolectal speakers don't know /ta'alok/, so use a word for "bow".] [EXEG: deliberately preserving ambiguity of Gk referents to “he”]</bt><note reference="15:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note><v n="26" />Abhu ca j'ara dhu pamusu dènge èdhi era, nuka mamadhe. Te ngaa d'ai limuri, ka Lamatua segi kahèi koasa mamadhe. De lèpa lod'o limuri, dhèu madhe heka.<bt>There is another matter/thing which is still opposing/warring with us-inc, that is, death. But in the end/ultimately, God2 is also going to conquer the power/authority of death. So (consequently), there will not be dead people anymore.</bt><v n="27" />Ètu Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua tao dhu Na segi aa'i-aa'i sèra, sèna ka ra pahaha iisi mi Dhèu dhu Lamatua pua mai èèna.&gt;&gt; De dhu suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;dhu Na segi aa'i-aa'i sèra, sèna ka ra pahaha iisi mi Dhèu Nèngu&gt;&gt;, de lèke, ladhe peka na, Ama Lamatua pahaha boe iisi mi Dhèu unu Nèngu èèna. Lula Ama Lamatua ka dhu ded'e Ne, sèna ka j'aj'i Kètu mi ngaa aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>In God2's Holy Writings it is written, saying, &lt;&lt;God2 makes all whom He conquers to bow to that Person whom He sent coming [svc].&gt;&gt; So (consequently) what (they) wrote, saying, &lt;&lt;all whom He conquers will bow to His Person&gt;&gt;, it is clear that God will not bow to His own Person. Because God2 himself is the one who appointed Him to be Head of everything.</bt><note reference="15:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 8:6</note><v n="28" />Bèli-camèd'a ladhe aa'i-aa'i nanene tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, èèna na Ana ne pangèd'u aa'i-aa'i hari mi Ama Na, dhu ded'e Ne j'aj'i Kètu nèti aa'i-aa'i sèra. Èle èèna, Ama Lamatua paredha taruu ètu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i, bagi mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Later when all truly listen to /obey God's Offspring, that Offspring will turn everything back over to His Father, who had appointed Him to be Head of all. Then God will rule/govern continually in everything, for everyone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe sèmi dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, na, tasamia?<bt>If it were the case [hypothetical] that dead people didn't come back to life, na, how would that be?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Abhu dhèu dhu neo sarani ho gati dhèu dhu madhe le dhu dhae sarani mèka. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, nga tao ka rèngu neo sarani hia dhèu madhe?<bt>There are people who want to get *baptised to replace/stand in for dead people who were not yet baptised. But if dead people do not come back to life, why is it that they want to get baptised for dead people?</bt><note reference="15:29" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat ne mèu iia boe. Ad'a nuka sèmi &lt;&lt;sarani ho gati dhèu madhe&gt;&gt; abhu boe ètu ayat leo d'ara <span class="Italic">Sasuri Lii Pajaji Hiu Ama Lamatua</span>.<bt>This verse isn't clear. A ritual like &lt;&lt;get baptised to replace dead people&gt;&gt; does not exist in any other verse in the books/writings of <span class="Italic">God2's New Promise.</span> [we're trying this out to see how people respond; contrasts with "God's Old Promise" There are other ideas for what to call the NT and OT too.]</bt></note><v n="30" />Aa nga tao ka ji'i oe madhe pahari-pahari ètu d'ara sasab'a ji'i, ladhe dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe?<bt>And why is it that we-exc are repeatedly willing to nearly die in our work, if dead people don't come back to life?</bt><v n="31" />Te bèli-bèli ja'a oe madhe! Te ngaa a'ari pasue! Ja'a subha, te ja'a pangee, na, ngaa-ngaa tao boe ladhe ja'a madhe. Te ja'a bisa boti kètu, lula miu pa'èki taruu dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pua le mai.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I keep nearly dying every day! But dear siblings! [CHECK if vocative placement is awkward. Should it be removed?] I swear (an oath), cuz (elaboration) I think it would not matter if I were to die. Cuz (elaboration) I can lift my head (legitimate pride), because you-pl continue to be bound/linked with our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, whom God sent.</bt><v n="32" />Ca hari ni, lod'o ja'a ètu kota Epesus era, ja'a patao-palaha dènge dhèu sèra nuka sèmi badha hui dhu bhelu. Te ngaa ladhe ja'a dhoka patao-palaha, ho bisa segi mesa ku, aa hia boe Lamatua, èèna parcuma. Guna boe ngaa-ngaa! Te ladhe tare'a dhèu madhe mamuri hari boe, hua iia èdhi madhutu dhu dhèu peka, na,<bt>At that time (past), when I was still in the city of Efesus, I argued (doublet) with those people who are like evil wild animals. But if I only argue (doublet) so I can win for myself, not for God2, that is pointless/futile/in vain. It has no use! Cuz (elaboration) if it is true that dead people don't come back to life, it would be better for us-inc to just go along with what people are saying, who say,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Mai èdhi pesta rame-rame,<bt>&lt;&lt;Let's-inc party festively,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa ta'a-tinu be'a-be'a,<bt>and just eat-drink tasty-tasty (to our heart's desire/pleasures),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te bèli èdhi madhe kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>cuz (elaboration) tomorrow we'll be dead!&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="15:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 22:13</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Miu baku lèke tipu, ho pangee sèmi èèna! Te abhu dhu peka na,<bt>You-pl should not be deceived to go along with that thinking! Cuz (elaboration) there is that which says,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ladhe èu pa'èci dènge dhèu bhelu,<bt>&lt;&lt;If you-sg are joined/united with evil people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">èèna pakaj'èu èu nèti mamuri dhu mola.&gt;&gt;<bt>that will distance you-sg from the life that is straight (morally).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ad'u-ue ia ka bhabhelu-katub'a! Rèno ka! Ator ngi'u mu! Tao dhu lèke di! Dhu lèke ka, miu hud'i me'a ku makae, te ètu talora aae miu, abhu era dhèu dhu tadhe mèka Ama Lamatua.<bt>Don't do evil anymore! Stop it! Control yourself! Just do what is right! The right thing is, you-pl should feel ashamed, cuz (elaboration) in your midst there are still people who do not yet know God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Rèno ka"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2010-11-04 06:53:19Z" status="Anyone">=loe ka</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ladhe èdhi mamuri hari, bèli-camèd'a ngi'u aae èdhi sèmi ngaa sa?<bt>If/when we-inc come back to life, what will our bodies be like?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Abhu dhu pakarèi, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu madhe mamuri hari, j'ara na tasamia? Aa ngi'u aae j'aj'i sèmi ngaa sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>There is someone who asks, &lt;&lt;If/when dead people come back to life, how will that happen? And how will their bodies be?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Goa, ee! Te ladhe sèle hini, hini ne hud'i roe ètu d'ara rai uuru ku, heka na bisa muri kèna.<bt>That's dumb, é! Cuz (elaboration) if you plant/bury seed, that seed must decay/come to ruin/be destroyed first, only then can it live/sprout/start growing. [NOTE: compare with John 12:23-24 plus discussion there. MC]</bt><v n="37" />Aa hini dhu èdhi sèle, rupa na leko-leo nèti dhu muri, èli, heka cèu rèu kèna. Te nèngu èèna hini dhu mango-meto, nuka sèmi gandum, do are, do hini dhu leo.<bt>And the seed that we plant, its model/form/type is different from what lives, sprouts and grows leaves. It's just a dry/bare (doublet) seed, like wheat or, rice/grain or, other seeds. [CHECK èli = taring, sprout (Ayub, Michael &amp; Lena not know second sense)]</bt><v n="38" />Èci-èci ka madhutu raropa ra, madhutu dad'èi Lamatua. Lula Nèngu ka dhu ator raropa nèti ana aaj'u sèra.<bt>Each one according to its type/form/model, following God2's will. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who has determined/decided each plant's type/form.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Badha dènge dhèu rai-haha sèmi èèna kahèi. Èci-èci ka dènge raropa ra, madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Hèia ngi'u dhèu rai-haha madhutu raropa dhèu rai-haha. Ngi'u badha èci-èci ka dènge raropa ra. Manu-bhui dènge raropa ra. I'a dènge raropa ra. Dhu leo sèra dènge raropa ra.<bt>Animals and humans are also like that. Each with its own type/form/model, following/according to God2's will. So, humans' bodies follow humans' type/form/model. Animals' bodies each follow its own type/form/model. Birds with their form/type. Fish with their form/type. The others with each of their form/type. [NOTE: we're taking this as for instances, not as a closed list.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Abhu mèdha ètu dedha-liru, aa abhu ètu rai-haha. Ètu dedha-liru dènge kolo-karisi na. Te ngaa kolo-karisi ne, leko-leo nèti dhu ètu rai-haha. Dhu ètu rai-haha abhu kolo-karisi kahèi. Te ngaa kolo-karisi se, leko-leo nèti dhu abhu ètu dedha-liru.<bt>There are things in the sky, and there are things on earth. Those in the sky have their own greatness/incredibleness. But their greatness is different from those that are on earth. Those on the earth also have their own greatness. But that greatness is different from those that are in the sky. [NOTE to daughter translations: this here and in following verses is Gk. /doxa/ "glory, beauty, splendour"; KM has to go more generic, but many of the surrounding vernaculars have a more specific term that is closer to the Gk.]</bt><v n="41" />Ètu dedha-liru kolo-karisi madha lod'o leko-leo; kolo-karisi hèru leko-leo; aa kolo-karisi hua-hètu leko-leo kahèi. Èci-èci ka dènge kolo-karisi ra. De aa'i-aa'i ra dènge kolo-karisi, si?<bt>As for in the sky, the sun has its own greatness; the moon has its own different greatness; and the stars also have their own different greatness. Each with its own greatness. So (consequently) all of them have greatness, right?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ladhe dhèu madhe mamuri hari, èèna nuka sèmi hini deo na. Te ladhe padhane ka dhèu madhe, ngi'u aae na ele iie, si? Te ngaa ladhe mamuri hari, ngi'u na sèmi heka uru èèna. Te ladhe mamuri hari, bisa heka madhe.<bt>If dead people come back to life, that is just like that seed mentioned earlier. Cuz (elaboration) if (we) have buried a dead person, his corpse becomes completely decayed, right? But if s/he comes back to life, s/he is not the same as previously anymore. Cuz (elaboration) if (s/he) has already come back to life, s/he cannot die anymore.</bt><v n="43" />Ropa èdhi padhane dhèu madhe, èdhi mad'enge ngi'u aae ne. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu èèna mamuri hari, na saraga titu kèna! Te nèngu j'aj'i mola-mèci! Dhèu dhu madhe le bisa heka tao ngaa-ngaa lod'o dhèu padhane ne. Te ngaa ropa na mamuri hari, nèngu èra titu kèna!<bt>When we-inc bury dead people, we avoid/are grossed out by that corpse. But if that person has come back to life, na, how beautiful it is! Cuz (elaboration) is has become clean/pure/holy (doublet)! A dead person can't do anything when people bury him. But when s/he comes back to life, s/he is so strong/powerful!</bt><v n="44" />Ladhe dhèu mamuri era, ne'a dhoka ngee dènge rasa di, si? Te ngaa ropa na madhe, ho mamuri hari, na, Roh Lamatua hia ne mamuri dhu lèke. Ka dhèu ne sèmi heka uru èèna.<bt>If/when a person is still alive, s/he only knows how to think and feel, right? But, when s/he dies, to come back to life, na, God2's Spirit gives him true life. And s/he is then no longer the same as before. [NOTE: reduced redundancy]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Dhèu rai-haha dhu uru-uru j'ara, dhu sama sèmi èdhi, nuka Adam. Madhutu Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua dhu suri tèke, peka na, &lt;&lt;nèngu j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha dhu mamuri, dhu ne'a ngee dènge rasa.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa dhèu rai-haha dhu raropa na sama sèmi Adam, dhu dedha risi eele, nuka Kristus. Roh Na ka dhu bisa hia dhèu mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>The first human who was like us, was Adam. According to God2's Holy Writings, it is written, saying, &lt;&lt;he became a living human who knew how to think and feel.&gt;&gt; But the human who is a type/form/model like Adam at the very top/peak (a metaphor they use in kinship and social structure), is Kristus. His Spirit is the one who can give people true life. [EXEG: "the last Adam" is common Jewish Messianic reference; last = highest ranking; see Ex. Summ.]</bt><note reference="15:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:7</note><v n="46" />Raropa dhèu dhu uru-uru j'ara, nuka dhèu dhu ne'a dhoka ngee dènge rasa di, ka bisa madhe. Te ngaa dhu mamuri hari, nuka dhèu dhu abhu mamuri dhu lèke nèti Roh Lamatua.<bt>The form of that first person, was a person who only knew how to think and feel, and then s/he could die. But the one who has come back to life, is a person who gets/obtains true life from God2's Spirit. [HCE]</bt><v n="47" />Raropa dhèu dhu uru-uru j'ara ètu rai-haha ne, dhu tao nèti ahu rai. Te ngaa raropa ka dua, nuka Kristus dhu mai nèti sorga.<bt>The human of the first type/form/model on earth was made from dirt. But the one of the second type/form/model, is Kristus, who came from heaven.</bt><v n="48" />Èdhi dhu mamuri ètu rai-haha ne ca ropa dènge dhèu partama dhu Lamatua paj'aj'i nèti ahu rai. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pa'èki dènge Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, ca ropa dènge Kristus dhu mai nèti sorga.<bt>We-inc who live on earth, are the same type/form/model as the first human who God2' created from dirt. But a person who is bound/linked to God in heaven, is the same type/form/model as Kristus who came from heaven.</bt><v n="49" />Èdhi dhèu limuri ne, ca ropa dènge Adam dhu Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i nèti ahu rai. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, gati dènge raropa hiu, sama sèmi Kristus dhu mai nèti sorga.<bt>We now are the same type/form/model as Adam who God2 created from dirt. But eventually we will exchange for a new type/form/model, which is the same as Kristus who came from heaven.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Dhu ja'a neo peka dènge miu, sèmi ne'e: èdhi dhu ca ropa dènge dhèu partama, ngi'u èdhi j'aj'i nèti sisi dènge raa. Dènge j'ara ne'e, èdhi bisa boe abhu pusaka ho j'aj'i ana-ana Ama Lamatua ètu sorga. Bisa boe! Te raropa dhèu sèmi èèna, bèli-camèd'a ngi'u ra ele iie, ka bisa boe sèmi rare ngaa dhu taha nare nèbhu.<bt>Dear siblings! What I want to tell you is this: we-inc who are/became humans of the first type/form/model, our bodies are from meat and blood. [NOTE: Dhao way of talking about "flesh and blood"] In that way/form, we are not able to receive our inheritance to become God's offspring in heaven2. Just can't do it! Cuz (elaboration) a person of that type/form/model, their bodies will completely decay, so they are not able to receive things that last/endure continually/forever.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />De nanene paie-iie! Te ja'a neo bhoke paled'a rahasia èci. Èèna na abhu dhèu parcaya cahag'e dhu madhe boe. Te ngaa èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, èèna na gati raropa hiu.<bt>So (consequently), listen carefully! Cuz (elaboration) I am going to reveal a secret. There will be some believers who do not die. But all of us-inc will change/substitute into a new form/type/model.</bt><v n="52" />Ropa lii tiu tèbhe limuri tèka, aa'i-aa'i se j'aj'i dènge sahèka. Malai risi nèti ate musi madha. Te ropa tèbhe limuri tèka lii, cag'ag'a laa dhèu madhe mamuri hari. Aa ladhe ra mamuri hari, dhèu se madhe heka, aa ele iie heka. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge èdhi dhu mamuri era. Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti abhu raropa hiu.<bt>When a/the trumpet (makes) its last sound, all this will happen suddenly. Faster than your-sg blink of an eye. Cuz (elaboration) when the trumpet sounds, at that (same) time dead people will have come back to life. And if/when they have come back to life, they will not die again, and they won't decay again. It's the same way with us-inc who are still alive. All of us will become a new model/type/form. [EXEG: Gk meaning is ambiguous between last trumpet (object) or last trumpet (sound). (see Ex. Summ. “the last trumpet sound”) But note that the first reading ‘last trumpet (object)’ is vague (e.g. the last Stradavarius remaining today was first played in 1728), whereas the KM rendering is pretty unambiguous that this is the final trumpet sound (therefore by implication the last trumpet that plays). I could accept either /tarompet pung bunyi paling tarahir/ or /tarompet paling tarahir pung bunyi/, but since this part of this verse already shows evidence of reworking, and the grammar of the TB (while slightly ambiguous) leans toward /bunyi/ “the final sound of the trumpet” being in focus, I'm inclined to leave it as it.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ate"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-12 03:28:18Z" status="Anyone">= kedip</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:51-52" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Tesalonika 4:15-17</note><v n="53-54" />Te ngi'u aae èdhi dhu bisa ele iie ne'e ne, j'aj'i ngi'u hiu dhu ele iie heka! Aa èdhi dhu bisa madhe ne'e ne, neo ub'a j'aj'i raropa hiu dhu madhe heka! Èèna madhutu ngaa dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci, peka na,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) our bodies which now are able to decay, are going to change becoming a form/type/model which is not able to decay anymore! And we-inc who now are able to die, are going to change becoming a form/type/model which is not able to die anymore! The is according to what was written beforehand in the Holy Writings, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua palaho eele le koasa mamadhe,<bt>God2 has already destroyed the power of death,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa segi le mamadhe!<bt>and has already overcome/conquered death!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèti èèna ka èdhi madhe heka.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why we-inc are not going to die anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="15:54" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 25:8</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="55" />&lt;&lt;He, mamadhe!<bt>&lt;&lt;He, Death! [NOTE: Yes, we realise it's personification.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Koasa èu ètu mia?<bt>Where is your power/authority?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">He, mamadhe!<bt>He, Death!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhudhu èu ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Where is your bite/sting (e.g. wasp, snake, sunburn, ember) now?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="15:55" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Hosea 13:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="56" />Nga tao ka mamadhe nèti rasa pèd'a hia èdhi dhèu rai-haha? Lula èdhi ad'u-ue sasala. Tasamia ka sasala sèra dènge koasa? Lula Atora Ama Lamatua peka na, sasala èdhi, nuka sisu paredha Na!<bt>Why is it that death brings a feeling of pain to we-inc humans? Because we do wrong. Why is it that our wrongs have power? Because God's Law shows that our wrongs violate His commands!</bt><v n="57" />Te ngaa limuri ne, aa'i-aa'i se j'aj'i leko-leo le! De èdhi hud'i manèngi makasi ae-ae mi Ama Lamatua. Te Nèngu ka tao èdhi bisa segi bhabhelu-katub'a lula Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus. Mema tare'a, te Kristus ka dhu segi aa'i!<bt>But now, everything has become different! So (consequently) all of us give lots and lots of thanks to God. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who makes us able to overcome/conquer evil things, through/by means what of our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus. And Kristus is the one who really won/overcame/conquered all!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />De a'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Pa'èra d'ara! Baku roe! Sasab'a miu hia mi Ama Lamatua hud'i asa be'a, aa asa ae. Te miu me'a le, na, sab'a bia hia Lamatua èdhi èèna, iia d'ara boe.<bt>So (consequently) dear siblings! Persevere/endure strongly! Don't weaken! Your-pl work for God must get increasingly better, and increasingly more. Cuz (elaboration) you already know that your hard work (idiom: work throwing bones) for our Lord/Master is not pointless/useless/in vain.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pa'oru doi sèna ka soru-bara dhèu unu Lamatua<bt>People collect money to help (doublet) God2's people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Ne'e ne, ja'a suri hia miu lula-nèti doi dhu miu pakaboko hia dhèu unu Lamatua ètu Yerusalem. Ja'a peka le dènge dhèu parcaya ètu propensi Galati, j'ara tasamia rèngu hud'i pakaboko doi èèna. Miu hud'i tao sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>Now, I'm writing to you-pl about the money which you-pl collected for God2's people in Yerusalem. I have already told the believers in the province of Galatia, how they must collect that money. Now, you-pl must do accordingly as well. [EXEG / background-foreground: Jerusalem from v.3, see NLT also]</bt><note reference="16:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Roma 15:25-26</note><v n="2" />Ladhe hari Migu, dhèu aa'i-aa'i hud'i pa'oru doi ciki nèti rui-j'aj'èra rèngu. Baku mate ja'a dhiu ku, heka miu parai-oru kèna.<bt>Each sunday, everyone must/should store away a little money from the results of their work/efforts. Don't wait for me to come before you begin collecting money.</bt><v n="3" />De ladhe ja'a dhiu, miu paj'uj'u dhèu dhu miu lèka, sèna ka rèti doi soru-bara sèra asa dhèu unu Lamatua ètu Yerusalem. Pe ja'a suri sasuri ho patadha rèngu dènge kètu juma'at ètu nèi.<bt>Then, if/when I have come, you can designate your person/people whom you trust, to take/bring that financial assistance to God2's people in Yerusalem. Then2, I will write a letter to introduce them to the congregational leaders there (remote).</bt><v n="4" />Aa ladhe miu ngee, na, be'a ladhe ja'a madhutu hèi, na, ji'i la'a palere.<bt>And, if you think it would be better/best if I also go along, na, we-exc can go together.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus neo kako palème era<bt>Paulus makes plans to go around to many places</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ladhe ja'a kako palème le propensi Makedonia, ja'a heka dhiu asa miu kèna. De mo'o do mo'o boe, ja'a hud'i laku uuru ku asa Makedonia.<bt>If/when I have gone around/throughout the province of Makedonia, only then will I go to you there. So (consequently), no matter what, I still must go to Makedonia first.</bt><note reference="16:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 19:21</note><v n="6" />Èle èèna, pe ja'a dhiu pea taha dènge miu ako panèbhu ciki; ele boe d'ai èle hèru pacuhi. Hèia miu bisa lere ja'a asa era leo hari.<bt>After that, only then do I want to stay temporarily with you for awhile; maybe through the end of the cold season. After that2 then you can escort me to the next place.</bt><v n="7" />A'abhu ja'a, na, ja'a dhiu ne ca lod'o boe di. Te ja'a neo pea dènge miu ako panèbhu, ladhe Lamatua d'èi.<bt>My intention for coming to you is not just momentarily/short time. Cuz (elaboration) I want to stay with you for awhile, if God2's wants.</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa ja'a neo pea era ètu kota Epesus ne, toke lod'o babe'a Pantekosta, [nuka lèmi nguru lod'o èle kalela Paska].<bt>But I still want to stay here in the city of Efesus until the Pentakosta holiday/feast day, [that is 50 days after the Paska holiday]. [NOTE: explicated for a non-Jewish Corinthian audience, following HCE]</bt><note reference="16:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 23:15-21, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 16:9-11</note><v n="9" />Lula ètu ne'e ja'a abhu lod'o taleo ae, ho sab'a taruu, masi ka abhu dhèu ae dhu lab'a sasab'a Lamatua.<bt>Because here there are many opportunities for me to still do/accomplish much/keep working, even though there are also many people who oppose God2's work.</bt><note reference="16:8-9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 19:8-10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ladhe Timotius j'aj'i dhiu paraga dènge miu, sèmi mere ne dènge be'a, sèna ka baku na ngee rupa-rupa. Te nèngu ne dhèu sab'a nèti Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, sama sèmi ja'a ne kahèi.<bt>If/when it works out for Timotius to come to you, receive him well, so he doesn't need to think/worry/be anxious about (various) things. Cuz (elaboration) he is worker of our-inc Head Yesus Kristus, just like me.</bt><note reference="16:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 4:17</note><v n="11" />Mage soro tèke dhèu laladhe ne dènge hui madha di. Soru-bara ne toke na lèpa asa ja'a dènge be'a. Te ja'a dènge a'ari dhu leo se, dhu mate tatae ne.<bt>Don't let people despise him (idiom: look slant-eyed at him). Help (doublet) him, until he goes back (home) to me safely. Cuz (elaboration) I and other siblings here are waiting (eagerly) for him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ca j'ara era dhu miu hud'i me'a ku. Ja'a dhu pamako le angalai èdhi Apolos, ho na dhiu pangad'o dènge a'ari dhu leo. Te ngaa no'o mèka dhiu. De mi mate, pe na abhu lod'o taleo, heka na dhiu kèna.<bt>There is one more thing you must know. I have tried to coax/persuade/cajole our-inc sibling Apolos, so he would go look after/see the the needs of you and other siblings. But he isn't wanting to go yet at this time. So (consequently) be patient, later when he gets a better opportunity, only then will he go there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tao hari ku ca j'ara<bt>Do one more thing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Miu hud'i j'aga ngi'u miu paie-iie! Miu hud'i pa'èra-èra ho parcaya taruu Ama Lamatua! Mage madha'u! Pa'èra iisi!<bt>You must watch/guard yourselves carefully! You must persevere/ endure to keep believing in God2! Don't be afraid. Strengthen/Prepare yourselves!</bt><v n="14" />Sad'i miu sab'a ngaa èèna ka, pad'elo la sasue.<bt>Whatever you do, demonstrate/show your love.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />A'ari pasue aa'i-aa'i! Miu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu me'a, na, Stefanus dènge isi èmu na ka dhèu partama dhu parcaya Kristus ètu propensi Akaya nèi. Rèngu sab'a re'a boe j'èra, sèna ka ladhe-leru dhèu parcaya ètu nèi. De ja'a manèngi ho<bt>Dear siblings! You all know that older brother Stefanus and his household were the first people who believed in Kristus in the province of Akaya there (remote). They also worked hard (worked not knowing suffering) to serve (doublet) all the believers there (remote). So (consequently), I ask that</bt><note reference="16:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Korintus 1:16</note><v n="16" />miu nanene dhèu sèmi sèra. Nuka rèngu dhu sab'a bia ho sama-sama lalau-lalo'o dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>you-pl keep listening to/obeying people of that type. That is, those who work hard (lit: work heavy) together to serve the believers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />D'ara ja'a neo dhiu pa'asu-pareo dènge miu. D'ara ja'a karej'e titu kèna, lula mamai Stefanus, Fortunatus dènge Akaikus asa ne'e. Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu bisa gati miu.<bt>I yearn to see (doublet) you-pl. My insides are overjoyed, because of the coming of Stefanus, Fortunatus, and Akaikus to here. In that way, they replace/ substitute for you.</bt><v n="18" />Tèlu ra pa'èra d'ara ja'a, sama sèmi ra pa'èra d'ara miu kahèi. Miu hud'i pakab'ua dhèu sèmi sèra.<bt>They strengthen my insides (=encourage), in the same way(s) that they encourage you-pl too. You must respect/honour people of that sort/type.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus hia lii maho'o mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i<bt>Paulus passes on greetings to all</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Juma'at-juma'at ètu propensi Asia hia miu lii maho'o. Akila dènge dhèu èmu na, Priskila,<bt>The various congregations in the province of Asia pass on greetings to you-pl. Akila and his wife Priskila,</bt><note reference="16:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani ètu ne'e, suri peka na, &lt;&lt;Priska&gt;&gt;. Priska dènge Priskila èèna, nèti ngara èci.<bt>The Yunani language Bible here writes, saying, “Priska”. Priska and Priskila are from the same name.</bt></note>aa dhèu leo dhu tema pakaboko ètu èmu ra, pa'adhu lii maho'o kahèi. Rèngu se dhu pa'èki kahèi dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus.<bt>and all the other people who normally gather in their house also pass on greetings. They are also bound/linked with our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus. [NOTE on ftn: Priscilla is the diminutive form of Prisca.]</bt><note reference="16:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 18:2</note><v n="20" />Dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i ètu ne'e, pa'adhu lii maho'o kahèi.<bt>All the believers here also pass on their greetings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ladhe miu pakaboko, na, pa'uu èci dènge èci, pake uu dhu nia hia dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>If/when you are gathered together, na, mutually greet each other using a kiss that is appropriate for believers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Mi laladhe! Te ja'a, Paulus, suri dènge kacui-aai unu ku: <span class="Italic">Saloom!</span><bt>Have a look at this! Cuz (elaboration) I, Paulus here, am using my own hand to write this: <span class="Italic">Saloom!</span></bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Dhèu cee dhu sue boe Kètu èdhi, pe Ama Lamatua huku ne.<bt>Whoever has no love for our-inc Head, God will punish him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ja'a d'èi tabea dhèu madhutu lii Aram èdhi dhèu Yahudi, dhu peka, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Marana ta!&gt;&gt;</span> dhu sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua! Mai ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>I like to greet2 people, according to our Yahudi people's Aram language, saying, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Marana ta!&gt;&gt;</span> which means, &lt;&lt;Lord/Master! Come!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Is “Marana tha” to be taken positively “we really look forward to your coming, Lord”, or negatively “hurry up and come judge these accursed people, Lord (that I was just talking about)”. Commentators are divided (see Ex. Summ.). But note a) these verses have a string of relatively unrelated exortations, and b) elsewhere in the Biblical and extra-biblical literature the use of “Marana tha” is overwhelmingly positive. In this light, the paragraph break to set up communicating to RL audiences what “Marana tha” is appropriate.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabea "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2010-11-05 01:13:32Z" status="Anyone">greet; kasi hormat; tab'e = pegang tangan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>I ask that our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, show His good insides (goodness/grace/kindness/generosity) to you-pl all.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ja'a sue miu aa'i-aa'i mi, lula èdhi pa'èki dènge Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua hia mai.<bt>I love you all, because we-inc are together bound/linked with Kristus, whom God sent.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sasuri ja'a sèmi ne'e ka. Saloom!<bt>My letter is like that. Saloom!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti ja'a,<bt>From me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Paulus<bt>Paulus</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>